column4: SYMPTOM_TEXT
Developed fever 103+ and whole body rash.

THE PATIENT WAS FAINTING WITH HER EYES ROLLING BACK IN HER HEAD. WE AWOKE HER - MADE HER ALERT AND GAVE HER WATER AT FIRST. SHE THEN SAID SHE WANTED A SODA. SHE STARTED GOING OUT AGAIN, AND  GOT A SODA AND SHE DRANK THAT. SHE HAS HAD A HISTORY OF FAINTING AT SIGHT OF NEEDLES. SHE RESTED AND AFTER ABOUT 15 MINUTES LEFT THE STORE.
Bloody stool.

This spontaneous report was received from medical assistant concerning to a 4 year old patient of unknown gender. No information was provided regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications. On 30-NOV-2017, the patient was vaccinated with one improperly stored dose of VARIVAX from lot number reported as N201582 with expiration date 09-AUG-2019, or lot number N014632 with expiration date 11-MAY-2019, or lot number N019131 with expiration date 22-JUN-2019, or lot number N019839 with expiration date 13-JUL-2019, or lot number reported as N019397 with expiration date 07-JUN-2019, or lot number N021317 with expiration date 07-AUG-2019 (route of administration and anatomical location were not provided); for prophylaxis. The VARIVAX was reconstituted with properly stored sterile diluent (MERCK) (lot # and expiration date were unknown). There was no previous temperature excursion and the data logger was no involved. The vaccines were exposed to temperatures between 47 F (Fahrenheit) to 77 F (Fahrenheit) during 10 hours and 18 minutes. No adverse effects were reported. Lot number N201582 is an invalid lot number for varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck). Lot number N019397 is an invalid lot number for varicella virus vaccine live (oka/merck).

Urticarial facial rash on 12/11/17 at about 4 pm. Patient given BENADRYL, rash returned 4 hours later. Patient taken to ER given BENADRYL and Prednisolone. Rash. Last knew rash was 12/10/17 at 10 pm. Pt seen and examined in office, recommended ZYRTEC and continue Prednisolone for a total of 5 days.
Numbness and parasthesia to left hand and forearm for less than 3 days.
Dime sized red area on L thigh at site of imm. firm to touch not painful. Afebrile.

Received vaccines on 12/14/17. The case had 2 bowel movements on 12/15/17 and then did not have a bowel movement  for the next  6 days. Mother reports that the baby is breast fed and normally has 4-5 stools per day. The baby became distended and cried when abdomen was touched. Mother did not report any vomiting. The baby resumed  having bowel movements on 12/22/17.The baby did not receive any special treatment for the decrease in stool. Mother did not note blood in the stool after he resumed having bowel movements. Symptoms disappeared.

4 days following the vaccine patient had developed headache, abdominal pain, knee and ankle pain without swelling, lightheadedness, fatigue and blurred vision which lasted several since. Since, the patient has had same sx every 2-4 weeks. Also hair seems more brittle and curly. Once with ~ 2hours of hives. No other rashes.
C/O left upper arm swelling, itching, painful, red, at injection site given on 12/20/2017 increased swelling today.

Pruritic rash developed 30 min after vaccination, scattered macular rash on neck, trunk, and back area. 5mls of BENADRYL given to patient at the office. Itchiness and rash improved in 15min. Patient and mother left office without anaphylactic reactions. Mother was advised to bring patient back to the office if symptom worsened.

Patient had a pre-syncopal event following the event. He felt pale and nauseous; dizzy. Did not pass out. 3-4 days later developed a very dry rash on cheeks of face bilaterally. I do not think the rash is related to the immunization. No hives.

Patient tolerated flu injection well, she was talkative with mom and was able to out of the room unassisted. Mom had to stop at our front desk for future scheduling, a that time patient was found to be sitting in the waiting room chair, slumped back and pale. Nursing staff was readily available to assist patient and mother (patient was still in chair and did not fall nor slip off), a doctor was called out to the waiting room help to assess the patient as well. Pt was instructed to lean forward, take deep breaths, and a cool compress was applied to the nape of her neck. Her BP was checked. Orange juice was provided to the patient as well. Patient felt well enough to walk back to the office room where she was monitored and re-assessed by her doctor. Her BP and pulse was continuously monitored, OJ was provided to drink, and a cool compress was also applied to her forehead. Patient stayed with mother in office room for several minutes. Prior to discharge, pt's doctor re-assessed patient and discharged her. The office placed a follow up call with mother the net day, she was very appreciative of the call. Patient was doing well the following day with no adverse symptoms reported. Mom explained that she forgot too mention to staff that patient had fainted when she was 11 years old after receiving the flu vaccine. This has been noted in the chart for future reference of staff and provider.
Adverse Event: Severe swelling of skin, hives, redness, severe itching. Treatment: Topical Steroids, Wet wraps, salt baths, bleach baths.
Redness at site of injection.
Had fever up to 104, widespread scattered  rash-no treatment.
Onset of generalized weakness/ whole body went limp/ febrile/ change of overall color with pallor and stopped breathing/ was given CPR and paramedics were called/ baby was then brought to ER.
Redness and swelling at site. No systemic issues.

This spontaneous report has been received from and refers to a 4 months patient of unknown gender. No information was provided regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions, drug reactions, allergies or concomitant medications. On 30-NOV-2017, the patient was vaccinated with an improper stored dose of ROTATEQ orally for prophylaxis, lot number N003984, expiration date 19-NOV-2018 or lot number M044397, expiration date 20-JUN-2018 (the specific lot number and dose administered were unknown by the reporter). The temperature excursion was above 32 degrees Fahrenheit (°F) up to 35.4 °F for a time frame of 45 minutes, without previous temperature excursion and was called because of a digital data logger. There was not product quality complain or adverse effect involved.

? febrile seizure vs BRUE in afternoon after event. Was unresponsive approx 30s not breathing required layperson CPR. EMS was called and transported child and stayed in ER several hours for observation. Child was d/c that evening.

This spontaneous report was received from an administrator referring to a 10 week-old patient of unknown gender. The patient's relevant medical history, drug reactions/allergies and concomitant medication were not reported. On 28-NOV-2017, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of ROTATEQ lot number: N003984 (expiration date: 19-NOV-2018) or lot number: M044397 (expiration date: 20-JUN-2018), orally, for prophylaxis (strength and dosage schedule were not provided). The specific lot number of ROTATEQ administered to the patient was unknown by the reporter. There was digital data logger involved. The storage characteristics were the following: Temperature: at or above 32 F up to 35 F (35.4F) for 45 minutes. - Previous temperature excursion: No No adverse effects were reported.
Patient was given the 0.5mL instead of the 0.25mL FLUZONE. CDC informed me there is no reaction to the patient.

This spontaneous report was received from an office manager referring to a 4 month old patient of unknown gender. The patient's pertinent medical history, concurrent conditions, drug reactions/allergies and concomitant medications were not provided. On 30-NOV-2017, the patient was administered a dose of improperly stored ROTATEQ lot # M044397, expired on 20-JUN-2018 or lot # N003984, expired on 19-NOV-2018 (the specific lot number administered was unknown by reporter), orally, for prophylaxis (strength was not reported). The vaccine was stored at or above a temperature of 32°F up to 35°F (35.4°F) for 45 minutes. No previous temperature excursions neither adverse effects were reported. The call was because of a data logger.

Per mom once patient was home the area were she received Dtap on thigh had red raised area the size of a golf ball, with even larger redness around that, it lasted several days before clearing up. Per patients mother this is the 3rd reaction for Dtap containing vaccine, each time the reaction gets larger and larger.

This spontaneous report was received from an office manager referring to an 11 year old patient of unknown gender. No information was provided regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications. On 02-NOV-2017, the patient was vaccinated with an adult dose of VAQTA lot number M039055 and expiration date of 22-JUL-2018 for prophylaxis (dose and route of administration were not reported). No adverse effects were reported.

Pt received 2nd HPV-did not eat breakfast prior but was given OJ in office prior. No previous reactions. Pt became Pale and vomited-mild dizziness -pt given sucker and cool pack on head-laid down and monitored x 30 min-Pt color returned, alert and left with mom. Will F/U on Pt tomorrow.
Hives on face and arms, mild eyelid swelling. Some itching. BENADRYL given.
Pt was given ZOSTAVAX when they should have received a Varicella.

After Flu vaccine was given @9:56am, pt presented with swelling @ injection site. Pt. was AOx3. BENADRYL 20ml given as ordered by mouth. Pt stable and was being closely monitored by (RN, MA) for  any s/s of allergic reaction to vaccine. At  10:17am pt. c/o wheezing, dizziness, and itchiness. MD  notified and pt. was assessed by MD. Emergency 911 was called @10:20am by MA. Pt. AOx3 at this time, but also began to show signs of swelling of the mouth. Prednisone 15ml given as ordered by mouth, EPIPEN 0.15mg given as ordered IM in Left thigh, and breathing treatment started via nebulizer using Albuterol Sulfate 2.5mg as ordered by MD. Vitals taken @ 10:30am: T: 98.0; BP: 119/76; P: 86. Rescue arrived @ 10:30am. Pt. was AOx3 with no s/s of allergic reaction. Pt transported to Hospital via stretcher for further evaluation; accompanied by mother.

STROKE. Patient presented with left hemiplegia and facial droop with MRI/MRA for large acute/subacute right MCA infarct. He was afebrile, normotensive, without any electrolyte derangement. He had recurrent seizure activities on 11/23 and 11/24, for which he received Keppra and fosphenytoin. He was weaned of the fosphenytoin on 11/28 and continues on Keppra. Left hospital for inpatient rehabilitation for 2 weeks. After, at home with outpatient physical and occupational therapy 3x week.
He was talking, walking and acting normal and progressing, and after the shots he couldn't walk or speak at all....
On of diarrhea, emesis, decrease appetite to all foods and liquids about 6 hours after the vaccines. No rashes, no new wheezing and no blood in stool. No seizures.

About 10 min after the shot Patient developed hives and complained about throat pain. BENADRYL given, vomited some and half given back. Hives got slightly better but he still got throat pain. EPI PEN Jr given. Hives disappeared in 5 min and throat pain is gone. Watched Patient for another 30 min and D/C home in stable condition. In the future, all flu shots in allergy clinic.
Pt developed scattered urticaria and itching. No oral involvement or respiratory difficulty. Resolved within 24 hrs with 2 doses of BENADRYL.

Erythema on left upper arm, temp 100.4 by ear thermometer, mild warmth, pruritic, edema, induration, mild tenderness was on 1/4/18. Erythema improving per mother on 1/5/18 with continued mild warmth, induration, mild edema, no tenderness, continued pruritic. Mother gave TYLENOL and applied hydrocortisone cream.  Recommended may also apply ice, BENEDRYL as needed.
12/19/17 site was swollen, lump, painless and itchy. (right arm) -size: slightly larger than a quarter.

Patient developed urticaria on trunk and extremities within 1.5 hours of receiving the vaccine. Patient went to ER on 1/3/18 and was diagnosed with allergic reaction, prescribed prednisolone. Patient never took the medication prescribed. Patient was seen in my office by me on 1/4/2018 and did have mild urticaria on exam, BENADRYL was prescribed.

This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant and refers to a 9 week old patient of unknown gender. No information about the patient's medical history and concurrent conditions was provided. On 26-OCT-2017, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of ROTATEQ (lot # M044397 with an expiration date in 20-JUN-2018), for prophylaxis, reconstituted with properly stored sterile diluent (manufacturer unknown), that underwent a temperature excursion from 9 degrees Celsius to 25 degrees Celsius during 20 minutes. There was no previous temperature excursion. Digital data logger was involved. No adverse effects were reported and no product quality complaint (PQC) was involved. This is one of several reports from the same reporter. Right deltoid cellulitis.
Local hive adjacent to vaccine injection site on left leg.

Congestion and cough with vomiting, rapid breathing that has lasted for 11 weeks (so far). Multiple trips to the doctor and ER in November and December. Have tried albuterol breathing treatments, prednisone, amoxicillin. Have had two chest Xrays and an EEG (after a strange episode of lethargy in December). Went to an ENT on December 26, who is guessing silent reflux may be a culprit (baby doesn't spit up). Currently on a daily dose of ZANTAC 2x a day (4mL). Symptoms persist. If no improvement by follow up appointment at the end of January, ENT will refer us to hospital.
Fever at 2:00am 101.7 (01/04/2018); Vomiting 6 times 1:00noon (01/05/2018); Drowsy napped 6 times (01/05/2018).
Fever, cough, spots all over the body.

Complaints of general back and joint pain within 2 weeks of vaccination. Approximately 4 weeks after vaccination, complaints of severe tiredness, some weakness, and intermittent vomiting (on 24- to 61-hour periodicity). Approximately 5 weeks after vaccination, hospitalized with loss of coordination; inability to walk without assistance (falling); severe jaw, joint, and back pain. CT of head, chest X-ray, blood analyses, lumbar puncture, MRI of brain and spine; diagnosed with Guillain-Barre' Syndrome.  Immediately initiated plasmapheresis (5 treatments), followed by intravenous immunoglobulin treatment (5 treatments beginning after 3rd plasmapheresis treatment). Outcome pending; complete recovery not yet realized. GBS recovery expected to be prolonged; residual paralysis remains; permanent/permanence of damage unknown at this time.

Extremely lethargic / sleepy for the following 24 hours, some mild upper respiratory signs, high pitched crying the night of December 9th. Fever >102 F December 9th. She was seen by her pediatrician and the ER both said completely opposite things: her Dr said she had bronchiolitis and redness in her ears, the ER doctors said they saw neither. She was not treated for anything. She continues to have difficulty sleeping overnight (as opposed to sleeping for long stretches and putting herself to bed before December 8th) and now will cry for hours before falling asleep which she has never done, not even as a newborn. She has never been colicky or sick before. During her vaccines at 2 months she developed hard swellings that lasted right up until a week prior to her next vaccines December 8th.

This spontaneous report was received from a patient's father via a company representative (also the father's friend) and refers to a 18-year-old female patient. The patient's medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant therapies were not reported. Since approximately 2014 (reported as "3-4 years ago"), the patient was vaccinated with 3 doses in series of GARDASIL, 0.5 ml (route of administration, lot# and expiration date were not reported) to prevent HPV related cancers. In January 2017 (reported as "1 year ago"), the patient was diagnosed with ulcerative colitis. The patient sought for an unspecified medical attention. All diagnostic tests needed to be done for ulcerative colitis were performed in January 2017. At the time of this report, the patient was being treated with HUMIRA.The outcome of the event was unknown. The relatedness between the event and GARDASIL was not reported. Upon internal review, the event of ulcerative colitis was considered to be medically significant.
Patient received the high dose flu vaccine instead of pediatric 6-36 mos.
Patient received high dose flu instead of pediatric 6-36 mos.

Pt's mother called at 4:30pm on 1/3/18, had received these 3 vaccinations at her visit about 3 hours prior. Pt was experiencing 7/10 abdominal pain, had 1 episode of emesis and denied nausea after that first episode. Pt began her period that day but had never experienced abdominal pain like this with previous periods.
Red, swollen injection sites both legs warm to the touch.
2.5 x 4 cm Red, raised area. Warm to touch. Area developed immediately after giving vaccine.

Patient had a very bad seizure. It lasted about 15 min and she ended up in ER on 10/15/2013 with the seizure. A day or two prior to it patient had her throat swollen. We called dr and she said we could seek medical assistance.

Child went down for nap day of event. Child had been acting and feeling fine all week and all day leading up to event. Child woke up from nap with fever of 104, 2 minutes after waking, child experiences an 8 minute febrile seizure.

4 hours after the vaccines, patient started screaming crying - a cry I've never heard before. It was piercing and she was inconsolable for over two hours. Until she finally fell asleep from crying so hard. She's never carried like that and has yet to cry like that again. All clear signs of encephalitis.
PATIENT WAS INADVERTENTLY GIVEN INTRADERMAL FLU VACCINE AND IT IS ONLY APPROVED FOR USE IN ADULTS AGED 18 THROUGH 64 YEARS OLD. PATIENT IS 14 YEARS OLD.

One hour after administration of vaccine, patient had a massive bloody stool. He was directed to the ER where he was found to have intussusception that was reduced with air contrast enema. He was kept overnight for observation and released the next day without complication.
Localized reaction - swelling, hot, hard, tender to touch.

Patient received 3 vaccinations. She had a fever for three days. The first night home she was very cranky. I was changing her diaper and she appeared to maybe have a seizure. It lasted for about 15 seconds, maybe less. My mom and I, didn't know what to do. Patient calmed down and we gave her some more TYLENOL according to instructions. Patient was very colicky for each evening and it was difficult to soothe her and to calm her down. Easter Sunday Evening and she was cranky but not as bad as days since April 3, 2007. Patient was cranky every night up thru April 8, 2007.
Patient presented with redness and swelling at the injection site.
Per mother, Patient had a "seizure" because of vaccinations. ER Physician did not agree with that assessment.
Mother noticed redness right thigh next day...DTaP and MMR placed right thigh, diphenhydramine 12.5/5ml 2.5 ml TID PRN itching. KEFLEX 250mg/5ml 5ml QID x 7 days.
The patient experienced syncope and some twitching. The episode lasted about 10 seconds or less. The patient looked pale initially.
Patient developed pain at site in right upper arm, associated with redness. Redness lasted approximately 2 days, pain persisted approximately 14 d.

Approximately 1.5 cm induration on lateral Lt arm. "Child appears to have had a reaction to recent immunization. Though it has been a month since her last immunizations which included Dtap, meningococcal, flu and HPV. She has continued to have a "lump" in her LT arm. There was initial erythema, but this has resolved and the child is not having pain at the injection site". Taken from office note 1/4/18.

Initial unsolicited report received from a pharmacist (patient's mother) on 03-Nov-2017. This case involves a 10-month-old male patient who was vaccinated with a 0.5 ml first single dose of FLUZONE QIV (batch number, expiration date, site of administration were not reported) intramuscularly on 31-Oct-2017. Patient's medical history was not reported. Concomitant medications were not reported. It was also reported that he had not received any other vaccines. On 01-Nov-2017, one day following the vaccination, the patient was irritable. On 02-Nov-2017, two days after the vaccination, he experienced an elevated temperature to 102.8 degree Fahrenheit and broke out in a rash. It was also a case of actual medication error due to overdose Other laboratory investigations was not reported. The patient did not receive any corrective treatment at this time. The outcome of the events was reported as not recovered. Follow-up information received from a pharmacist (patient's mother) in the United States on 28-Dec-2017. This patient was vaccinated with a 0.25 ml first single dose of FLUZONE QIV (Batch number: UT5897JA) intramuscularly in left thigh on 31-Oct-2017. The patient's immunization history included first, second and third doses of PEDIARIX on 17-Feb-2017, 19-Apr-2017 and 20-Jun-2017 respectively. First dose of VAQTA on 20-Dec-2017, first dose of HEPATITIS B VACCINE on 15-Dec-2016, first and second dose of PEDVAXHIB on 17-Feb-2017 and 19-Apr-2017, first and second dose of  FLUZONE IIV4 P-FREE on 31-OCT-2017 and 06-DEC-2017, first dose of MMR II on 20-DEC-2017, first, second, third and fourth doses of PREVENAR 13 on 17-Feb-2017, 19-Apr-2017, 20-Jun-2017 and on 20-Dec-2017 respectively and first and second dose of ROTATEQ on 17-FEB-2017 and 19-APR-2017. The event of medication error (overdose) was removed as the patient received correct dose of flu vaccine. On 03 Nov 2017, one day post following vaccination, mother called office reported fever and rash on arms. He also had runny nose due to possible viral illness. No distress noted. It was unsure if the patient was seen by medical staff. Mom was advised if he worsened she may give DIPHENHYDRAMINE HYDROCHLORIDE (Benadryl). Patient was in care of grandparent at the time. The patient was recovered from the events. He received a second dose of Fluzone 0.25 mL on 06-Dec-2017 without any incident. List of documents held by sender: none.
Mother called to report swelling/redness in right thigh 1" across, no fever or pain at injection site, no heat, no streaking redness. Developed fever on 1/6/18 of 103.3, responded to Tylenol.
Raised splotchy red rash all over body which started about 2.5 weeks after MMR injection given. No difficulty breathing or other sx.

On 6/30/17, the day after receiving the vaccines; my baby developed extremely blood shot eyes. The whites of her eyes were red and swollen. She randomly would have a fever for the following week after injections. Also had moments where she was completely inconsolable. Screaming and crying not eating well and barely napping but also lethargic and not acting herself. Exactly 7 days after injections on 7/06/17 she woke up with a rash all over her face and neck. We took her to the Peds office and her Pediatrician was out of the office so we saw a different doctor, and she said it was likely a reaction to the MMR vaccine she had the previous week. Keep an eye on her and as long as she didn't get a high fever she would be fine. I believe it took about 3 days for the rash to go away and never spread past her neck.

Left thigh became swollen and painful from groin to mid-calf. Left knee became very swollen and painful - child unable to flex knee. Child became febrile about 36 hrs after vaccines given. Left knee was aspirated and child went to OR for knee irrigation. All joint fluid cultures were negative for bacteria, fungal CX pdg. Child had 48 hrs of IV ceftriaxone and clindamycin. Child seen 1/3/18 for F/U exam. She is improving but still has pain in Left knee and swelling of knee joint. She is able to walk with help of her parents or a walker.

This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of blurred vision in a 12-year-old female patient who received BOOSTRIX. On 14th August 2017, the patient received BOOSTRIX .5 ml. On 15th September 2017, 32 days after receiving BOOSTRIX, the patient experienced blurred vision (serious criteria disability), myopia (serious criteria disability), creatine phosphokinase increased (serious criteria disability) and feeling unwell. On 16th September 2017, the patient experienced walking difficulty (serious criteria disability), increased reflexes (serious criteria disability), myalgia of lower extremities (serious criteria disability), lower extremities weakness of (serious criteria disability), dizziness (serious criteria disability) and unable to walk. On an unknown date, the patient experienced paresthesia (serious criteria disability) and numbness (serious criteria disability). The patient was treated with Ear Drops {NOS} and TYLENOL. On an unknown date, the outcome of the blurred vision, walking difficulty, increased reflexes, paresthesia, numbness, myalgia of lower extremities, lower extremities weakness of, dizziness and unable to walk were not recovered/not resolved and the outcome of the myopia was unchanged and the outcome of the creatine phosphokinase increased and feeling unwell were unknown. The reporter considered the blurred vision, walking difficulty, increased reflexes, myopia, creatine phosphokinase increased, paresthesia, numbness, myalgia of lower extremities, lower extremities weakness of and dizziness to be possibly related to BOOSTRIX. It was unknown if the reporter considered the unable to walk and feeling unwell to be related to BOOSTRIX. Additional details were reported as follows: The physician was a pediatrician who did not work at the location where the vaccine was administered to the patient, who said that the nurse practitioner was responsible for the vaccine's administration at the clinic where the vaccine was administered. The patient's concomitant medication included ear drops starting from 14th August 2017. The reporter described that the patient's vision changed as being blurred vision but that was a subjective symptom because the pediatric eye examination was normal. On 15th September 2017, 32 days after vaccination, the patient was not feeling well, blood creatine phosphokinase increased and had myopia. The leg muscle pain was described as occurring in both legs with leg weakness in both legs. The difficulty in ambulating was described as the patient being unable to walk for more than a few steps. The dizziness occurred in the evening on the same day as the leg muscle pain with weakness and ambulation difficulty, which had occurred in the morning. On 16th September 2017, 33 days after vaccination, the patient experienced ambulation difficulty, mildly brisk reflexes, leg muscle pain and weakness, dizziness and unable to walk. On 16th September 2017 and 12th October 2017, the patient went to the emergency room because of the symptoms but was not admitted. The medical workup for this patient now included an ophthalmologist visit in which she was diagnosed with myopia and nothing else. The recent Blood creatine phosphokinase test results were pending. The patient recently started having numbness, tingling, and paresthesias which had been waxing and waning day to day. Less than a year after vaccination the patient experienced paresthesias, tingling, and numbness. On 13th October 2017, the patient was seen by a neurologist and the exam results were inconclusive, excepting diagnosis of mildly brisk reflex. On 13th October 2017, the patient had a normal cardiology workup. The patient had a pending Electroencephalography. The patient's parents were distraught and the reporter said these symptoms had been disabling that she had not been able to go back to school and was still unable to walk on her own most of the time. All of the symptoms were still waxing and waning from day to day. The reporter said the myopia could just be a baseline physical finding and was unsure if it was related to all of the other symptoms. The reporter gave permission to be contacted by GCSP. The reporter had no specific dosing details for the vaccine beyond what was documented already above.
2 Hep B shots at same time!! No reaction yet - should not had gotten 2 hep b shots at one time.

This spontaneous case, initially received on 30-Mar-2017 was reported by an other non-health professional (consumer) and concerns about 11 Years old male patient. Administration of Company suspect drug: FLUVIRIN was administered for Influenza immunization on 04-Oct-2016 (Dose: 0.5ml, via intramuscular route of administration, solution dosage form where frequency was one single dose and batch number was not reported). Patient was previously immunized with a first dose of flu vaccine. Adverse reactions/events and outcomes: On 04-Oct-2016, the patient received FLUVIRIN at pharmacy. On 11-Mar-2017 the patient also experienced fever and cough. He was diagnosed with influenza on an unspecified date in Mar 2017. At the time of vaccination the patient was healthy and had no medical history. Nasal swab confirmed influenza. The patient was treated with TAMIFLU. On 13-Mar-2017, the events were reported as recovered / resolved. Reporter's Assessment: The reporter assessed the causality as related. Follow up received on 24-Apr-2017: Patient's immunological status, prior vaccination details, information regarding medical history and lab test were updated. Follow up received on 09-May-2017: Since the batch number was not reported, a batch specific review could not be performed. Based on the Annual Product Review (APR) of FLUVIRIN vaccine, it was concluded that FLUVIRIN manufacturing process was operated at a good level of overall control and the supporting systems are effective in supporting the compliant production, testing and supply processes for FLUVIRIN vaccine. From this conclusion there was no reason or explanation to account for the reported adverse event.

This initial spontaneous case, received on 02-Nov-2017, reported by other non-health professional and concerns a 12-year-old female patient of weight: 48.3 kg, height: 148 cm. The patient's historical condition included stomach pain throughout the years. The patient's concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date, the patient received Influenza vaccine (dose, route, anatomical location, trade name and manufacturer was not reported). On 20-Oct-2017, the patient was also received ILARIS (300 mg, subcutaneous, once a (as reported)) for TRAPS (tumor necrosis factor receptor associated periodic syndrome). On an unspecified date, after receiving INN flu vaccine seasonal (reported as two and half weeks ago) and ILARIS injection on 20-Oct-2017, the patient had bad injection site reactions. She used topical BENADRYL but it had no effect, hence it was replaced with oral BENADRYL which helped, but one of the reaction sites returned about in 10 days. On 29-Oct-2017, as soon as BENADRYL was stopped, since then she had bad stomach pain, was tired, appetite lost and was not going to school. It was also reported that, the site reaction that returned was  noticeable, burned and itched, but not as large as it originally was. The patient was not eating and sleeping all the time. She had an intense feet pain (pain level: 5.5). It was reported that, the patient had reoccurring stomach pain throughout the years, she was on ILARIS but not to the intensity that it  did not go away like it was then. She also felt like she was being punched in the stomach. The reporter also reported that, ILARIS reduced length of flare and blood work looked good a month ago, for the first time and had normal sedimentation rate. The outcome of the event injection site reaction was recovering and for events stomach pain, loss of appetite, tiredness and intense foot pain was not recovered (ongoing). The outcome of the other events was not reported.

11-year-old female who was admitted to medical center on 1/2/18 with a sudden onset of weakness of the lower extremities. The father states that she was in her usual state of health until the morning of 1/1 at which time she complained to her father that her legs and shoulders were hurting when she was walking to the bathroom. She stated that she felt weak and was unable to walk to the bathroom without help. The father states that the rest of the day she was unable to ambulate without help because of the weakness. There was no history of pre-existing symptoms such as URI symptoms, cough, congestion, vomiting or diarrhea. No one else was sick at home either. The weakness and pain worsened so she was brought to the emergency room. There was no history of numbness or tingling associated with this. She did come from another country approximately 1-1/2 years ago and has not returned. There were no known sick contacts. She was admitted to the pediatric ICU for further management. Neurology consult was obtained who recommended an LP in addition to blood work and MRI of the head and spine. The MRIs were unremarkable as was the blood work. She was started on IVIG. They did send a respiratory virus panel which was negative. I was consulted today because she now has a fever associated with this weakness. Overnight her condition worsened requiring intubation and mechanical ventilation. There is no family history of similar type symptoms in anyone in the family. The father states that she is normally a healthy 11-year-old female attending 4th grade. Her vaccines are up-to-date according to the father. She is currently intubated and sedated. She was started on IV ceftriaxone because of fever.

After receiving the vaccines, he was fussy, and since has stopped sleeping normally, and has had more fevers and rashes and lack of eye contact. He stopped trying to roll over or move on his own for about a month post vaccination. This is a huge concern as he was hitting milestones wonderfully prior. We did not seek immediate help. We decided to wait and decided to see if he would feel better after a few days. Then he was so sick. Seemingly with one cold virus after another, and then with a horrible cough and ear infection, which we saught treatment for at Health Center in December, No injury report was filed. I felt like no one would listen to my concern. I'm not anti vaccines. I am just concerned about my baby. With so many cases of aubism and other disorders in our genes, I am worried that I we may be too sensitive for these shots. I really would like someone to respond via Email or telephone. Thank you for your time.

Initial unsolicited report received from a nurse on 10-Jan-2018. This case involves a six-month-old patient (gender not reported), who was vaccinated with first dose of 0.25 ml FLUZONE QIV via intramuscular route (batch number: UT5949KA; expiry date, route and site of administration not reported) and PEDIARIX (manufacturer: GSK) (batch number, expiry date, dose, route and site of administration not reported) and ROTAVIRUS VACCINE (batch number, expiry date, dose, route and site of administration not reported) and PNEUMOCOCCAL CONJUGATE VACCINE (PCV12) (manufacturer: Pfizer) (batch number, expiry date, dose, route and site of administration not reported) on 20-Dec-2017. Patient had a mild cough at time of vaccination. No fever. Concomitant medications were not reported. On 26-Dec-2017 in morning, six days following the vaccination, patient was found dead. Patient was previously vaccinated with all vaccines other than FLUZONE QIV twice. Lab test and corrective treatment was not reported. Reporter stated an autopsy was being performed to determine cause of death and rule out SIDS (sudden infant death syndrome). Patient's mother felt it was the flu shot (Fluzone QIV) that caused her child's demise. Documents held by sender: none.; Sender's Comments: Time to onset is compatible. The patient already had mild cough at the time of vaccination. No other medical history was reported. The patient also received Pediarix and Rotavirus vaccine on the same day as Fluzone QIV. Autopsy was being performed at the time of reporting to determine the cause of death and rule out SIDS. Considering that several different vaccines had been co-administered at the same time it is difficult to elicit role of each vaccine in reported event. Result of autopsy, patient medical history, past surgical history, and state of health at the time of vaccination would be helpful with identifying role of each vaccine in reported event.; Reported Cause(s) of Death: found dead the morning; Autopsy-determined Cause(s) of Death: found dead the morning

60 minutes after oral ROTATEQ vaccine patient returned to clinic with 1 cm oval blisters on upper and lower lips on right of midline. No intra oral lesions. He had not been sucking on anything (like a popsicle) and had no other exposures.
O.5 ml Influenza Quad vaccine given to a 6 month old. Discovered during chart immunization audit. No adverse effects noted.
Flu vaccine 0.5 ml given to 20 month old. Discovered during vaccine audit. State Epidemiologist notified. No ill effects.

Quickly after got shot, called into room because mom said she wasn't feeling good. Nose was purple, hands got red and swollen, face pale and lips pale and just kept saying when asked "don't feel right". Pulse ox okay, no stridor, wheezing on exam. Talking without difficulty. Given BENADRYL po. Did give DECADRON once IM in office.

The patient went home after her well child exam and several hours later she developed a welt where her injection was given and a rash that extended up her arm and back. Mom was advised to give BENADRYL according to age and weight and apply ice to her injection site. I called the patient back 2 hours after her initial call and the mom stated the rash had resolved.

This spontaneous report as received from a nurse prescriber via a company representative and refers to an 1-year-old male patient. No information regarding the patient's pertinent medical history, concomitant medications, drug reactions or allergies was provided. On an unknown date in the middle of December 2017, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of M-M-R II subcutaneously (dose, frequency, lot# and expiration date were note reported) for Vaccination against measles, mumps and rubella. On an unknown date, after the M-M-R II administration, the patient experienced a fever, fatigue and a poor appetite. It could not be confirmed when the fever, fatigue and poor appetite resolved. On an unknown date, 10 days after the M-M-R II administration, the patient experienced a suspicious rash. The rash started at the patient's head and neck and progressed to the trunk. There was "no peeling" associated with the rash. The rash disappeared within 24 hours. The patient did not seek medical attention. At the time of this report, the patient was totally fine, healthy with no concerns. The relatedness between the fever, fatigue, poor appetite and rash and M-M-R II was not reported.

This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other healthcare professional calling on behalf of a physician. An 8 month-old male patient of an unspecified ethnicity received PREVNAR 13 at single dose via an unspecified route of administration on an unspecified day in Dec2017 (3 or 4 weeks before this report) for immunisation. The patient medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient experienced wheezing on an unspecified date in Dec2017 (3 or 4 weeks before this report). In response to the event Albuterol nebulizer treatment was given. Outcome was unknown.

Baby had all of his 8-week shots administered. He developed a nodule on the left upper thigh that has remained for over a year. The doctor was unwilling to give us the vaccine information and said any injection can cause a long-standing skin nodule.
None - Advised to report so that it could be documented.

Presented 12-29-17 wth 2 days of generalized petechial rash, nosebleeds X2. Labs 12-30-17 WBC 2.1, Pltt 30 ER 1-1-18 with bruising and hematuria, Admitted to medical Center. Dx  ITP. Given IVIG X2 , prednisone @ 70 mg. Discharged several days later on prednisone with ongoing FU with hematology.
Patient began developing rash to face and arms.

Began to scream, became unresponsive, opened eyes, then limp. Seemed to stop breathing, became very pale. EMS transferred home to ED -> hospital. Occurred Dec 11, 2017. Apnea and hypotension. Dec 26, 2017 similar episode but did not stop breathing. Jan 1, 2018 eye squinting episode, eyes rolled back.

This spontaneous report was received from a license practical nurse referring to currently 8 months old patient of unknown gender. The patient had no medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications. On 12-JUL-2017, when the patient was 2 months old received the first dose of oral, ROTATEQ for prophylaxis lot N003970 and expiration date of 13-OCT-2018 (route of administration was not reported). On 14-SEP-2017, when the patient was 4 months old received the second dose of oral, ROTATEQ for prophylaxis lot N003970 and expiration date of 11-NOV-2018 (route of administration was not reported). On an unspecified date in 2017, (also reported as "on an unspecified date on or after 14-SEP-2017"), the patient developed respiratory syncytial virus infection (RSV). Furthermore, the patient sought medical attention and received treatment to the aforementioned event. The outcome of respiratory syncytial virus infection was unknown. Additionally, the reporter did not provide causality assessment between the event and therapy with ROTATEQ. Lot number N003970 is an invalid lot number for Rotavirus Vaccine, Live, Oral, Pentavalent.
Red round spot at injection site, warm to touch, no pain, slight itch.
Had seizure-like activity (had rhythmic tremors and eyes rolled to back of head) lasting about 3 seconds (according to mother).
Rash: x 2 days, arms, head and neck. Rash is itchy. He had low grade fever and has been fussy for about 3-4 days.

PATIENT AND MOTHER REPORTED FAINTING EPISODE WITH PREVIOUS HEPATITIS B SCHEDULE. NEITHER REPORTED ISSUES WITH PREVIOUS FLU SHOTS. THE FLU SHOT WAS ADMINISTERED AT 5:30 PM AND LESS THAN 30 SECONDS AFTER PATIENT FAINTED IN HER SEAT BUT I WAS ABLE TO CATCH HER HEAD FROM HITTING ANYTHING. I LAID HER DOWN ON THE GROUND AND SHE REGAINED CONSCIOUSNESS. HER MOTHER AND I BOTH MONITORED HER FOR 15 MINUTES UNTIL THE MOM DROVE HER HOME.

That night she developed fever, chills, and sweats. The next evening she said her arm itches and she had a 4 1/2 by 2 3/4 bright red, hard and hot spot at flu injection site. The next morning it was over 5 1/2 inches by 3 1/2 inchs and even redder. She saw doctor the 1/19.
Fever the night of the vaccination, diarrhea x1, vomiting x1 the morning following vaccination.
21 X 25 CM swelling on L arm localized. warm to touch. No pus, no problems with breathing.

PATIENT'S MOTHER CALLED MORNING OF THE 2OTH TO SAY HER DAUGHTER BECAME ILL AFTER RECEIVING THE VACCINATION ON THE 19TH. SHE REPORTED A FEVER, CHILLS, BODY ACHES, AND SORE THROAT. MOTHER WAS GOING TO TREAT PATIENT WITH TYLENOL; PHARMACIST SUGGESTED VISITING AN URGENT CARE CLINIC TO RULE OUT AN ACTIVE INFLUENZA INFECTION BUT TO DATE THEY HAVE NOT SOUGHT ADDITIONAL MEDICAL TREAMENT.

Patient was fine up until leaving the building at which time he became light headed and then blacked out, falling to elbows and then hit head to floor. He came to immediately and was walked back to the pharmacy with his family. He lied down with feet elevated x20 minutes, was given some water, and continued to be confused with what happened within the last hour or so. Repeated the same question of "what happened" even after being told just a minute ago. Paramedics came and BP and pulse were normal and head seemed otherwise unharmed. He was then taken the hospital though since he remained very pale and kept asking the same question of "what happened". He could remember what happened yesterday and memory was intact for most everything except for the previous few hours.

Pronounced angioedema, swelling, pain, redness, hardness and fever at the injection site >10 cm diameter, from 2 hours post injection, worsening at 12 hours post injection and gradually improving to 72 hours post injection, with rash still visible.

High fever of 102+ controlled with MOTRIN around the clock. Baby will not sleep longer than 30-45 min at a time. Restless or awake all night. Screams and writhes for up to an hour at a time multiple times during the night. Decreased appetite. Decrease in wet diapers. Pale face. Red around eyes. Looks exhausted. Excrement is tan and soft.

The same day, the patient  was vaccinated with a dose of M-M-R II intramuscularly for prophylaxis, lot # N008366 (dose and expiration date were not reported). This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant referring to 12 months old male patient. There was no information about the patient's concurrent conditions, concomitant therapies or medical history provided. On 10-JAN-2018, the patient was vaccinated with VARIVAX (lot # N019128, expiration date 22-JUN-2019) (dose and route of administration were not reported) for prophylaxis. She started shaking her head back and forth really fast and then she started shaking head to toe, I rolled her onto her side and it subsided after 25-30 seconds. There wasn't any symptoms before hand, I checked her temp afterwards and it was 99.8 by underarm.
Cellulitis, KEFLEX 500 mg PO /3 TIMES A DAY for 10 days.

Pt. upset prior to HPV injection, crying 5 min after shot was given pt became clammy and dizzy-urinated self-easily aroused-Examined by Dr.,  Vasovagal event. Had pt lay for 20 min-Left office in stable condition.

MOP states that daughter woke up morning following her vaccinations with nickel size hives on her calves, elbows. MOP states that she put on a topical anti-itch steroidal cream and the hives went away. Patient did not seen bothered by the hives and had no other symptoms with her reaction. MOP states that the next morning, day 2 following vaccines, daughter woke up with nickel size hives again but on her back. MOP applied the same topical anti-itch steroidal cream and the hives went away. MOP reports no other symptoms.

Pt was given ROTATEQ vaccine orally, waited 2-3 minutes and then administered IM vaccines. Pt then left with mom. As mom was loading pt into car she noticed red rash/welt type lesion on right side of face and immediately came back into clinic.
Accidentally sibling vaccines to this patient.
Flu vaccine 0.25 ml was given to 12 year old instead of 0.50 ml dose. Recalled several times to get .5 Flu dose. Has not yet been revaccinated.
Mother reports erythema and "bumps" at vaccine administration site following vaccination. Now is a well demarcated, annular hypopigmented patch, non palpable, non tender, measures 8 cm x 5.5 cm
Right thigh became red, swollen, hardened, hot to the touch and extremely itchy.

Patient passed out approximately about 5 minutes after receiving flu shot. She got up from a sitting position to leave and experienced vision darkness before passing out. Once patient was placed on the floor, she was awake and alert. Spoke with patient's mom 3 days later, patient is doing fine.

MMR injected into (R) thigh SC. Patient immediately cried. Almost immediately, a large red area developed at the injection site. Flat erythematous circular lesions on forearms, upper arms and near injection site. Flushing of both cheeks also occurred.
1 hour later grandmother had to call 911, because patient's heart rate has increased. (She is 8 years old).

Pt. rec'd 1 year IMM in office on 01-08-18. Returned for O.V. on 01-17-18 D/T rash (LT) arm which appeared 01-17-18. Afebrile; (LT) posterior arm with approximate 1" x 1.5" area of erythema; no induration, no warmth; non-tender to touch, no fluctuance. Not cellulitis. TX: Monitor. Ok for 5yr IMM.
No adverse event noted. Parent was called as soon as the incident was discovered. Patient's mom called again this morning and she is reporting that patient is doing fine.

1/21/2018 child presented with a fever of 102.5 around 11:00pm. 5ml of TYLENOL given. 1/22/2018 child's fever remained but had no other symptoms. Was taken to pediatric clinic for catheterization and urine sample since there is a history of VUR. 5pm lab called and confirmed urinalysis was clean. 72 hour wait for cultures. 1/22/2018: child bathed and had temperature taken rectally around 7pm. Rectal temperature read 103.5. Child then starting having arm convulsions, staring at the ceiling, would not respond to his name being called and had shallow breathing. Episode lasted less than 30 seconds. Child was given 5ml of TYLENOL which he vomited within minutes. Child seemed dazed, and confused for roughly 30 minutes after episode. Child was taken to the emergency room and presented a 102.9 fever. Was given TYLENOL rectally.
Redness and slight swelling at injection site. Warm to the touch.

The storage characteristics were the following: Temperature: 47 F to 77 F for 17 hours. Previous temperature excursion: No. No adverse effects were reported.
Redness and slight swelling at injection site. Warm to the touch.

This spontaneous report has been received from a currently 34 year old female patient who was also a registered nurse concerning herself. The patient's pertinent medical history included gluten intolerance. The patient's drug reactions or allergies included allergy to latex. The patient's concomitant therapies were reported as whatever vaccines they administered to 1 year olds in 1984. On 30-NOV-1984 or early December 1984, when the patient was one year old, she was vaccinated with M-M-R II, 0.5 ml once for prevention of measles, mumps and rubella (dose number, route of administration, anatomical location, lot number and expiration date were not provided). On the same day, she developed fever and hives and it was reported that she was brought back to the doctor. It was unknown if treatment was given for the events or if lab diagnostics or studies were performed. It was also reported that because of those events, she did not get any further doses of M-M-R II, however, the patient stated that she had had multiple titers done since then and she was immune to measles, mumps and rubella. On an unknown date (reported as after stopping the therapy), the patient had recovered from pyrexia and urticaria. The causal relationship between M-M-R II and the events was unknown.

Initial unsolicited report received from a physician on 11-Jan-2018. This case involves a 4-year-old male patient who was vaccinated with 0.5 ml dose of QUADRACEL (Batch no: C5248AA) via subcutaneous route at right thigh and also with 0.5ml dose of PROQUAD via intramuscular route (Batch number: N020619) at left thigh (expiry date and dose in series were not reported for both the vaccines) on 10-Jan-2018. Patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. Pt did not have any chronic illness, no known drug allergy. It was also reported that this was a well visit for vaccination. On an unknown day following the vaccination, patient's right thigh had local tenderness to the injection site and was limping and dragging the right foot. No other symptoms were reported. It was also a case of actual medication error due to inappropriate route of vaccination as patient received QUADRACEL subcutaneously instead of intramuscularly. Laboratory investigations and corrective treatment were not reported. The outcome of the events limping and vaccination site tenderness were not recovered at time of reporting. This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error. Documents held by sender: none
Five papular rash on torso.

Dad noticed bulging anterior fontanel approx. 14 hours after receiving Immunizations. Lgf earlier in evening treated with TYLENOL. Brought to ER and followed up in clinic in AM. Labs in AM WBC and CRP moderately elevated. Hgb/Hct WNL. Platelet count WNL. U/S head normal on 1-17-18. 1-18-18 baby is back to normal behavior baseline (previously not as happy or perky). Anterior fontanelle open and flat.

Day of immunization developed fever of 102.8 taken rectally, a cough, was lethargic, vomiting couple of times. Parents took child to urgent care who thought it might be a bad reaction to vaccine. Symptoms lasted 2 days and then fever broke, slight cough for 1 wk after, did have x-ray of lung - slight inflammation but no treatment, no major irritation at site of infection.
Redness, inflammation, hot to the touch.
Had vomiting 4 hours after vaccine, had constipation then diarrhea.

Mom in our clinic with patient to receive 4 month vaccines. Mom states after receiving 2 month vaccines her baby ended up hospitalized. He was unable to have a bowel movement and was screaming in pain. Took patient to ER and spent 5 days at the hospital. Negative for suspected Hirschsprung's. Upon following up with her pediatrician after discharge pediatrician states it could have been a possible adverse reaction related to ROTARIX vaccination.

This spontaneous report was received from a registered nurse and refers to a 10 month old male patient. The patient's pertinent medical history included umbilical hernia and cardiac murmur functional (reported as: "PPF functional heart murmur"). The patient did not have any concomitant medications and drug reactions or allergies. On 08-JAN-2018, the patient was vaccinated with a first dose of ROTATEQ vial, orally, lot # N014980; expiry date 16-NOV-2018 (dose was not reported) for prevention of rotavirus. On 08-JAN-2018, the patient was vaccinated with the second dose of ROTATEQ vial, orally, lot # N009962; expiry date 15-NOV-2018 (dose was not reported) for prevention of rotavirus. On 17-JAN-2018, the patient was admitted to the hospital with a diagnosis of intussusception. Unspecified treatment was given for the event. On an unknown date, intussusception was reduced but re-occurred at the time of the report. Unspecified lab diagnostic and studies were performed (reported as: " whatever was completed in the hospital"). At the time of the report, the patient was hospitalized. Re-reduction of intussusception was being attempt. The outcome of the event was reported as not recovered. The relatedness between the event and ROTATEQ was not reported. The reported considered the event to be life threatening and causing the patient a significant disability or incapacity. Upon internal review, the event of intussusception was considered to be medically significant.

Patient's left wrist ganglion cyst grew in size. Both the patient and his mother are convinced that he woke up the morning after the 2nd HPV shot with a notable increase in the size of his ganglion cyst. They also stated that they are convinced that the ganglion cyst originated after having received the first dose of HPV vaccine on 6/27/17, but they did not bring him to see me for his ganglion cyst until 12/12/17. The ganglion cyst has always been asymptomatic: no pain, no limit in his range of motion. He saw an orthopedic hand specialist for it on 12/14/17, who recommended monitoring it clinically. He again saw me for it on 1/23/18, after it had increased in size, and it is now approximately 1 cm in size but still painless, nontender, and without any limit of his ROM, so I recommended continuing to monitor it and to return if it causes pain or limited range of motion or continues to grow. I also told them I would file this VAERS report but felt that it was not related to the HPV vaccine.

Vomiting. Occurred within a few hours after the shot. Child acting normal all day before the vaccination. Late that night we called the hospital to see if he should be brought in. We decided on the phone to see if it got any worse before doing so.
Red, hot, swollen arm.

The reporter stated that on an unknown date, the patient developed a lump at the injection site (injection site mass) that was painful (injection site pain). This spontaneous case, initially received on 01-Jun-2017, was reported by other health professional (registered nurse) and concerns students in an academic campus, who received flu vaccine. This case deals with nineteenth of 23 reports. From 03-Oct-2016 to 04-Oct-2016, 176 students were vaccinated with FLUCELVAX in the total of 258 students in the campus. In the spring of 2017, an outbreak of the flu occurred and lasted for approximately 10 days. The reporter stated that, from 13-Apr-2017 to 18-Apr-2017, they treated 22 students with flu and among them 5 students had the vaccine on campus. In the beginning of 18-Apr-2017, they treated another 23 students with flu symptoms and only 3 of those had not received the flu vaccine. The students were tested positive for influenza A via rapid flu test with nasopharyngeal swab. This case concerns 15-years-old patient of unspecified gender. On 03-Oct-2016, the patient received FLUCELVAX QIV (dose, route of administration and anatomical location: not reported, batch number: 185888, expiration date: 31-May-2017). On 24-Apr-2017, the patient was tested positive for influenza A via rapid flu test with nasopharyngeal swab (characterized as vaccination failure). Based on the investigation performed, it can be concluded that FLUCELVAX 185888 was manufactured in compliance with the approved internal procedures and in accordance with the quality requirements. No evidence was found that the LOE complaint was the result of the Fill Finish or Bulk manufacturing process and no trends were identified for the batch number 185888, or any other FLUCELVAX QIV batches from the 2016-2017 FLUCELVAX Commercial season. Therefore no internal root cause could be confirmed. Outcome of influenza A virus infection and vaccination failure was not reported. The reporter did not assess the seriousness and did not provide the causality between events and suspect vaccine. The reporter stated that, the students received flu vaccine had less severe symptoms than those who had not received the flu vaccine. Batch review report (QAIR number: 1022277) received from quality assurance department on 29-Jul-2017: QA investigation results were updated. Narrative amended accordingly. Non-significant case correction received on 10-Aug-2017: Corrections were made in the narrative and case comment.

I was completing our monthly medication review form today, 1/25/18, to be submitted to the pharmacy. Our clinic has had two doses of stock PENTACEL available since November, possibly even before, no additional stock PENTACEL has been ordered after November. Both doses of PENTACEL shared the same lot number and expiration dates. I found one complete dose of the two components, and one dose of only the DTaP-IPV. It appeared the Hib portion had been used. I found one patient within the appropriate time frame from December's medication review form until today's medication review form. I followed-up with the manufacturer. The manufacturer stated the dose received on 1/2/18 was not to be considered valid, and the patient is to repeat the dose.

This non-serious spontaneous case, was initially received on 14-Aug-2017 from physician, concerning a 11-year-old, female child. On 11-Apr-2017, the patient was administered with FLUCELVAX QIV (batch number: 185686 (reported as 185586, 186686), expiry date: 31-May-2017, dose, route of administration, anatomical location: not reported). It was reported, that multiple temperature excursions occurred on 02-Mar-2017, as the vaccine was stored at 47F for 14.7h (1st excursion), 03-Mar-2017 at 47F for 16h (2nd excursion), 04-Mar-2017 at 47F for 19.75h (3rd excursion), 07-Apr-2017 at 35F for 14.5h which was considered as incorrect product storage. The patient was administered with vaccine which was stored at 46F to 77F up to 24 hours instead of storing at 36-46F it was considered as drug administration error. The outcome of the events was not reported. The reporter did not provide the seriousness assessment. Non-significant case correction received 14-Aug-2017: Batch no. (185686) was captured in the case form and narrative was amended accordingly.

Began with stomach cramps followed by one bout of loose stool/diarrhea. At approximately 2:00AM vomiting began with a sore throat. She says she is feeling quite well, is eating a mild diet and drinking water with no adverse side effects.

Outbursts, Much Sleepier/lethargic, Sleeping longer periods, Jittery, Lack of appetite for solid foods, Periods of Crying for no reason in the floor, Fussiness, Screaming, Irritable, Severely Uncomfortable, Diarrhea for 2 days, Throwing things.
Patient's left eye and cheek were extremely swollen. He was irritable and crying with a fever.

Pt was very nervous about receiving the shot. Right after its administration, pt noted that she felt her left arm hurt a lot, then the left side of her body felt numb - arm leg and left cheek. The left arm was pale as was pt's face. She was conversant throughout this event with no LOC no change in phonation, no lip or tongue swelling, no hives. She was asked to lie back down - her arm and cheeks pinked back up, her strength was strong and equal in her arms and legs and her face showed no asymmetry, tongue was midline, smile without a droop. Per NP in the room, this appeared to be a vasovagal reaction in an anxious pt -  pt recovered quickly once lay down, had sips of water and lollipop and was back to normal within 15 minutes. Initial skin pallor of left arm and left cheek pinked quickly once laying down. Per mom, an RN, this felt different, more like an allergic reaction. Mo noted three small pink dot rash on her left cheek a few minutes after pt was laying down. There were not raised like hives and did not itch, and resolved by the evening time. Given mo's strong concern that this is an allergic reaction, I am reporting this event to VAERS, with her knowledge.

Four days after receiving the 3 vaccines stated (HepA, HPV and Meningo) my daughter noticed a significant patch of her hair had fallen out/was missing. The area where this occurred was on the right side of her head just behind her right ear. The patch was roughly the size of a 50-cent piece.

Patient received flu shot. Patient's mother returned shortly after stating her daughter should sit down because she felt she was going to pass out. Patient fainted after being seated. When patient lost conciousness, 911 was called. Patient may have also seized for a brief moment . Before 911 call finished, patient fully regained conciousness. Vitals taken once before paramedics arrived. Paramedics arrived and took family to the ambulance for observation. Ultimate outcome is unknown, patient's family not reachable - phone #'s in profiles not working.

My baby experienced lethargy, fever up to 101 and stomach cramping. She was just comforted at home, no meds were given. Her fever broke sometime in the early morning but she still experienced stomach pains through the next day; January 26th.

Loss or developmental regression in expressive speech and increase in inability to regulate emotions by self soothing or accepting caregivers soothing comforts. Increased sensitivity and insensitive to environmental input. Lack of pain response and increase in sensitivity to soft touch and oral stimuli subsequentally diagnosed as Autism.

Patient describes within two hours after receiving the vaccine, that he felt his throat swelling. No shortness of breath, no reaction at the injection site or other rashes. The feeling he had was similar to the oral/pharyngeal symptoms he has with his oral allergy syndrome. He tool his allergy medications as usual, with the symptoms persisting until examination the following morning. He was able to swallow, although it was uncomfortable. It was difficult to breath through his throat while exercising, although it did not feel like his asthma.

Temp to 101.6 No redness of swelling at site of immunization.

Patient developed a fine pink rash on arms, cheeks and abdomen one day after influenza vaccine. Using Loratadine for symptom relief.

This initial spontaneous case, received on 03-Oct-2017, reported by a pharmacist and concerns a 12-year-old adolescent female patient. The patient's medical history was not reported. On 03-Oct-2017, FLUCELVAX QIV was administered (dose: less than 0.5 ml, batch number: 195227 and expiry date: 31-May-2018, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: left deltoid). On 03-Oct-2017, while administrating FLUCELVAX QIV, when the needle of the syringe was screwed to give the shot the Lori lock came apart, the needle and Lori lock ends up stuck in the patient's arm and it sprayed all over the skin (explicitly coded as syringe issue). The patient received partial dose (explicitly coded as under dose). It was reported that, there was no damage in the package condition or in the syringe (25 gauge, no signs of leakage), but broke when needle was inserted as the hub was loose. It was reported that, the product was stored in the original box until used and placed in a refrigerator. It was reported that, no adverse event was experienced by the patient. Based on the PTC (product technical complaint) (PTC reference number: 1025025) investigation performed, it was concluded that, FLUCELVAX with batch number: 195227 was manufactured in compliance with the approved internal procedures and in accordance with the quality requirements. No internal root cause was identified in the manufacturing process, or relating to the syringes or stopper components, and no trends were identified for the batch, or any other FLUCELVAX batches from the 2017/2018 FLUCELVAX Commercial Season for syringes for luer lock separation during administration. The most likely root cause could be attributed to improper handling by the user. The reporter assessed the case as non-serious. Follow up report received on 13-Oct-2017: It was reported that, no adverse event was experienced by the patient. The route of administration and anatomical location was added. The narrative was amended accordingly. Follow up report received on 16-Nov-2017: The PTC Investigation results were updated. The narrative was amending accordingly.
Hard tender "bubble" under skin at inj site.

This initial spontaneous case was received on 10-Oct-2017, from other health professional, concerning a 09-year-old child. The patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On 08-Oct-2017, the patient was administered with FLUCELVAX QIV (dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid, batch number: 195128, expiry date: Apr-2018). On the same day, the patient experienced injection site redness, pain and warm. The patient was treated with BENADRYL oral, applied ice and hydrocortisone cream. It was reported that, the events resolved after 2 days. The reporter assessed the event as non-serious. Follow-up received on 26-Oct-2017: The injection site reaction was reported as raised, red, hot, size of coke can. The patient applied hydrocortisone cream and the events resolved after 2 days. Narrative amended accordingly.

Patient presented to office approximately 24 hours after IM injection of annual flu vaccine. No fever or resp distress. Injection site with approx. 7x6cm erythematous area below injection site, mildly warm to touch, nonfluctuant, not raised, mild tenderness to touch. No bogginess.

This initial spontaneous case, was received from a pharmacist on 11-Oct-2017, concerning a 9-year-old, male child. This refers to 01 out of 04 reports. On 10-Oct 2017, the patient was administered with FLUCELVAX QIV (influenza vaccine, dose: 0.5 ml, route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: deltoid, batch no: 195216 and expiry date: Apr-2018). It was reported that the Influenza vaccine was left out of the refrigerator for a couple of days and temperature had reached maximum of 72F to 90 hours (explicitly considered as incorrect product storage). The same vaccine was administered to the patient (explicitly considered as drug administration error). It was reported that, the patient did not experience any adverse effects after vaccination. The reporter assessed the case as non-serious. Follow-up received from the reporter on 20-Oct-2017: This case was updated from invalid to valid due to reported identifiable age of the individual patients. The patient's age was updated and narrative amended accordingly. Significant case correction received 20-OCT-2017: The onset date of the event incorrect product storage was removed. The event 'no adverse event' was removed from events tab.

All Sx's resolved after seizure with no other illness. Pt. was quickly back to baseline. However, he did develop URI Sx's in the next 24 hours.

Was ill 2 days before influenza IZ - resolved with no more loose stool or vomiting (had only one vomiting). Received IZ after well approximately 10 hrs, went to sleep and awoke 9 hrs later with fever 102 degrees, vomiting many times for 2 days. No diarrhea, had normal formed stool x 1 today. Fever 101.5 in clinic with emesis.

Erythematous, non-raised, blanching 9 cm x 9 cm area around vaccination site. No warmth to touch. Injection sites 1 cm apart. Redness started 1/25/18 and worsened 1/26/18. Advised on OTC BENADRYL and ibuprofen for pain. Denied any respiratory or GI sxs.
Rash on both cheeks. No fever.

An hour after he received the vaccine he had a seizure, no fever at the time. The following day he had two more seizures, one at home while eating and one at the emergency room. He had no fever at the time of any of the seizures. The Doctors indicated these were not febrile seizures.

Mom states child got Flu shot in clinic around 930 1000 on 1/23/18. States child was fine at home all night. States he woke up next morning and arm was red; swollen. Went to school. Fever.

Staff gave the patient a flu shot. 15 minutes later, the patient and her mother told the pharmacist that they were having no interactions to the flu shot and that they were leaving the store. 5 minutes after that, the mother returned with the patient and said that the child was breaking out in hives and was having an allergic reaction to the flu shot. She requested some BENADRYL be given to the child. Staff noticed one small spot on the child's back. Staff gave the child 10 mls of BENADRYL liquid. Upon discussing the reaction further with the mother, it came to light that the child has had hives for the past 5 days. The mother said that the child gets allergy shots, but had to stop them because they couldn't make it to the clinic during school hours. She asked which antihistamine is best for hives, and staff told her ZYRTEC. Staff instructed her to continue to watch the hives and go straight to the ER if she noticed any swelling around the mouth or difficulty breathing. She said she would.

Pt.'s mother reports pt. developing a hive type rash on the back of left leg during around 11:30 am on 1/28/2018, gave pt. 5mL of Benadryl. Rush, trouble breathing, body week as if air has been sucked out of his body. At night crying for all night, fever, lost of appetite.

This nurse suggested BENADRYL and TYLENOL. The morning of 01-12-2018, the swelling was down and the redness was decreased. The itching went away with one dose of BENADRYL.

Vitamins, b12 shots, etc. He is coming around a little bit. But not as much as we had hoped.
Local erythema, Induration, Fever of 101 F.
Patient received the TDAP instead of the DTAP.
Redness on Rt thigh, with blistering and looks blue. Spreading as well. Dx Cellulitis of thigh. Treated with Amoxicillin-Pot Clavulanate 600-42.9 mg/5mL. Pt to take 3ml BID x 10 days.
CHILD RECEIVED 2 VACCINES OF TDAP. LAST ONE RECEIVED WAS 01/27/2017. NO ISSUES AT THIS TIME.
CHILD RECEIVED 2 VACCINES OF MCV4. LAST ONE RECEIVED WAS 01/27/2017. NO ISSUES AT THIS TIME.
Redness, fevered, swelling, pain mother advised to take child to Emergency room.

Minutes after the vaccine was administered Dr. re-entered the exam room to speak to the parents. He exited the room and asked us to mark a raised bump that had formed on the patients right thigh.
