Rash - hive-like to bilateral arms and legs. Described as pink streaks, rash itches.
Vomiting 1 day after Rotavirus , diarrhea 2 days after Rotavirus.
Patient received PEDIARIX, PREVNAR and a accidental TDAP dose instead of Hib dose given by LPN. Patient had no adverse effects.
Pt fainted few minutes after the shot. Though has a history of fainting before after shots.

Patient fainted shortly after leaving immunization room. Told his mom he felt dizzy. I brought him back into immunization room, gave him some water to drink and a couple pieces of chocolate to eat. Was very pale but regained his color and wasn't dizzy after resting for about 10-15 minutes.

Mom reported witnessing patient state suddenly that he didn't feel right. Knees buckled, hands and cheeks "twitched". No LOC. Positive vomit. Then felt better. Episode lasted 15 seconds, estimated. Was back to himself next morning.

This case was reported by a physician via call center representative and described the occurrence of anaphylactic reaction in a 16-year-old female patient who received FLULAVAL QUADRIVALENT. Previously administered products included Influenza vaccine (yearly without difficulty or reaction). Concurrent medical conditions included multiple allergies (has number of basic allergies) and egg allergy (unknown reaction). On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of FLULAVAL QUADRIVALENT. On an unknown date, 1 day after receiving FLULAVAL QUADRIVALENT, the patient experienced anaphylactic reaction (serious criteria GSK medically significant), tonsillar hypertrophy, difficulty breathing, throat swelling and documented hypersensitivity to administered product. On an unknown date, the outcome of the anaphylactic reaction, tonsillar hypertrophy, difficulty breathing and throat swelling were recovering/resolving and the outcome of the documented hypersensitivity to administered product was unknown. The reporter considered the anaphylactic reaction, tonsillar hypertrophy, difficulty breathing and throat swelling to be possibly related to FLULAVAL QUADRIVALENT. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient's concomitant medication was unknown. The physician reported that day after vaccination the patient was picked up from the school and reported to have difficulty breathing, swollen throat and tonsils. The patient was going to be taken to be seen, however it was reported back to the physician that the patient was doing better and treatment was not required. The physician did not see the patient. The physician noted that she did not plan to use FLULAVAL for this patient in the future. It was noted to the account manager that the physician was going to file a report, but the representative was unaware if that was to GSK or VAERS.
3 days after, fever 102 which lasted 3 days. Then rash broke out on day after fever resolved.
Red, swollen, and hot to touch injection site. Pt. is also fussy.
We had five ped patients that received the PENTACEL. Out of the 5 patients one patient didn't receive the reconstitute ACTHIB.

Student complaint of feeling hot inside. Red patches noted to forhead, cheeks, chest and back approximately 15 minutes after vaccination. Vital signs as follows; T 96.9, P 106, R 18  B/P  120/100. Benadryl 50 mg/ml injected IM to her Lt. deltoid. Tolerated well. Rash was cleared one minute after Benadryl injection. Mother was notifed and student pick ed up from school.  Instructions given to parent.
Running nose , breathing difficulty, cough.
Fever 102.5, body temp drop before fever to 97. Excessive crying 2+ hours after vaccines. Fever with acetaminophen 99. Decreased appetite.
2 hours post influenza vaccine, redness and swelling, much discomfort - missing school today d/t the pain.
Pain in Left shoulder.
Large 5in diameter round, raised, hot, swollen area at injection site. Headache and felt dizzy. He was given steroids, BENADRYL and MOTRIN by urgent care clinic around 36 hours after injection given.
Redness and warm to touch about the size of 50 cent piece.

Pt. rec'd 12 mo immunizations 01/22/18 at WCE o.v. mom reported on 01/31/18 that s/s began 01/29/18. Seen for check 02/01/18. S/s= (Rt) arm with positive erythema 3.5 cm x 1.8 cm; splotchy redness with firm 0.4 cm papule; afebrile. Monitor for tiredness fever tenderness = Re-check PRN.
Extreme difficulty falling asleep, screaming for hours on end, complete drop in appetite and thirst for a total of 8 days and then fully recovered. Exam on day 7 was normal except irritability.
Stuttering, Childhood onset fluency disorder.
The next day my daughter started to get a rash on her arms and legs. It has never receded, she seems to have this bumpy rash permanently.

My daughter had a reaction at each injection site and within 6 months, had lost her intelligibility. She has been diagnosed with a speech delay and apraxia. We are doing speech therapy and trying to get her to 50% intelligibility.
I gave patient KINRIX and they should have received PEDIARIX. They need to come back and get a Hep B dose.

PT has not yet been contacted to evaluate if any adverse reactions were present. CDC was contacted, they stated there was no serious risk with giving the extra dose of KINRIX. CDC stated PT will not need the regular adolescent dose that is administered at the age of 11-12 of TDAP, will need a booster of TD at the age of 18.

Exactly 24 hours later, my son's eyes were red and puffy. He could not focus his eyes, they were looking everywhere, but would not look me in the eyes. He would rub his eyes and say "itchy". He had a fever at that moment as well, of 102.5. His leg where he got the injection was red, swollen, hard, warm to the touch and painful. He was unable to walk normal- he limped and walked crooked. I contacted the nurse who told me to put a cool compress over eyes and give TYLENOL. I gave him ibuprofen to keep fever down and monitored. His fever went away in 24 hours. His eyes were not swollen after 48 hours. Then he broke out into cold sweats the second night (01/28/2018). The leg inflammation continued for three days and he finally had no more red swelling and pain on the morning of 01/30/2018.
Following day patient complained of earache in left ear and had a tactile fever. He started reporting to mom that he could not hear out of his left ear.
No adverse events (medication error-administered wrong dose).
Patient developed hives around the injection site. Patient was given Benadryl 3 times. Hives are improving.

Per mother, child had been incredibly fussy since vaccines given on 1/23/18. When mother went to change child's diaper 2/1/18 AM, she noticed a half-dollar size lump/redness on child's R thigh, at the area where MMR had been administered.
Syncope episode after leaving clinic. Patient was taken to ER by parents, Negative CT, Urine culture with >100,000 colonies, treated with antibiotics with instructions to follow up with PCP.

Within three hours of injection of HVP vaccine to left deltoid my daughter started experiencing "stabbing" pain (6/10) in her left wrist (palmer side) that was unrelieved with Ibuprofen, ice or heat. (She denied injury or changes, etc. since office visit) Upon waking up the next morning (0600) she reported bilateral "aching feet", 7/10 on pain scale. Upon examining her feet-she appeared to have a light red/un-raised rash/discoloration over the top of her feet-she denies any itching, burning, etc.-Just that the bottoms of both feet and the tops in some places ached. She was given Ibuprofen- a couple hours later the light red/pink rash was gone but the aching to both feet remain. Upon waking this morning (02/02/18) she said that throughout the night her bilateral hands "tingled" for "a couple of minutes"- she reports she is still experiencing "aching" pain in her bilateral feet, 3/10 this morning. I administered another dose of IBU and sent a message to PCP that pain continues and that we need to follow up. I contacted the CDC yesterday morning and they suggested I take her to her PCP-He had no available office or after hours appointments and suggested I take her to ER. ER attending and NP, reported the could not find a reason for the pain and did not think it was related to the HPV vaccine but "could not be 100%" suggesting that she have second vaccine in six months. NP stated that she didn't know what the VAERS reporting system was and that she had never done it. She refused to provide vaccine information until I requested to see hospital administrator.

Syncopal episode in Health Department lobby 5 minutes after vaccination. These were patient's first-ever vaccinations in her life. She was nervous, had not had breakfast, and reports previous "passing out" with phlebotomy and an intramuscular injection in the past. Patient fell against the wall and was escorted to the floor by her mother. Less than 1 minute later, patient walked on her own to a lobby chair and was given ice to her left cheek where contact was made with the wall. Patient also walked out of the Health Department.

No adverse events have occurred at this time. Patient received a flu vaccine from MD office 11/1/17. Patient and mother came on 1/30/18 to get a flu vaccine and the vaccination was given. On 1/31/18, the MDs office called to let us know the patient had already received a flu vaccine in November.

Child's mother states that child had rash all over her body (front and back) that was itchy. Mother states that she spoke with child's doctor and child was given BENADRYL and is currently clearing the rash.

Pt with febrile seizure on 2-01-18 after receiving 15 month vaccines. Mom noted jaw moving side to side (2-3 min) and looked blue around her mouth, sounded like she was choking on her spit. Was sitting up, seemed like she was reactive to mom, looking at her and moving her arms. Ambulance came and she was not fighting and out of it - post ictal period. No fever noted in office (had vaccines) but temp in ambulance found to be 101. Went to ER (arrived to ER at 13:50PM) and was back to herself and no tests done since she had previous febrile seizure x 1. Has been acting like nl self since. Temp today 99 Temporal scan.

A 0.5ml dose of FLUZONE QUAD was administered in error instead of the 0.25ml dose. MD was notified, he advised cool compress and APAP in case of swelling, which was not needed, no symptoms of event detected by staff or through follow-up with patient's father the next day.

12 mo F w fever Tmax 101 F wo episodes, skin rash papular-erythematous on the left upper thigh round 2x2 cm in the same location she got immunizations, started 12 days after vaccines were given on 1/19/18. TYLENOL was given PRN for fever, w f/u appt on 2/6/18.

Mom called to report that child had developed Chicken Pox and injection site infection. She stated that child developed fever up to 102.3 at 3-4 days after vaccines given and site was swollen, raised, purple-red and hot to touch. He was taken to an urgent care clinic and dx with infection and chicken pox. He was started on an antibiotic for the infection. Mother claims that site of infection was "oozing clear fluid". Also states that lesions were tested "and it is chicken pox".

Mother brought child patient back in 2 days after immunizations were given. Mom stated right thigh was red, swollen. Mother stated child patient was in pain, crying, didn't want to walk. Mother stated no medication was given to child patient for symptomatic treatment.
Patient broke out in severe Hives. Also, she has swollen fingers and pain in her wrists.

Patient experienced an rapid increase in body temperature with a rectal temperature of 103.6F registered at approximately 5:45pm on 2/1/2018. At approximately 5:50pm, patient experienced a Febrile Seizure which had convulsions of less than 2 minutes followed by approximately 2 minutes of non responsiveness. Patient did not stop breathing, but was unresponsive to vocal commands and did not focus attention from his blank gaze. Within 5 minutes, patient was fully responsive and began chattering and crying. At approximately 6:45 when we arrived at the urgent care facility and his temperature was taken temporally, he registered 99.9F with no introduction of fever reducing medications being given.

My baby stopped talking completely!!! She was babbling and making lots of different sounds before, nonstop! She was watching and repeating sounds, sounded like she was saying "hi!" when we said "hi" to her at four or five months. After vaccination she just sat quietly all day. As days passed, she made throat scraping noise to call for our attention.
Blood in stools two times several days after the vaccine, mucousy stools 3-5 days after vaccine, diarrhea beginning 5 days after vaccine.

Right leg shaking when awakened, occurred 3 times at home. Also had episode of right leg flexed and extended right arm, eyes staring straight ahead. Lasted a few seconds. Examined in the office - seemed OK. No fever, no URI symptoms, no vomiting or diarrhea. The next day seen in ER after right arm twitching, legs twitching and  head turned to left. This episode lasted about 15 seconds.

Eating dinner, then sudden onset seizure with head turning to left, eyes fixed, drooling, became stiff and twitching noted. Lethargic afterward and vomited once. Temperature 99.4-101. Taken by EMS to hospital. Became more alert after 30 minutes- vomited again.

My daughter received her 3rd HPV injection/vaccination. Within two months, she experienced several months of unexpected, sporadic, leg weakness, falling down, leg giving out on her, tired, weak, knee gave out, fall over, cant stand up for too long, general weakness and fatigue. Missed school, peers laughed and ridiculed her at school during episodes, teachers viewed her and reported her as a distraction. Emotional distress with trying to fit into the new school while trying to control adverse events from occurring in front of complete strangers. Adverse reactions occurred at home but mostly in school when walking, changing classes all day.

Patient was given the wrong vaccines at the wrong time. Pt received PEDIARIX, PREVNAR and FLUZONE on 2/1/18. Pt had already received PEDIARIX and PREVNAR on 1/18/18. Pt did not display any adverse reaction on 2/1/18 or 2/2/18.

The injection site and approx 2 inches around the injection site started swelling, turning pink, firm and warm to the touch and also had a very prominent border at 10am. By 1pm the size of the swelling was much larger and it became a lot more firm, red, and very hot to the touch. He was starting to pull and scratch at the area and became fussy during diaper changes. I administered TYLENOL suspension (6.5mL) by mouth and also BENADRYL (2.5mL) by mouth. I also applied a cold compress to the site for approx 10-15mins. By 7pm the redness spread and covered a large portion of the front of his thigh. The following morning at 6:30am his leg was the same so I took him to emergency room. They performed a sonogram of the area and diagnosed him with cellulitis and prescribed clindamycin 15mg/mL. I was unable to fill his prescription at the time so he never took it. This morning (the next day) the swelling and redness has subsided. It is still slightly warm to the touch and a hard knot at the injection site remained.

NO adverse events occurred. Expired vaccine was given as the expiration date on box and vial was confusing. Listed as 18OCT17 and thought to expire October 17, 2018 BUT actually expired October 18, 2017.

NONE - The expiration for HIB on the box and vials was written as 18OCT17 and it was thought that the vaccine expired October 17, 2018 when it actually expired October 18, 2017. This was not found until the end of January 2018 when all of our vaccines were brought back to office after the 2 1/2 months of the vaccines being at the main hospital due to the vaccine refrigerator being broken.

Mother presented in clinic on 2/5/18 c/o itchy bumps on pt's legs, arm, and back since 1/29/18. Mother applied Vaseline with no relief. Pt's mother reported subjective fever when bumps first appeared, pt was afebrile in clinic today. Treatment:  Benadryl.
After patient's second set of toddler shots he began to have staring spells, he lost words and had problems walking his head also swoll up. He developed.

At school my son had a powder chemical substance, that I do believe to be a powdered vaccine of some kind put in his face. He broke out in a rash that cause his throat to burn, his entire upper body broke out. His head swell up on the left side.
Patient experienced dizziness and fainting that resolved immediately without treatment.

Per mom, child developed fever (103.6 deg F), injection site redness, swelling, tender to touch. She phoned PCP 1-24-18 afternoon who advised to give TYLENOL or MOTRIN PO. 1-26-18 mom took child to a quick care clinic; child was found to have an ear infection and was prescribed OMNICEF by mouth. The site of injection reddened, warm, sore to touch, appeared to have cellulitis approx. 3" wide x 4.5" long area. Mom advised to give antibiotic, which would help both ear infection and cellulitis, moist compresses, TYLENOL and MOTRIN alternating for pain/fever/ or discomfort. If condition worsened or red streak developed, to notify office. When I spoke to mom Monday 1-28-18, she stated child was running around and much improved. Site improved, not growing in size.
Flu shot administered by local Pharmacy. Child coming into clinic the next day with symptoms of soreness, redness and swelling of left deltoid.
Inconsolable crying which is still occurring as of the date of this report.

Approximately 3.5 hours after receiving the vaccines, my baby became unresponsive, lost all color in her face, and was barely breathing. We rushed her to the hospital across the street where they gave her oxygen and critical care. Her color returned and she was breathing normally after 10 minutes or so, but she seemed dazed for hours. She was  transferred to Hospital that evening. They monitored her overnight with no episodes. She was released the following day. I am happy to include hospital notes. From the emergency room: Procedure The patient received 5 minutes of critical care excluding separately billable procedures and family discussion judging an infant with an altered mental status episode. The child also had decreased tone and cyanosis all of which has resolved. The child is interactive and is breast-fed and clinically has nothing to suggest meningitis and therefore a lumbar puncture has not been performed. We have discussed this with the pediatrician at Hospital and they have accepted this child in transfer. Mom is aware of the need for transfer for further observation. The patient has a slightly elevated white count normal hemoglobin and slightly elevated platelets. Differential is pending. Electrolytes are normal. Random glucose is 111 with the electrolytes. BUN is 7 and creatinine is 0.31. Medical Decision Making Child improved in the ED after having a 10 minutes episode of AMS with decreased responsiveness with cyanosis and pale appearance. Her blood sugar was normal at 114. We have instituted a septic work up that includes, labs, urine, and an x-ray. Portable chest x-ray reveals no infiltrate or other significant abnormalities per EDP Reexamination/Reevaluation Heart is markedly improved. She will however need observation and monitoring. This was more than a very brief episode. Urinalysis is also pending. X-ray per EDP and per radiology reveals no infiltrate.

At a recent visit (2/1/18), I recommended the second HPV vaccine. At that time mom reported to me that for two months after HPV#1, given on 9/27/16, patient had extreme fatigue and sleepiness. She believes it started right after receiving the HPV vaccine. It self-resolved after about 2 months. Per mom, there were no other illnesses or stressors occurring at that time. They did not seek any medical evaluation during this period and the first time I became aware of this was about 18 months later, at the 2/1/18 visit.

Patient report to her mother that her left arm hurt after vaccinations given on 11/22/17. Initially patient had pain and swelling at site. Subsided. In January 2018 patient tells mom that her left arm has begun to hurt again. Mom states "there's a nodule at the injection site. Denies redness, fever, warmth or drainage. Seen at Family Physicians and was prescribed Azithromycin.
MD ordered FLUZONE 0.25ml IM but FLUZONE 0.5ml IM instead. Parent called today 24H later (today) and child had no symptoms and no injury.

Initial unsolicited report received from a physician via phone on 23 Jan 2018. This case involves a 15-month-old male patient who was vaccinated with 0.5 ml second intramuscular dose of FLUZONE (Frequency: once, batch number, expiry date and site of administration were not reported) on 19 Jan 2018. Patient's medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On an unspecified date (also reported as last night), following the vaccination, the patient had developed a temperature of 102 degree Fahrenheit with nausea and vomiting. They are treating the child as appropriate for age. It was also a case of actual medication error due to overdose. Laboratory investigations and corrective treatment were not reported. The outcome of all the events was reported as not recovered. This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive and Module of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error. List of documents held by sender: none.

Patient broke out in hives presented on, face, abdomen, back, and R/L legs. Local Allergy Doctor contacted and alerted of situation. Parent told to administer children's zyrtec. Parent educated on s/sx of anaphylaxis/when to seek medical attention. Local Allergist office will call and schedule appointment for child.
My son has a rash all over his body.
Swollen upper leg/mother brought baby to ER/issues resolved.

Pt. rec'd. 5 yr. routine vaccines in office on 01-31-18. Seen again 02/02/18 for S/S = (LT) arm with redness/warmth; no induration; afebrile. Area 9 x 15 cm. Dx as local reaction to KINRIX. Tx - BENADRYL if achy. Monitor and C/B for fever/worsening.

This spontaneous report was received from a registered nurse and refers to a 4 year old patient of unknown gender. Concurrent conditions, medical history, historical and concomitant drugs were not reported. The registered nurse reported that on 09-JAN-2018, the patient was inadvertently vaccinated with a dose of PROQUAD subcutaneously in the left arm, lot # N010865, expiration date 01-OCT-2018, for prophylaxis (strength, dose and albumin status not reported), instead of the intended dose of M-M-R II (albumin status, lot # and expiration date not reported). The registered nurse also reported that on the same date (09-JAN-2018), the patient received her second dose of VARIVAX subcutaneously in the right arm, lot # M010480, expiration date 01-MAR-2018, also for prophylaxis. All vaccines were reconstituted with sterile diluent (MERCK). No adverse effects reported.

This spontaneous report was received from a medical assistant and refers to a 2 months old patient of unknown gender. Concurrent conditions, medical history, historical or concomitant drugs were not reported. The medical assistant reported that on 09-JAN-2018, the patient was vaccinated with a pediatric dose of VAQTA Injection, 0.5 ml, lot # N020689, expiration date 22-OCT-2018, for prophylaxis (strength, route, dose number and anatomical location were not reported). The reporter denied any adverse effect on the patient.

Pt received her vaccination first, stood up and waited while mother and sister received theirs. While on way out, patient passed out. Did not hit head or hurts self in fall. Pt said his ears felt full right before fainting. Fire dept came. Checked pulse, O2 sat and blood sugar, all ok. Pt left w/mom. Checked on him Sunday. Mom said he was ok.

Left 6th cranial nerve palsy. Patient's mother called into the office for advice/input, and was put on the schedule to be seen. After Dr. (PCP) assessed the patient, he was then referred to Dr. (Pediatric Ophthalmology), as well as Dr. (Pediatric Neurology).

On 11-02-17 patient's grandmother told me that after the 4 month vaccinations that the patient had a three day history of fever of 102+. The patient had "jello legs" and was unable to stand for perhaps as long as three weeks after the immunizations. Family did not notify anyone. "There's nothing you can do anyway," she says. Now problem resolved. Grandmother stated the family wanted to only administer one vaccine at a time. Today she described the event as "Guillain-Barre Syndrome".

Parents note pt became "unresponsive" later in the day after the vaccine, and that her "eyes rolled back."  Parents could not get her to look at them. She would not feed well. They became worried and called our office at approx. 10:30 pm. Our triage nurse documented the patient being more sleepy than usual and difficult to feed. She urged parents to wake pt for feeds and to call back if pt would not take the next feed. Parents state by 2am patient was more awake and fed better. She gradually returned to baseline by the next morning. Parents state her decreased arousal lasted just under 24h.
Vomiting.
Vomiting.
Drowsy, throwing up, stopped breathing. We called 911.
Stopped breathing on several occasions and turned blue then gray in color.

Patient developed sudden onset flushing and edema of extremities in addition to hives on his lower back. Event occurred several minutes after administration of vaccines. He received 12.5 mg of Benadryl and had improvement in symptoms.

Mom reports redness, swelling, and hot to touch at injection site. Started the evening of the day the vaccines were given, got progressively worse. Mom called PCP's office the next day to report. Also stated the site was very hard. Advised mom bring child in to be evaluated by MD. MD evaluated and measured a 5cm x 5cm area of redness and warm skin surrounding the injection site. Diagnoses of "adverse reaction to vaccine" given. No treatment prescribed.
Very pale, whitish lips and dizziness.

Patient sat in mother's lap while administering vaccine in Left Deltoid. Patient squirmed immediately prior to insertion of needle, causing the needle to scrape left upper arm, leaving an approximate 1 inch vertical abrasion. Site was cleaned and bandaged by staff. Staff instructed mother to monitor the site when child returned home from school, clean it and apply a topical "bacitracin" as necessary. Staff also notified patient's School Nurse (as patient at clinic for vaccination before the school day) to be aware of the situation and to monitor the site, clean and redress as necessary throughout the school day.

Patient responded well to vaccine and stated it that it did not hurt at all. Patient put her sweatshirt on and jacket on and stood up and was talking with mother and RN without problems. Mother and Rn were talking and patient fell into cabinet in nurses office. Rn immediately assessed patient who had her eyes open with a look of fear and carried her to exam table. Patient did not remember falling. Rn questioned patient on how she was feeling. Patient stated that she felt sick. Rn had her lay down on exam table for approx 10 minutes and then was provided some crackers and water. Patient stayed in nurses office for approx 20 min total until she was feeling better. Rn did assess child's head r/t fall. Patient had hit her left ear on cabinet with slight redness noted to ear. No further injury and patient denied any pain. Rn contacted mother the next day and left voicemail to check on patient with no response. Rn contacted mother again the following day and spoke with her. Mother states that child is fine and that she "rode" it out for a little bit  that evening but has had no further complications. Rn advised mother in the future to tell healthcare personnel that the child has history of passing out post vaccinations.

After one minute of immunization administer patient was speaking and understanding conversation  he fell from exam table. Older brother picked him up screaming his name. I was thinking patient was having a seizure I asked for him to lay back down. Dr. came into room I stepped out to call EMS. EMS arrived and took him to ER.

Swelling of entire upper arm, with redness, tenderness and fever. Started evening of vaccine administration. Seen in office 2 days later, difficult to tell whether cellulitis or severe local reaction. Then developed respiratory symptoms triggering his asthma.
Patient was given 0.5 ml prefilled FLUBLOK syringe at age earlier than current recommended guidelines. No adverse reactions or symptoms noted.
Reporting because 1st dose is to be given before 15 weeks of age. Infant was 6 months and 23 days old. Too old for 1st dose.

With in 15 minutes, we just left the dr office and were in the car ride home, he started to laugh/ cry that his left side of face was numb and droopy. Started to talk strange and I looked over and his left side of his face was droopy and he had tears in his eyes. I called the doctors office immediately. Once we got home, 15 minutes later it was gone but he was tired. The next day (Friday)around 1pm he complained of a headache and had a fever of 102.3. The remainder of the weekend, he had fevers from 101-103.7, was exhausted, weak. He was able to stay hydrated and still ate but mostly slept. That Monday I took him to doctors again. Complained. Dr was stumped and was going to do research on shots. Told me to continue with Motrin, advil. If still fever on that Wednesday to call again. His fever ended Wednesday but to this day he now has a dry cough and still exhausted. He plays soccer and is very active. He was perfectly healthy walking in for these shots and no one will convince me this was a fluke virus thing. A healthy person does not walk in for a shot and walk out with bells palsy.

Patient has rash, right upper deltoid area with papular rash oval in shape 3x1.5 cm. Slightly tender to touch. Patient had fever to 102 after PROQUAD on 1/29/18-2/6/18. History of shaking and arm flapping after DTAP/HIB/IPV shots at 6 months of age along with fevers to 104. Also, "spaced out" look. Questionable absence seizures.
By mistake I gave the patient Hepatitis B and PEDIARIX (DTap-HepB-IPV).

This was my daughter's 3rd set of vaccinations. After each vaccine appointment, she became extremely sick with a fever over 101.0 and was lethargic. She wouldn't eat and she was not herself. After the first vaccine appointment when she was 2 months old, we took her into the emergency room only to be told that it was "normal" After this 3rd vaccine appointment, about 2.5 weeks later, I noticed that my daughter was acting different and would start to do this involuntary like movement with her neck bobbling her head to one side-almost like a seizure. She did this multiple times that I documented with my cell phone video on July 5, 2017. I made her an appointment with her pediatrician who told me that she didn't know what it was on the video but that it was possibly a tantrum. To my surprise, after I left and looked at my checkout documents, I saw that she diagnosed my daughter with "gross developmental delay" which is astounding to me since she started crawling at 6 months, walking at 9 mo etc. I then decided to take her for a second opinion the next day with a different pediatrician- she also didn't know what this seizure like activity was so I asked for a referral to a neurologist. I went the following week as scheduled only to be told by the neurologist that " this must be my first child" and that there was absolutely nothing wrong with her and that it was her throwing a tantrum. This happened only once or twice more and then never again with no explanation whatsoever.
Injection administered; pt grabbed at needle with hand. Pt did not get hurt; no skin punctured but vaccine was wasted. Pt had tiny scratch on left leg from needle. Vaccine readministered.
Fainting after received HPV vaccine MENVEO and TDaP.
Positive swelling and mild redness around the injection site with warmth. Non tender. BENADRYL 7.5 ml given.

Child was squirmy and restless while sleeping. At 2:00AM he woke up saying he was going to throw up. He went back to sleep for 30 minutes then woke up and began vomiting. Child went back to sleep at 3:30AM and slept for the rest of the morning and so far has been fine.

Within 30-60 minutes of vaccine, patient developed swelling and redness and pruritis of left upper arm, below injection site. Mother reports that immediately after injection, patient had bleeding (more than normal). On exam 1 day later, there is a 11cm x 6.5cm indurated erythematous patch on left deltoid region, with visible injection site superior to patch. Nontender to palpation. No fluctuance. No other skin rashes/hives present. No shortness of breath, trouble swallowing, facial swelling, lip swelling, vomiting. She did have some mild abdominal pain this morning (usual type of pain for her). She has had multiple flu vaccines in the past with no reaction. No other vaccine reactions in the past. Questioning whether injection ended up subcutaneous rather than intramuscular.
Patient had rash reaction in left thigh where PREVNAR was around injection site. Fever unknown etiology.

I mistakenly took a BOOSTRIX vaccine from our immunization fridge rather than an INFANRIX and inadvertently administered it to my 7 month old patient. Once I realized what I had done I immediately notified the doctor and the mother of the patient. Dr. then notified the Health Dept to speak with one of the immunization nurses there. They together reviewed the prescribing information. Dr. then went and spoke with and reassured the mother of the error and what to watch for in the case of an adverse reaction.

Patient tensed prior to giving shot. Shot was administered. He was fine. After giving shot, pharmacist was notified that he has passed out during shot administration. Patient wasn't feeling well. Pharmacist asked patient to remain seated. He started passing out. He passed out and came back to. Was given food and drink and sat for 15 minutes. Patient was fine and was able to leave pharmacy unassisted with father.
Within minutes of her first MMR she developed redness and wheals at injection site, total area of involvement was about 6cm. 12.5mg of BENADRYL given.
Within minutes, she had fatigue, increased injection site soreness. Redness, muscle pain, swelling noted within 10 minutes after TRUMENBA injection.

This is what Mom reported to me on 02-07-2018. On 11-24-2017, the child had a fever of 101 degrees and then had a seizure. They took the child to the emergency room. According to Mom, one of the seizures lasted 45 minutes. Health Center flew the child out to another Hospital. The child stayed at hospital for 3 or 4 nights according to Mom. Mom reports the child was on medication for seizures, but isn't anymore. Mom reports that the child has not had any seizures since this.

This spontaneous report was received from a nurse regarding an unspecified patient of unknown demographics. Information on pertinent medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. On 18-JAN-2018, the patient received improperly stored VARIVAX lot# N020016 with expiry date of 17-JUL-2019 for prophylaxis. The patient also received a properly stored sterile diluent  lot# M037020 with expiry date of 02-MAY-2019. Temperature: -14 C to -10 C. Timeframe: 10 minutes. There was a previous temperature excursion. -14 C to -10 C for 327 minutes. The call was because of data logger. No adverse effect was reported. Follow up information has been received on 30-JAN-2018 from the registered nurse (R.N) referring to a 13 months old female patient in regards to the letter received. The registered nurse stated that this patient did not experience any adverse events. The request for information was reviewed with the registered nurse in light of vaccine storage events. At the time of report, the registered nurse was able to inform regarding the patient who received VARIVAX Lot N020016 was a female. The registered nurse had no further information. The registered nurse would not be sending back the form. Additional information was not expected.

This spontaneous report was received from a registered nurse regarding a 14 year old female patient. The patient had no pre-existing physician diagnosed allergies, birth defects and medical conditions. The patient had no illness at the time of the vaccination. The patient had no concomitant medication. On the morning of 07-NOV-2017, the clinic refrigerator had a temperature excursions of 39/48 degrees Fahrenheit (F). Temperature was short lived as believed by clinic staff but was unsure on the length of time of the excursions. The patient went to clinic for examination. On 07-NOV-2017, the patient was vaccinated with first dose of improperly stored dose of GARDASIL 9 (dose and unit not reported) (lot # M040412, expiry date: 30-JUN-2019) intramuscularly for prophylaxis at public health clinic/hospital with private funds. The patient did not receive any prescription drug treatment. The patient tolerated immunization well. No adverse event or complications were noted. It was reported that possibly a temperature excursions occurred as a result of reading from a Digital Data Logger. The reporting nurse stated that the state representative was notified on 22-DEC-2017 and the manufacturer was notified on 04-JAN-2018 who stated it should be ok.

This spontaneous report as received from a physician refers to a female patient currently 11 years of age. The patient's relevant medical history, concurrent conditions and concomitant medications were not reported. On 03-APR-2007 (reported as 12 days before she turned one year old), the patient was vaccinated with an unspecified dose of VAQTA (dose, frequency, route, lot # and expiry date were not reported) at an unspecified location for prophylaxis (drug administered to patient of inappropriate age). No adverse effects were reported.

This spontaneous report was received from a physician, referring to a 4 month old male patient. The patient did not have relevant medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications. On 05-JAN-2018, the patient received a dose of improperly stored ROTATEQ, orally for prophylaxis, lot # M043836 and expiration date on 17-JUN-2018. On 22-JAN-2018, the patient experienced fever and runny nose and went to the emergency room. The patient was not admitted to the hospital and it was unknown by the reporter if treatment was given for the events. The physician reported that the vaccine experienced temperatures below 32 F for 9 hours 6 minutes and of 32 F up to 35 F for 19 hours 11 muntes. There were no previous temperature excursions reported and the call was because of a data logger. The outcome of fever and runny nose was not reported. The physician considered that the events were not related to the vaccination with ROTATEQ.
Redness on LT deltoid area, itchiness x 2 days.
Left upper arm with erythema and swelling extending from shoulder to elbow. No systemic reaction.

This spontaneous report was received from a patient's mother via a company representative and refers to a 11 year old male patient. There was no information regarding the patient's medical history, concomitant medications, drug reactions and allergies provided. On 01-FEB-2018, the patient was vaccinated with unidentified Merck hpv vaccine administered (name and lot number not provided). On the same day after vaccination, the patient's eyes rolled back in his head, he twitched and passed out for more than two minutes. The outcome of the events was reported as resolved on 01-FEB-2018. The reporter considered aforementioned events to be related to the vaccine.

Invalid dose due to spacing error at office. MMR vaccine was given on 1/24/16 in the office then on 2/2/18 a Varicella dose was given in the same office. No known adverse reaction, school nurse called Local Health Department because office was not understanding that the dose would be invalid and said child didn't need further vaccines as that would be over vaccinating the child.  Local Health Department sent a letter to office that child would need another Varicella vaccine with spacing 3 months from 2/2/18. This will protect child and fulfill school requirements. CDC directed me to report this.
Swelling, Mild tenderness, redness, 8"4 effected area.

Approximately one minute following the vaccine the child began to slump forward as if she was reaching down to pick something up. When I saw that her hands were not reaching and she was going head first I reached down prevent the fall. Upon lifting the child she was limp and her eyes were closed and color of her skin was pale. She regained consciousness in approximately 2-3 seconds. I lifted her on to mother's lap and immediately provided a Sprite to sip on. Mom stated child hadn't eaten anything since the morning. Child remained on mom's lap for several minutes while we ensured safety of child.
Symptoms: Full body rash that started on his abdomen upon getting home from the office visit and spread. Treatment:  Watch and wait.
Parents report after that series of vaccines, child starting showing behavioral changes (not engaging with parents, isolating himself to play). Also reported GI symptoms that have persisted.
Redness and pain on the injection site.

On 1/10/18 pt was brought in for an acute visit regarding a rash on the right leg. Although a significant amount of time has lapsed since the vaccine was administered, the rash that examined was most consistent with shingles in the exact location that the varicella vaccine was administered. The rash remained limited to that specific area before slowly resolving by 1/18/18 (the next time the patient was seen).

This spontaneous report was received from a consumer refers to a 14 year old female patient. The patient's concurrent conditions included attention deficit/hyperactivity disorder, anxiety and depression. The patient's medical history and historical drugs were not reported. The patient's concomitant medications included ADDERALL and LEXAPRO. On an unknown date in October 2017, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose in the HPV vaccination series with GARDASIL or GARDASIL 9 intramuscularly for prevention of cervical cancer. The patient reported that the patient started having symptoms of cellulitis on 31-JAN-2018. It was unspecified where the cellulitis was located on the patient's body. The patient reported that the patient was hospitalized for cellulitis on 02-FEB-2018 and was still in the hospital. The patient also reported that on an unspecified date between 02-FEB-2018 and 05-FEB-2018, while hospitalized, the patient was diagnosed with "the flu." The patient underwent lab diagnostics: complete blood count and extensive blood tests: results were not provided. The patient received unspecified treatment for the events, on an unknown date. The outcome of events, cellulitis and influenza was reported as not recovered. The relationship between events and GARDASIL or GARDASIL 9 was not provided. No product quality complaint was involved. The patient had significant disability or incapacity and missed the school due to the events. Upon internal review, the event cellulitis was determined to be medically significant and also considered serious due to hospitalization.

About 15 minutes after leaving the doctor and receiving her 18 month I believe MMR vaccine, my child began projectile vomiting, and her fever spiked to 102. Her fever did come down but stayed at 99-101 for the next 2 or so days, her doctor said this was normal, but the projectile vomiting & inconsolable crying for a half hour after, didn't seem normal. A friend gave me the link to report, after her second reaction last night, to another vaccine.

Extremely irritable, not sleeping or napping at all, screaming and holding head, hives all over abdomen and blisters and welts all over thighs, butt, pelvis and lower stomach. Started 3 days after shot was given and lasted 3-4 days. More than a week later child is still angry, not sleeping and in pain.
Client inadvertently was given influenza vaccine mixed with hepatitis A vaccine (HAVRIX-Peds Lot EMD4R Exp 9/18/18). No adverse effects reported at this time.
Left arm pain, fever 100.8, hives on chest and abdomen.

Less than 48 hrs after admin of vaccine fevers 103.5. Lethargy - unable to walk - developed neck and back pain. Seen in ER - for meningitis; Sx D/C after spinal tap 2/1/18 admitted to ER due to having seizure. EEG normal. As of 2/7/18 doing better.
1/2 dollar sized lump at inj site. C/O itchiness, warm to touch.

Approximately 2 weeks after receipt of this vaccine my son developed high fevers of 103-104 and developed red raised papules all over his body. These persisted for approximately 4 weeks in duration. My son was lethargic and had regression in his verbalization and intermittent diarrhea. I tried to get into our pediatrician for an assessment but they were unable to see him in until much later in the afternoon so we opted to see another pediatrician that day. We were told it was a fever of "unknown origin" but the physician documented it in my sons chart as an "adverse vaccine reaction" within 1 month of receipt of the vaccine series. We were never told by either physician that his reactions were a vaccine related despite the fact both pediatricians noted in his medical records that his reactions was vaccine induced. I only discovered this after requesting his medical records in 2017. That is why there was a delay in reporting.

My son has had vaccine injuries that I was unaware of because my doctor never told me the signs to look for but after educating myself about the vaccines and the injuries and thinking back I now realize it's because of the vaccines that my son can't talk.

(Note has had flu vaccine twice previously reported with no reaction). Pt c/o rash which started after FLUZONE vaccine - child says same day, not observed by parents till several days post. Present today for eval and found to have petechiae over legs (approx 2 inches apart), and more widely separated on arms and torso, not on palms or soles of feet. No other symptoms. No itching, no malaise, "rash" is flat.
Pt developed a 4-5 cm urticaria spot over injection site 1 day after injection was given.   Recommended treatment was antihistamines & topical anti-itch cream in addition to monitoring.

Parents reported pinpoint pink dots on skin (one on upper lip, two on right cheek, on right ear) and a flesh colored dot on left arm. Areas slightly raised, no warmth. Parents did not recall them being there prior to immunization. Patient monitored and released from office.

This spontaneous report was received from an unspecified health professional and refers to a 4 year old male patient. No information was provided regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions or concomitant medications. On 13-NOV-2017, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose number 1 of PROQUAD lot # M043307, expiration date 24-APR-2018, by subcutaneous route in the left thigh for prophylaxis. Previous temperature excursions were detected and the digital data logger was involved (product storage error). Additionally it was reported that the patient did not have any illness at the time of vaccination and no other vaccinations were administered within 4 weeks prior to this date. On 13-NOV-2017, reported by the patient's mother, he got sick following vaccination (malaise). This event was reported to an unspecified doctor and the patient recovered from the event on an unknown date. The reporter did not assess the causal relationship between therapy with PROQUAD and the aforementioned event. This is one of several reports received from the same reporter (MARRS # 1712USA003118); Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1712USA003118.

Monday morning 2/12/18, our little patient woke up with cross eyed vision. We immediately called a Pediatric Ophthalmologist and upon reviewing her, requested an emergency MRI at hospital. The thought of our baby going under anesthesia was so terrifying. To see our little baby in the recovery room with an oxygen mask over her face completely passed out because of the anesthesia was a sight no parent EVER wants to see. How could this have happened to our baby? She was perfectly fine on Sunday. We started to put the pieces together and the only conclusion was this could have been a direct cause of her recent MMR vaccine she had last Wednesday. I did notice her acting fussy Saturday, she had serious diarrhea and thought she was catching a cold or possibly teething. Thanks to GOD the MRI results came back normal Thursday. They did see some sinus congestion, but no major mass or tumors. Her ophthalmologist and pediatrician are both saying it?s now a waiting game, this is completely normal and her vision should go back to normal on her own. Worst case, she'll need glasses or surgery. As a mommy, this is NOT normal. When your baby?s eyes are getting worse, there's heavy green mucus in both eyes, you feel like you?re racing against time, you fight, you research, and you're on the phone to get seen by more doctors. This has given me a whole new hunger to know what's in the vaccinations that are given to our children. Again, she was completely normal and her pediatrician even saw her on the day of the vaccine for her 1 year wellness check and said she looked perfectly healthy. I'm a desperate Mama searching for answers and for our baby to get her vision back.

After receiving the GARDASIL vaccine, I had a routine pap smear at age 18. At this time, they found suspicious cells on my uterus, and recommended I get another pap smear every 6 months to 1 year. Had I never received this 3 series of injections, I would have had a normal pap smear. They were starting to lean towards the idea of biopsy in order to check for cancer.

This initial spontaneous report was received on 20-FEB-2018 from the mother of an 11 year old female patient. The patient had no drug reactions/allergies. She was diagnosed with asthma when she was six years old and used albuterol inhaler as needed (but had not used it in three years). On 28-JUN-2017, the patient received her first dose of GARDASIL 9 intramuscularly, given by a physician for the indication of "vaccination" (lot # N043731; expiration 22-JUN-2019) along with diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified), tetanus toxoid (manufacturer not specified) and MENACTRA.  Her daughter reported stomach pain after receiving the vaccine but no treatment was given. The patient received a flu vaccine (manufacturer not specified) on 13-OCT-2017. Then, on 29-DEC-2017, she received her second dose of GARDASIL 9 (lot # N021475; expiration 31-JAN-2020). On 21-JAN-2018, the patient experienced pain in the ear and head, nausea, and dizziness. The reporter took her daughter to a pediatric and adolescent urgent care and was told she had swimmer's ear and was given unspecified ear drops. On 23-JAN-2018, the patient followed up with the physician who administered the vaccine and was told she had a sinus infection. AUGMENTIN was prescribed but no treatment was observed. On 26-JAN-2018, her daughter's condition got worse and she couldn't walk anymore. On 29-JAN-2018, she was seen by the physician again and was told she failed the unspecified neurology test and was told to go to the Emergency Room (ER). The patient was admitted. A computerized tomography (CT) scan, magnetic resonance imagining (MRI), urine and blood work call came back negative. The mother stated "they think she has acute cerebellar ataxia." Meclizine was prescribed for her dizziness. The patient was discharged on 31-JAN-2018. On 06-FEB-2018, she was admitted to the hospital ER due to low blood sugar and slurred speech but was discharged the same day without any treatment. On 12-FEB-2018, her daughter saw a neurologist at a hospital. An unspecified spine test came out normal and no treatment was ordered. The patient has an appointment with another neurologist on 21-FEB-2018 (the mother wanted all follow up questions directed to this physician). The mother reported that up to this point, her daughter had been healthy, other than asthma diagnosed at age 6. She added that her daughter was currently experiencing headache, nausea, vertigo, dizziness, sensitivity to both hot and cold water (described as burning sensation), can't feel both legs and feet starting with the knee caps down, numbness and tingling in legs and feet, pain in the neck, feet, ear, and jaw, fatigue, blood in the stool, and constipation. She believed her daughter's condition was due to a viral infections because that's what most of the doctors and nurses she spoke to stated could be the cause. Therefore, she thinks GARDASIL 9 is the reason her daughter cannot walk and now she is in a wheelchair. The mother also stated that if her daughter does not get better in six months, and Merck does not provide any type of compensation, she will sue Merck. The outcomes of stomach pain, slurred speech, low blood sugar and sinus infection were unknown. The outcomes of the other events were not recovered/not resolved.  The mother felt all the events were related to GARDASIL 9. On 23-FEB-2018, it was determined that lot # N043731 is not valid for GARDASIL 9. The events couldn't walk anymore, acute cerebellar ataxia, numbness of extremities, and viral infection were considered disabling at the patient was now in a wheelchair. Upon internal review, blood in stool was considered medically significant. Additional information has been requested.

Lesion measuring 1.2 cm in elevation and 1.5 cm in diameter. Firm to touch with no associated fluctuance. No drainage. Erythematous. No associated hot. Ultrasound: A region of increased echogenicity, which is moderately demarcated from adjacent subcutaneous fat, is demonstrated anteriorly in the right thigh, corresponding to the palpable abnormality. It measures 7.8 x 6.8 x 4.5 mm. A portion of the center is slightly more hypoechoic, but no significant fluid is identified within the region. A small linear collection of fluid may be present deep to this region. Findings are most consistent with a region of induration/reactive change. A drainable abscess is not identified. This apparently corresponds with a region of a vaccination.

This spontaneous report was received from a physician and refers to a 12 year old female patient. On an unknown date, the patient developed a lump the size of a quarter at the injection site (vaccination site mass), that lasted a little over a month. It was reported that the patient sought medical attention, however, no treatment was provided for the event and the patient had not received any additional doses of GARDASIL 9 due to this reaction but might complete the series at a later time. Additionally, it was reported that there might had been something wrong with the medical assistant's injection technique because there had been multiple other unspecified patients who had also developed a "lump" at the injection site after receiving unspecified injections administered by the same medical assistant. The reporter did not provided the causality assessment between the event vaccination site mass and therapy with GARDASIL 9.

While Mom was nursing patient, about 15 minutes after receiving immunizations, approximately 10:25 AM, Mom noticed that patient's face was really red and she brought him out to the nurse's station. RN noticed that patient's face was red and blotching, resembling hives with what appears to be an allergic reaction. The blotching and developing hives appeared to be spreading down to his upper chest. By the time RN got patient back in the room, the blotching had spread to his abdomen. Redness and swelling at the injection site to the right thigh was also noticed. Epinephrine 0.15 mg auto injector was administered to right vastus lateralis by RN at 10:35 AM. During this time, patient is awake, responding to Mom, and crying/breathing without difficulty. Lungs are clear to auscultation in all lobes. At 10:38, blood pressure in L leg is 106/64, respiration rate is 66/min, heart rate is 144 bpm, capillary refill is less than 2 seconds, blotching in face and trunk as well as in right thigh is diminishing. Patient continues to respond appropriately to Mom and is interacting with her; calms down and is no longer crying. Lungs remain clear to auscultation. At 10:50 lungs remain clear in all lobes, respirations are even and unlabored at 24/min, heart rate is 146 bpm, capillary refill less than 2 seconds, redness to the face and trunk as well as in right thigh is almost completely gone, patient is smiling, alert and calm in Mom's lap. RNs and office manager, discuss with Mom the options of having EMS transport patient to either his doctor's office or the ED, or Mom could transport patient directly to his doctor's office on her own as patient is much improved and has not needed any repeat doses of epinephrine. Mom decides to transport patient to her doctor's office. Patient is a patient of Dr. RN notified Dr.'s nurse of the situation and that Mom is transporting patient to their clinic to be assessed. Nurse says Dr. is out all week, but that patient will be seen by one of the other providers. RN also requested that the notes and plan from patient's visit from today at clinic be faxed so that we will know how to vaccinate patient moving forward. Mom left clinic with patient at 11:05 AM to head to his doctor's office. RN called doctor's office around 11:30 AM to check if patient made it to their clinic, which he had and was checked in.

This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published literature article, concerning a 12-year-old female patient. No information regarding the patients' medical history or concurrent conditions was provided. The patient was a part of a retrospective analysis that studied the impact of 7-valent pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV7) on the incidence of invasive pneumococcal disease (IPD) in cancer patients, along 20 years. The patients included were registered with at least 1 visit between 01-JAN-1992 and 31-DEC-2012. Unique patient-visits (UPV) (inpatient or outpatient) per calendar year, age, and cancer type were obtained from hospital databases. However, non-cancer patients were also included. Patients <15 years were considered "children", and at least 15 years old were "adults". Children 0-4 years were referred to as "vaccinees", and patients at least 5 years old were "non-vaccinees". The IPD incidences were categorized as "before PCV7" (occurred between 1992-2000), "after PCV7" (2001-2010) and "after PCV13" (2011-2012). The authors observed an abrupt decline in the incidence of IPD in 2000, coinciding with the introduction of PCV7. It remained relatively stable through 2010. The IPD incidence declined after PCV7 in children 0-4 years (vaccinees) and in at least 5 year old patients with hematologic malignancies (non-vaccinees). This suggested an indirect effect of routine childhood immunization with PCV7. They suggested that continued surveillance is warranted to characterize the burden of IPD in the era of PCV13 and optimize preventive strategies in highly immunocompromised patients. On 06-JAN-1993, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of PNEUMOVAX 23 injection (dose and route of administration were not reported). There were no concomitant therapies reported. On 28-DEC-1993 ("before PCV7"), the patient was found to have invasive pneumococcal disease (type 6; one of the vaccine serogroups). The patient was hospitalized due to the event on an unknown date. No prescription drug treatment was required, however it was reported that the patient required unspecified medical/surgical intervention to prevent one of the serious outcomes. She recovered from the event on 12-JAN-1994. The authors considered the event of invasive pneumococcal disease to be medically significant, life-threatening and related to the vaccination with PNEUMOVAX 23. The physician stated that no further information was available. It was a study done via chart records from over 5 years ago, and those records were no longer available at the time of contact. This is one of several reports derived from the same literature (linked reports MARRS# 1802USA000459, 1803USA007152). Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1802USA000459.

This literature report has been received from the authors of a published article. In this case series, the authors described seven immunized healthy children without a history of primary varicella who presented with herpes zoster that correlated with the vaccination site of live attenuated varicella-zoster vaccine. These cases highlight the varied clinical presentations and diagnostic and therapeutic considerations for herpes zoster in healthy children. Seven vaccinated healthy children without underlying immunodeficiency presented with herpes zoster in the limb that correlated with the vaccination site. Their clinical histories are summarized. Each patient underwent varicella zoster vaccination at 12 to 14 months of age. The pediatrician's office confirmed the site of vaccination in six patients and the parents in the seventh. Median age at presentation was 3 years (range 1.5-6 years). There were no precipitating factors elicited by history in five patients; one patient developed the rash at the site of recent influenza vaccination and one patient developed the rash after surgery. The morphology of the lesions included erythematous papules, pseudovesicles, pustules, and plaques, with associated pain in two patients and pruritus in three. Systemic symptoms ranged from none to low-grade fevers, upper respiratory symptoms, and joint pain. Clinical and laboratory findings, specifically positive direct fluorescent antibody (DFA) testing, were consistent with herpes zoster in four cases; because of distinct similarities in the clinical examination, DFA testing was not conducted in the other three cases. Acyclovir was prescribed for five patients but deferred in two because of the mild or late presentation. The evaluating physician's differential diagnosis in the seven cases included viral exanthem, eczema herpeticum, atopic dermatitis, contact dermatitis, microcystic lymphatic malformation, herpes simplex infection, and herpes zoster infection. In one patient with knee pain, there was initial concern for septic hip, but inflammatory markers were not elevated, joint effusion was not seen on ultrasound, and the rash and knee pain self-resolved after several days. This report refers to a 1 (reported as 1.5) year old male patient without a history of primary varicella. On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with varicella-zoster vaccine (code as varicella virus vaccine live (Oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown), Zoster Vaccine Live (manufacturer unknown) and Measles, Mumps, Rubella and Varicella (Oka-Merck) Virus Vaccine Live (manufacturer unknown)) (dose and route unknown, left leg) for prophylaxis. On an unknown date (reported as 6 months later), the patient experienced herpes zoster in left leg (in L3-L5 dermatomal distribution) (no symptoms specified by the reporter). The direct fluorescent antibody (DFA) testing was positive. The patient did not receive acyclovir treatment for the event. The outcome of the event was recovered without complications. The reporter considered the event of herpes zoster was related to the suspected therapies. This is one of several reports from the same reporter.; Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1803USA007855: US-009507513-1803USA007856: US-009507513-1803USA007857: US-009507513-1803USA007858: US-009507513-1803USA007859: US-009507513-1803USA007860:

We hadn't connected yet that it was vaccine related but we knew that her body was desperately trying to detox through her skin. We gave her daily lemon essential oil baths and applying detox oils. Within about a week the hives started to subside but they didn't completely go away for two whole weeks after the vaccines. The initial hives did go away. She also started having extra sensitive skin after this event. Out of no where we had to choose even gentler options for our daughter. Now three years later, after a lot of detoxing, she can just barely start to handle things being applied to her skin again so she is just now starting to really recover - especially since we've connected the vaccine to the skin issues and started to take detoxing after the vaccines seriously.

We first noticed her lymph node swelling on the right side of her neck approximentally 02/17/2017 where it had swelled roughly the size of a dime with no dis-coloration. It could have been swollen sooner, but gone unoticed. I waited around 7 weeks before taking her in since it didn't grow very much in size at first, she had no symptoms like fever, or pain in the area when it was touched or rubbed, and we honestly contributed it to allergy season. However, it started to swell more, so I took her in first 04/07/2017, where they assumed allergies as well at the time being, and prescribed Cetirizine HCI 1MG/ML which we gave her as directed. It's important to note that on this visit, they also went ahead and gave her the HEP A VAC PED/ADOL, 2DOSE INTRAMU (90633). After this visit, her node began to more rapidly swell, started showing red discoloration and she started showing some discomfort. We took her in again, a week or so later, (I can't find the paperwork when exactly) and they prescribed Clindamycin Palmitate HCI 75MG/5ML which we took as directed for the course of time directed. We brought her back in 04/27/2017 where they started her on Amoxicillin-Pot Clavulanate 600-42.9MG/5ML, which we started giving as directed, but after 5 days I stopped it after it gave her thrush, made her more irritable, and I simply wasn't convinced it, or the previous medication was working, and wanted better answers as to why this may be happening. We were then sent to Medical Center at their ENT department to see NP where they prescribed taking Clarithromycin (BIAXIN) 50 MG/ML until her appointment with Dr. on 05/17/2017. I was still insistant that medication wasn't working, as it kept giving her diarrhea, thrush, and horrible rashes, and wanted a hospital visit to find out what was wrong since everyone seemed stumped. I asked of course, if it had anything to do with vaccines, but the notion was shut down by every doctor I asked. We were admitted to the Medical Center. After several tests, to include a sonogram, they still couldn't determine what caused the reaction, but concluded it wasn't systemic, which is why medications weren't working, and essentially the lymph node had become like a cyst. We were told to give her Azithromycin 40 MG/ML for 4 days, which I did as directed, and to allow the node (which at this point was about the size of a silver dollar and completely red with some purple, and seemed to cause discomfort when we touched it.) to simpy pop and drain on its own. Which it did a few days later in the middle of the night. Dr. recommended a type of cosmetic surgery upon our visit to him on 05/17/2017, which I turned down. Since then, we've been instructed to let it heal on its own, and "see what it does". No one still seems to know or accept what truly caused it in the first place, or what any long term damage might be yet, and it hasn't been further addressed since the follow-up appointment after the hospital visit. No more vaccines, or medications have been administered to pt since.

Information has been received from the authors of a published article regarding to 14 year old female patient. The patient did not have a history of chicken pox infection and was up to date with her vaccines. The patient was in good health and had no sick contacts or travel history. Immunity to hepatitis B had been previously documented. The patient had no known history of asthma, allergies, atopic dermatitis, or allergic rhinitis; no other infections were noted in the patient's history. Moreover, the patient was not receiving any medications. The patient received the recommended two doses of M-M-R II, 0.5 ml, subcutaneously  (strength, frequency, lot# and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis and PROQUAD 0.5 ml dose subcutaneously  (strength, frequency, lot# and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis after reconstitution in a sterile diluent for subcutaneous injection). The first dose VARIVAX 0.5 ml, subcutaneously  (strength, frequency, lot# and expiration date were not provided) for prophylaxis, was administered at 14 months of age and a second dose PROQUAD at 4 years of age. The third dose (re-immunization) VARIVAX was given at 14 years of age. It was reported that peripheral blood samples (5 ml) were collected. Data were reported as ratios as follows: ranges for varicella zoster virus (VZV) Ab IgG: negative <0.91, positive >1.09; VZV Ab IgM: negative < 0.901, positive > 1.09. On an unspecified date in May 2017, the ranges of post-re-immunization bloods for VZV IgG Abs changed to negative < 135.00; 135.00–164.99 equivocal; >165.00 positive. Prior to re-immunization, VZV IgG Ab levels were negative (< 0.90 Ab index) and VZV IgM VZV Ab levels were also negative (= 0.90 Ab index) indicating either no prior exposure to VZV or lack of a specific immune response to immunization. However, 1 week post-re-immunization VZV IgG Ab levels were positive (690.70 Ab index) and VZV IgM Ab levels were negative (= 0.90 Ab index). For weeks 2–8, VZV IgG Ab was present, while VZV IgM levels were negative (-), except for week 8, where VZV IgM levels were positive (0.99 Ab index). In contrast, VZV IgE Ab levels were undetectable pre- and post-re-immunization. Measles Ab IgG levels were < 25.00 AU/ml (range <25.00 negative, 25.00–29.99 equivocal, >29.99 positive). Mumps Ab IgG levels were 17.90 AU/ml (range < 9.00 negative, 9.00–10.99 equivocal, >10.99 positive). Rubella Ab IgG levels were < 0.90 Ab index (range <0.90 negative, 0.90–0.99 equivocal, = 1.00 positive). Pre-re-immunization, distributions of lymphocyte subpopulations (CD3+CD4+, CD3+CD8+, CD19+, CD4+CD60+, CD8+CD60+) in the peripheral blood of the patient were all within normal ranges. However, post-re-immunization (4 weeks), numbers of T cell subpopulations remained unchanged, while CD19+ B cells increased 48% post-re-immunization (8 weeks), the numbers of T cell subpopulations remained unchanged, while the numbers of CD19+ B cells decreased slightly (6%). It was reported that the patient received two doses of M-M-R II, but had negative responses for measles and rubella (Vaccination failure). It could be speculated that a lack of a robust T cell memory response may indicate the underlying pathology of secondary vaccine failure, which was defined by the authors as a gradual loss of immunity after an initial immune response over a period of years after vaccination (wanning immunity). Upon internal review, the event Vaccination failure was considered to be medically significant. A copy of the published article is attached as further documentation of the patient's experience.

This literature marketed report has been received from the authors of a published article and refers to an 11-year-old patient. On an unknown date, the patient received her first dose of GARDASIL vaccine (dose, route of administration, lot# and expiration date were not reported) at a well-child visit. She had been healthy aside from sinus surgery and frequent infections. Prior immunology evaluation was negative, but there was a family history of autoimmune disease. Two days postvaccination, she developed headache and vomiting thought due to a viral illness. Her symptoms were progressive, however, and by 5 to 6 weeks postvaccination, there was abdominal pain, frequent vomiting, severe fatigue, pallor, daily syncope, chest pain, dyspnea, low-grade fevers, arthralgias, daily headache, memory loss, tinnitus, hearing loss, vertigo, unsteady gait, leg weakness, muscle twitches, paresthesias, and insomnia. By 7 weeks postvaccination, she had become bed-bound. She also developed moderate alopecia, Raynaud's phenomenon, recurrent oral ulcers, and nasal scabbing, suggesting the possibility of systemic autoimmunity. Eight months postvaccination, she was diagnosed with postural tachycardia syndrome (POTS) and neurocardiogenic syncope (NCS) by tilt table testing and autonomic reflex testing revealed abnormal blood pressure response to Valsalva and reduced baroreflex adrenergic sensitivity. Nonautoimmune causes for her symptoms were excluded with laboratory testing, echocardiogram, cardiac monitoring and brain magnetic resonance imaging. The autoimmune dysautonomia panel antibodies, NMDA (N-methyl-d-aspartate) receptor antibodies, thyroid antibodies, and celiac antibodies were all negative. Testing for Sjogren's syndrome (including the early Sjogren's antibodies), antiphospholipid syndrome (with primary and secondary antibodies) and lupus was also negative. However, autoantibodies against adrenergic and muscarinic receptors were detected (Anti-beta-1 adrenergic receptor antibodies: 21.7 units/ml (positive), anti-ßbeta-2 adrenergic receptor antibodies: 11.4 units/ml (indeterminate), anti-muscarinic cholinergic receptor-3 antibodies:13.5 units/ml (positive) and anti-muscarinic cholinergic receptor-4 antibodies: 24.9 units/ml (positive)). The patient did improve with conservative therapy, but she remained moderate to severely disabled by her illness. Small fiber neuropathy was suspected due to her cardiovascular and presumed gastrointestinal autonomic dysfunction as well as the presence of muscle twitches and paresthesias, and a skin biopsy was performed (from the lower legs as normative data were available) to evaluate for this possibility (biopsy results: Epidermal Nerve Fiber Density: left lower leg: 8.1/mm (normal), right lower leg: 8.6/mm (normal); Sweat Gland Nerve Fiber Density: left lower leg:16.7% (abnormal), right lower leg: 27.5% (abnormal). Given the patient's young age (13 years at the time of the biopsy), these results were consistent with a very severe autonomic neuropathy and likely a mild to moderate small fiber sensory neuropathy. Given evidence for autoimmune autonomic neuropathy, a trial of intravenous immunoglobulin therapy was initiated. After four months of therapy at a dose of 1 gm/kg monthly, the patient continues to gradually improve. Her COMPASS-31 score has improved from 46 to 29 and her estimated level of functioning has improved from 20% (mostly bedridden) to 60% (more good days than bad days). The earliest signs of improvement came after the second week of treatment. Her recurrent syncope and paresthesias have resolved. Her epigastric pain, migraines, insomnia, anxiety, fatigue, and cognitive ability have all moderately improved and she had been able to stop her biweekly saline infusions. She continued on monthly intravenous immunoglobulin. The outcome of autonomic neuropathy, syncope, small fibre neuropathy and autoimmune neuropathy was reported as recovered/resolved. The outcome of systemic immune activation and postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome was reported as recovering/resolving. The authors considered postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome, systemic immune activation, autoimmune neuropathy, small fibre neuropathy, autonomic neuropathy and syncope to be related to GARDASIL. All the events were considered to be disabling by the reporter. Upon internal review, the events of systemic immune activation, autoimmune neuropathy and autonomic neuropathy were considered to be medically significant.

Patient is a(n) 10 y.o. female who presents to clinic after fainting this morning. She was here for WCC yesterday afternoon, received TDAP, MENACTRA and HPV. We observed her for 15 min after vaccines, she felt great, went home. Her evening was uneventful. This morning, after waking, went to take a bath. While waiting for the tub to fill, she was standing in the tub and suddenly "felt weird." She then noticed she "couldn't see or hear," so went to get out of the tub and find her mom. The next thing she knew, she found herself on the floor. She heard water running, got up and turned off the tub, went to her mom and told her she was having trouble seeing and hearing, fainted again. Her mom said she was unresponsive for a brief period (seconds) and then awoke. After lying on the floor for a few minutes, she was acting normally, reported feeling only tired. Mom brought her in. She feels tired now and on and off has had a mild headache. She isn't sure whether she hit her head, denies any point tenderness to head or other part of body. She's never before fainted. She has several severe food allergies, has had multiple episodes of hives and angioedema.

This initial spontaneous report was received from the mother of a currently 26 year old female patient. No information was provided regarding the patient's medical history, concurrent conditions, or concomitant medications. In 2003 or 2004, at the age of 12, the patient was vaccinated with GARDASIL 9 (dose, route, lot and number in series not provided). However, the mother also could not confirm whether the product was GARDASIL 9 or Quadrivalent Human Papillomavirus (Types 6,11,16,18) Recomb. Vaccine GARDASIL (note that GARDASIL was approved for marketing in June 2006 and GARDASIL 9 was approved for marketing in December 2014). The mother reported that GARDASIL 9 did not work the way it claimed. On an unspecified date (but reported as "recently"), the patient was diagnosed with cervical cancer and high grade HPV types 18 and 16.  Due to the diagnosis, the patient "has to have some, if not all, of her cervix removed." The patient has many medical bills due to the issues that resulted in the vaccination failure and the mother was trying to get her daughter's past, current, and possibly future medical bills covered by Merck. The mother stated if she needs to, she will get a lawyer. It was not specified whether the vaccination series was completed. The outcome of the events was unknown. Causality assessment was not provided. Upon internal review, cervical cancer was considered medically significant. The reporter did not provide consent to be contacted for follow up.
