Immediately after the injection (less than a minute), she was lightheaded & dizzy, very pale/grey, had ringing in the ears. She said she didn't feel good, then fainted/passed out. She began twitching. She was very clammy to the touch and she was shivering cold. The doctor was notified right away and I (her mother) was able to wake her, by then the doctor was in the room. The doctor had my daughter lay on her back with her knees to her chest for a few minutes. After a few minutes, her well child visit was able to be completed. After the exam, my daughter moved from the exam table to a chair to begin putting her clothing back on. She was able to get her pants on before she just sat there feeling nauseous along with lightheaded, dizzy, pale/grey, ringing in the ears for a second time. I was able to get her back to the exam table to lay down just before she again fainted. She again felt cold and clammy, she was shivering. The nurse happened to pop her head back in and quickly spoke to the doctor who advised my daughter to have a Popsicle. That was actually very helpful. My daughter had eaten breakfast, but that was about four hours prior to the vaccine. After all of this, she is mentally and physically exhausted. She is moving very slowly and deliberately. Every time she stands, it takes effort because of the dizziness/lightheaded feeling. It will be a few days before I can fully say that she's okay. As a parent, this is very traumatic. I made the choice to give her this vaccine, but will not be finishing the dosing.

My son woke up totally normal full of energy Friday April 13th, 2018. He had his annual 4 year old wellness visit and he was looking perfectly healthy. About a hour after vaccination my son complained of both of his legs hurting really bad and then said he was "really tired" words never spoken by my active 4 year old boy, who will never admit he is tired even if he is. He no longer naps and when we got home he took a 2-3 hour nap and woke up with a fever of 102.5 F. He complained of bilateral leg pain but still wanted to go to the park to play with friends, so we took him and he was unable to keep up and play with the other kids something I've never witnessed in him. His legs appeared heavy and stiff and he was tripping while trying to run around with the other kids. Later that night he was having a lot of trouble walking. He crawled upstairs to bed and he was screaming uncontrollably saying his "brain hurt." He cried himself to sleep and still had a fever in the morning. He woke up screaming of bilateral wrist and hand pain. He could not walk or stand up on his own at all. His lower limbs were limp and when I stood him up to urinate he peed all over the place because he couldn't stand up on his own. We rushed to the Emergency Room and we were there for 8 plus hours. He was given ibuprofen and later that night he was able to stand up again and somewhat walk. He was stumbling very badly and doing a weird skip/run and he is normally very coordinated. Sunday and Monday he wasn't very active, which is very out of the ordinary for him. He tried to ride his bike and go for a walk but he didn't last more than 100 feet before wanting to be carried. Today he is walking so much better.

Leading up to the date of 6-18-2015, patient had several episodes of ear infections treated with Amoxicillin. On 6/18, his pediatrician at that time injected pt with 8 combination vaccines (listed above) while pt still had an active ear infection. After this, pt slowly lost his ability to verbally communicate. Before the vaccines, pt had a vocabulary of around 50 words and after he is only able to verbalize about 5 words. By the beginnning of 2016, pt lost verbal communication and social skills. He began stimming, spinning in circles and engaging in repetitive behavior. Today, he is still almost completely nonverbal and struggles with social skills. He was diagnosed by Hospital with Encephalopathy and by Dr. with Encephalitis.

This 5-month-old male subject was enrolled in an open label study. The subject received the 2nd dose of Rotavirus vaccine lyophilized formulation (oral) 1 ml on 5th December 2017. The subject received the 2nd dose of DTPa-HBV-IPV vaccine (intramuscular) .5 ml on 5th December 2017. The subject received the 2nd dose of Hib vaccine (intramuscular) .5 ml on 5th December 2017. The subject received the 2nd dose of PREVENAR 13 (intramuscular) .5 ml on 5th December 2017. On 21st January 2018, 47 days after receiving Rotavirus vaccine lyophilized formulation, DTPa-HBV-IPV vaccine, Hib vaccine and PREVENAR 13, the subject developed mild - grade 1 abdominal distension. Serious criteria included hospitalization. Additional event(s) included mild - grade 1 rhinovirus infection on 21st January 2018 with serious criteria of hospitalization and mild - grade 1 enterovirus infection on 21st January 2018 with serious criteria of hospitalization and GSK medically significant. The subject was treated with ampicillin. DTPa-HBV-IPV vaccine was continued with no change. Hib vaccine was continued with no change. PREVENAR 13 was continued with no change. The outcome of abdominal distension was recovered/resolved on 22nd January 2018 12:38. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included rhinovirus infection (recovered/resolved on 26th January 2018 23:00) and enterovirus infection (recovered/resolved on 26th January 2018 23:00). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the abdominal distension may have been caused by Rotavirus vaccine lyophilized formulation. The investigator considered that there was no reasonable possibility that the rhinovirus infection and enterovirus infection may have been caused by Rotavirus vaccine lyophilized formulation, DTPa-HBV-IPV vaccine, Hib vaccine and PREVENAR 13. The investigator considered that there was no reasonable possibility that the abdominal distention may have been caused by DTPa-HBV-IPV vaccine, Hib vaccine and PREVENAR 13. Relevant Tests: CXR 1/21/2018 AM: Bilateral perihilar consolidation, left great than right, findings suspicious for pneumonia. ABD 1/21/2018 AM: Colonic distention secondary to large amount of stool at the rectal vault. CXR Comparison 1/21/2018 at 0520 Hrs: Diminished perihilar patchy opacities are seen, left more than right. Diagnostic results (unless otherwise stated, normal values were not provided): On 21st January 2018, Abdominal X-ray result was see text, Abdominal X-ray result was normal, Chest X-ray result was see text, Chest X-ray result was see text, Enterovirus test result was positive, Human rhinovirus test result was positive and Oxygen saturation result was 88%. Investigator text: Subject presented at ER on 1/21/2018 with cough and abdominal distention with sick siblings at home. Abdominal xray showed colonic distention secondary to large amount of stool at the rectal vault. Surgery was contacted for concern for obstruction while subject was in the ER. Subject was transferred to a nearby hospital for further evaluation. Surgery evaluated subject as had a large stool, abdominal distention resolved, and well. Initial imaging CXR, there was concern for bilateral perihilar consolidation, left greater than right. Findings are suspicious for pneumonia. Subject was treated with 1 dose of Ampicillin. While overnight in the ED patient has desaturation to 88%. Follow up Abdominal Xray was normal which was completed on 01/21/2018. Subject tested positive on 01/21/2018 for rhino/enterovirus infection. Patient was tolerating regular diet and remained well-saturated. The hospital who admitted the subject stated in their report that the 1st hospital who transferred the subject for their initial concern for pneumonia, however upon the hospital review of the chest xray it's more consistent with viral process. Patient was discharge on 01/22/2018. Discharge Diagnosis: Rhino/Enterovirus Lower respiratory tract infection and Follow up with PCP in one week. Confirmed at today's visit by dad that symptoms did not start until around 1:00 AM on 21Jan2018. Dad states patient was feeling better and back to himself by Friday 26Jan2018. Follow up information received on 18 Apr 2018: Per discussion with PI on 18April2018: The cause is unknown but there is a possibility that the Abdominal Distension was caused by the HRV.

This case was reported by a other health professional via call center representative and described the occurrence of serum reaction in a 4-year-old male patient who received KINRIX (batch number 2439H, expiry date 25th April 2020). Concomitant products included Measles Mumps Rubella and VARIVAX. On 6th February 2018, the patient received KINRIX. On 7th February 2018, 1 days after receiving KINRIX, the patient experienced serum reaction, extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site erythema and injection site warmth. On an unknown date, the outcome of the serum reaction, extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site erythema and injection site warmth were recovered/resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the serum reaction to be related to KINRIX. The reporter considered the extensive swelling of vaccinated limb, injection site erythema and injection site warmth to be almost certainly related to KINRIX. Additional information was received as follows: The registered nurse called to the call center representative regarding adverse event. The reporter stated that the patient received a dose of KINRIX in his left deltoid on 6th February 2018 and on the same day he also received MMR and VARIVAX which was manufactured by Merck. The reporter stated that symptoms began the day after vaccination and the patient had a follow-up physician's visit on 6th February 2018. The reporter stated that the patient experienced redness, swelling, and warmth which was extended to the elbow and spread to back of shoulder of left arm. The reporter was not aware of any other medical intervention taken and stated that symptoms are now resolved. The reporter stated that the physician diagnosed this as other serum reaction due to vaccination and stated that there were no signs of infection. The reporter stated that she was not aware of any other medication or medical history of patient.

This spontaneous report as received from a consumer (patient's mother) refers to a 13 year old female patient. The patient had no pertinent medical history, drug reactions/allergies and concomitant medication. On an unknown date in August 2017, the patient was vaccinated with first dose of GARDASIL 9 and on 10-APR-2018, the patient was vaccinated with second dose of GARDASIL 9 intramuscularly for prevention of human papillomavirus (HPV) (dose, frequency, lot # and expiry date were not reported). On 15-APR-2018 (reported as approximately 5 days after receipt of second dose), the patient began to break out in red, itchy, welts all over the body from head to toe. The patient's mother also stated that that patient had not been exposed to any new environmental changes or potential skin irritants and the reaction began while the patient was sleeping in her bed. The patient was administered with BENEDRYL to counteract the reaction, which was initially successful, however, after the effects of the BENEDRYL wore off, the reaction began to spread again. The patient was also prescribed with ZANTAC (dose unspecified) and prednisone (manufacturer unknown) 60 mg in addition to BENEDRYL once every 6 hours by the pediatrician. The patient had responded well to BENEDRYL, prednisone (manufacturer unknown) and ZANTAC regimen and was able to attend the school. The patient's mother closely monitored the patient for rebound signs of breaking out again. The patient's mother explained that the patient was not expected to need any future dosing with the GARDASIL 9 as she had followed the 2 dose series for the vaccine. It was reported that, the patient sought medical attention for the events. The outcome of pruritus, erythema and urticaria was reported as recovering/resolving. The relationship between the events and GARDASIL 9 was not provided.

This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of seizure in a 6-month-old female patient who received PEDIARIX (batch number FF723, expiry date unknown). On 21st November 2013, the patient received the 1st dose of PEDIARIX (intramuscular) .5 ml. On 21st November 2013, less than a day after receiving PEDIARIX, the patient experienced injection site rash and injection site erythema. On 22nd November 2013, the patient experienced crying, fontanel bulging and fever. On 23rd November 2013, the patient experienced weakness, behavior abnormal, communication disorder, difficulty sleeping and yeast infection. On 28th November, the patient experienced diaper rash and eating disorder. On 29th November 2013, the patient experienced seizure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), ear infection, sore throat and diarrhea. On 18th December 2013, the patient experienced restlessness, acne and skin eruption. On 1st March 2016, the patient experienced eczema and food allergy. PEDIARIX was discontinued (Dechallenge was unknown). Rechallange with PEDIARIX was unknown. In November 2014, the outcome of the injection site rash and injection site erythema were recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the seizure, crying, fontanel bulging, weakness, behavior abnormal, communication disorder, difficulty sleeping, yeast infection, diaper rash, eating disorder, ear infection, sore throat, diarrhea, restlessness, acne, skin eruption, eczema, food allergy and fever were unknown. It was unknown if the reporter considered the seizure, injection site rash, injection site erythema, crying, fontanel bulging, weakness, behavior abnormal, communication disorder, difficulty sleeping, yeast infection, diaper rash, eating disorder, ear infection, sore throat, diarrhea, restlessness, acne, skin eruption, eczema, food allergy and fever to be related to PEDIARIX. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient was administered PEDIARIX in the left thigh. On 22nd November 2013, 1 day after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced crying, fontanel bulging and fever and body temperature was recorded as 103 degree. On 23rd November 2013, 2 days after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced weakness, behavior abnormal, communication disorder, difficulty sleeping and yeast infection. On 28th November 2013, 7 days after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced diaper rash and eating disorder. On 29th November 2013, 8 days after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced seizure (serious criteria GSK medically significant), ear infection, sore throat and diarrhea. On 18th December 2013, 27 days after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced restlessness, acne and skin eruption. On 1st March 2016, 831 days after receiving vaccination, the patient experienced eczema and food allergy.

Client left exam room at 11:52 AM following immunizations. At approximately 12:00 PM the client's mother yelled "excuse me, she's going into a convulsion." Clinical staff responded immediately. Client was found on mom's lap, fully conscious, alert and oriented, and displaying no seizure-like activity. She did appear weak and pale and was complaining of chest pain and not feeling well. No respiratory distress was noted. The client was moved back to the exam room and vitals were taken at 12:06 PM: BP: 80/50 Pulse: 54 Respirations: 16 Temperature: 98.5 F. The client remained alert and oriented and answered questions appropriately. At 12:09 PM she reported that her chest no longer hurt and she was feeling better. The client's grandmother called EMS and they left the clinic shortly after to wait for EMS in the lobby (grandmother's request). A nurse accompanied the family to the lobby. EMS arrived at 12:20 PM. A follow up phone call was made to the client's mother on 5/8/18. She indicated that she took the client to Hospital, where they found the client to be stable and did not admit her.

KEFLEX 250 mg/5 mL suspension; Take 500 mg (10 ml) four times a day for 7 days.

Site red/swollen, patient felt warm ("but not burning up") last night so mom gave him a dose of ibuprofen and he has not felt warm ever since (mom denies any other possible reactions).

Vaccines administered approx. at 10AM. Mother noticed rash and irritability at 2:30pm (red rash to forehead) called office advised to return to clinic. (mother had given TYLENOL at 9:45am and again at 1:45pm). Child arrived at 4:46 at office. Irritable with multiform rash to face, head. T99 no stridor - no facial or arm swelling - today color good, good strong cry. TYLENOL 160/5ml 1.25ml given at around 5pm. Child observed (Approx 45 min) examined by Nurse Practitioner. Normal vital signs, temp 99.3. According to mother child did well after leaving office. Slept and ate well, did administer TYLENOL at 8:45pm just in case.

Per patients mother, approximately 24hrs after injection (5/15), the area became reddened and sore and client had a low grade temperature. Mother reports providing child with ibuprofen for pain. This case was reported by a nurse via sales rep and described the occurrence of injection site rash in a 15-month-old male patient who received INFANRIX (batch number Y5475, expiry date unknown). This case was associated with a product complaint. On 23rd April 2018, the patient received INFANRIX. In April 2018, less than a month after receiving INFANRIX, the patient experienced injection site rash, generalized rash and injection site erythema. On an unknown date, the patient experienced pharmaceutical product complaint. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site rash and pharmaceutical product complaint were unknown and the outcome of the generalized rash and injection site erythema were not recovered/not resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site rash, generalized rash and injection site erythema to be related to INFANRIX. Additional information was received as follows: The nurse reported that the patient experienced a red rash at injection site that was larger than usual and a systemic rash (rash over body). In total 13 patients received INFANRIX with the same lot number but only 3 patients including this patient experienced reactions. The vaccine was administered at the 15 - 18 month visit. According to the treating physician, the adverse events reported were not due to the INFANRIX but thought it was a normal reaction to DTap. The nurse reported that they had 40 more doses from this lot number and she was not sure if they should use so she had sat them aside in the refrigerator until she hears from GlaxoSmithKline (GSK). The nurse was informed that there had not been a recall on this lot but that investigation would be carried out. The reporter had return one vial from the lot for investigation. This case is link with case US2018GSK080192 and US2018GSK080194, reported by the same reporter. The reported agreed to contact on follow up.
VACCINE EXPIRED ON 5/12/18 AND WAS GIVEN ON 5/18/18.

Bump progressively getting bigger every day, looks red, hurts a little bit - on exam: L upper arm with approx 2 cm indurated area 1cm redness overlying, slightly ttp, also with yellow bruise surrounding area, no streaking  - TX: Cool compresses, MOTRIN, gentle cleansing BID, KEFLEX 750 Mg Oral Capsule Take 1 capsule po bid x 10 days.

Cried for the entire first 3 nights, would not nurse, extreme discomfort. Complete Loss of balance. Went from walking to not being able to take 2 steps without falling. He was not able to stand in one place alone, he constantly fell down. I bought him a helmet because he fell so many times, he would hit his head. He was so frustrated, it was awful for him and my family. We changed his shoes and everything. It has taken 4 months and he is up to 8 steps, still falls and balance is NOT 100%. Rash and welts day of shots and came back week 2 and week 3. Constant head banging for the first 5 weeks. He would bang his own head with his toys. He would bang his head on kitchen cabinets, and walls. Loss of speech. He used to say MAMA over 10 times a day. He has only said mama twice in the last 4 months. He used to say BALL 3 to 10 times a day. (Depending if he sees the ball he would pick it up and say BALL) He has never said the word ball since 1/26/18. Daycare said his behavior was aggressive for the first 3-4 weeks. Hitting and pushing kids, which he didn't do before. Constantly still cries and wants to be held all the time, loss of independence.

Sadly the doctor did not provide me any information about vaccines (name/type), etc other than: DTAP IPV + Polio. After the shots (in the morning), my son quickly developed fever and complained about body aches (few hours after the shots). Then apathy (barely moving/talking). He would only cry in pain. I gave him TYLENOL (recommended by Dr) and it would ease the pain every 4 hours. In the evening, he developed hives on the face (they would come and disappear as quickly as they came) and he would cry in pain. The next day, Dr told me it was an allergic reaction to the vaccine. Sadly he never told me anything else: never mentioned me there was this registry/reporting system, never told me what would be the next step (when my son will be 11 and due for the same vaccine, what will happen)?

Syncopal episode with epistaxis post vaccination and confusion to occipital region. Patient complains of blurry vision, headache and stomach ache after 10 minutes of vaccination. Ice pack was applied on head and provided with water. Follow up if symptoms worsen or as needed or post x-rays.

Atypical Steven's Johnson Syndrome ~15 days post vaccination. Recurrence of SJS (as noted previously, ~3 months ago had SJS secondary to influenza B). Developed mouth + eye + penis involvement (ulcerations, clear discharge, pain, photosensitivity) starting 14 days post vaccination.  Worsening over the next two days. History of preceding URI as well about 10 days prior to SJS symptom appearance. Patient admitted to the hospital on 5/25/2018 (15 days post vaccination) -- started on acyclovir, IVFs, clindamycin (secondary to concern of bacterial superinfection of extensive mouth lesions), tobradex drops, and IV steroids (3 days; 1mg/kg/day of Solumedrol). Improving 4 days into hospitalization. Patient received ophtho consult, peds ID consult, and peds GI (to evaluate for esophageal involvement). Dermatology consulted via phone over the weekend. Etiology of recurrent SJS believed secondary to recent URI versus receipt of influenza vaccine --- contacting VAERS for review and recommendation for receipt of influenza vaccine next year. At this time, tracking down lot/manufacturer of influenza vaccine received as well as DTaP.

This spontaneous report has received from a registered nurse via a company representative, referring to a 10 year old male patient. The patient had no medical history, concurrent conditions, drug, allergy history or concomitant medications to be reported. On 16-MAY-2018, the patient was vaccinated with GARDASIL 9 lot # N017686 in the right deltoid for prophylaxis (strength, dose, frequency, and expiration date were not provided). It was reported that on the same date, the patient also received BOOSTRIX in the same arm. Approximately 20 minutes after the patient received vaccination (on 16-MAY-2018), the patient fainted, and experienced seizure like activity, described as tonic clonic movements. It was reported that the patient received unspecified fluids and his heart rate and breathing were monitored as treatment for the events. On the same date, within 20 minutes after the onset of the event, the patient recovered from the generalised tonic-clonic seizure. The causality assessment between both vaccines and the event was not provided. Upon internal review, the events seizure like phenomena and tonic clonic movements were determined to be medically significant.

Patient appeared to be in pain for nearly a week after his vaccines. He didn't look at me/us as often, he cried when we picked him up or moved him at all. His sleeping schedule was changed dramatically, he had bruising at injection site. He was unusually fussy. It seemed like he was in pain when he moved/when I picked him up or moved him (I called the Dr and they said it's "normal" after vaccinations). He's normally very on the go, after the vaccines he wanted to sit and cuddle, or sleep. He'd crawl around some, shortly after he cried and came to me and wanted comforted. He cried loudly instantly when he woke up as if he was having a bad dream or something. He didn't look at me as much, didn't seem as happy, and didn't seem to respond the same way he used to. It's like he was in a fog or something. He woke up as if he was choking, gasping and he woke up coughing. He didn't seem like himself and it was heartbreaking.
HEADACHE.

The shot was given on the evening of the 26th and on Monday the 30th, patient had a grand mal seizure as he was entering his school. He was rushed to the Hospital by ambulance. He did not regain consciousness until he was half way to the hospital. We estimate he was unconscious for about 10-15 minutes. He was given a CAT scan, blood was taken, and an appointment at Medical Center was made for the same day. We met with the neurologist at 1:00 on the same day as the seizure. An EEG was ordered and found to be abnormal. He was then given an MRI and MRA with contrast. These tests were normal. He is now on Ethosuximide twice a day.

My son woke up on 11/26/17 with swelling and pain in legs and lower back. Would not walk. There were also small petechiae on legs. Later in afternoon took him to ER where the ER doctor diagnosed him with HSP (Henoch-Schonlein purpura). Over next week swelling become widespread and very bad rash on legs. His pediatrician did routine urinalysis to monitor blood and protein in urine. Over next several weeks he developed nephrotic-range proteinuria and was sent to pediatric nephrologist at Hospital. The nephrologist monitored his labs closely and by early January kidney function was declining rapidly so nephrologist ordered kidney biopsy and started long-term immunosuppressant medical treatment. My son is now on 4 different medications to hopefully cure his HSP. Medicines (IMURAN, enalapril, prednisolone, ranitidine). We are hopeful he can be off the medicines in 2 years but nephrologist indicated it could be a lifelong battle since treating HSP has mixed results.

Three days after receiving ROTARIX vaccine patient began having gassiness, fussiness and abdominal pain. A day later, he also began having bloody stool. He was thought to have milk protein allergy and was sent home. Later that night, 4 days after vaccination, patient also began refusing food. Seven days after vaccine he developed fever and bilious emesis in addition to persistence of preceding symptoms. He was found at that time to have intussusception. Ex-lap was performed and patient underwent subtotal colectomy, partial ilial resection and end ileostomy on 5/24. My son first received the ActHIB vaccine in his right arm/shoulder. There were no reactions outside of mild/normal with that vaccine. However, then he received the PCV13 vaccine in his left arm/shoulder. By the time we left the Health Department, his left shoulder showed redness at the injection site. He began developing a large, hard knot at the injection site. He would cry out in pain if you touched it. I began giving him epsolm salt baths to help. For two weeks after the PCV13 shot, he had a large, noticeable knot in his left shoulder at the injection site. His vocabulary was very well-developed for a two year old, and he expressed to me the immense amount of soreness and pain that he was in. I had to go to extreme lengths when dressing him as to not disturb his shoulder. At the two weeks mark after injection, the large, hard knot in his shoulder began to shrink. However, he was still terrified and in pain if you tried to go near his left shoulder. By three weeks after injection, it was a small, barely there knot in his left shoulder. It took a full month for it to completely heal. The epsom salt bath did make a positive difference in promoting healing and reducing swelling of the arm.

This literature marketed report has been received from the author of a published article and referring to a 7 year old male patient. Objectives: The patient presents for evaluation of bronchiectasis of bilateral lower lobes and poor growth. Past medical history was significant for gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) with poor weight gain during infancy and childhood, oral thrush, recurrent respiratory infections and bilateral partial hearing loss. The bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL) showed abundant neutrophils and was positive for Strep pneumoniae and Haemophilus influenza. Methods: Serum immunoglobulins were normal with an elevated IgA (369) and mildly elevated IgE (361). Tetanus IgG was protective (0.4 IU/mL) but post-vaccine responses to the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) were poor with protective titers achieved to 3/14 serotypes. Lymphocyte phenotyping was remarkable for a complete absence of B and NK cells. CD4:CD8 ratio was inverted (0.25) and the majority of the CD45+ T cells were memory phenotype. Mitogen proliferation was essentially normal. Due to the absence of B cells and despite normal total serum immunoglobulins, the patient was started on subcutaneous immunoglobulin (SC IG) weekly and antibiotic prophylaxis with trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole and fluconazole. Clinically he demonstrated good weight gain and a reduction in cough and respiratory symptoms. Results: Whole exome sequencing was performed. A single base mutation in ADA1 (c.320 T>C) was identified in one allele. This mutation (p.L107P) is known to be deleterious and when homozygous is associated with typical severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID). However, this mutation was not present on the other allele. Secondary analysis looking for large deletions and duplications failed to identify any abnormality in sequence in the normal allele. But the expression of this allele was markedly diminished causing us to suspect that its function might be impaired. Functional testing was performed and demonstrated that there was no adenosine deaminase (ADA) activity in the patient's red blood cells, thus confirming a diagnosis of combined immune deficiency due to ADA deficiency. Conclusions: Null mutations in ADA result in an absence of ADA function with profound CD3 cell lymphopenia and dysfunction. Clinically affected infants have typical SCID. Hypomorphic mutations may lead to partial function of ADA with more variable immune defects. Interestingly, most patients with ADA deficiency have neurologic complications, frequently hearing loss. We believe that most likely this patient has had some degree of spontaneous reversion of the mutation in the normal allele leading to a less severe phenotype. As reported previously in a case involving a mutation in Interleukin 2 Receptor Subunit Gamma (IL2RG) chain, normal function was not restored and the patient remains with a combined immune deficiency. This case highlights an important limitation of whole exome sequencing and the need for confirming the impact of a genetic defect with a functional assay. The outcome of post-vaccine responses were poor with protective titers achieved to 3/14 serotypes was unknown. The author considered the event to be related to pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown).

Vaccine administered at 10am. Possible side effects explained and patient instructed to wait following administration. Approximately 2 minutes later mom called out for help. This RN entered patient room and witnessed patient had lost consciousness and appeared to be convulsing.  Consciousness was regained soon after (3-4 seconds later). At this time patient was alert, but endorsing continued lightheadedness and a headache. Patient was helped onto exam table, feet elevated. Tried to sit up to take sips of water, but patient c/o "heaviness" and blurred vision so was encouraged to lie back down. Vitals at this time: HR in the high 40s, BP 90/40; vitals approximately 10 minutes later: HR 70s, BP 110/60. Patient stable, alert at this time (approximately 15 minutes from onset of LOC). This literature marketed report has been received from authors of the published article, referring to a 21 month old male patient with aluminum allergy. He received standard 2 - and 4-month immunizations without any reactions. At 6 months of age, he received a PENTACEL and ENGERIX injection in the left leg. Several days later, a golf ball-sized, firm lesion appeared in the left thigh. The lesion became fluctuant and was subsequently incised, producing a culture which was sterile with a negative Gram stain. Seven days later, a small lesion reappeared in the same area that eventually self-drained purulent fluid. His next series of immunizations were administered at 1 year of age, on 19-OCT-2015, including the first dose of VAQTA (dose, lot# and expiration date unknown) in the right thigh for prophylaxis. Concomitant therapies included FLUZONE and M-M-R II. Following the immunizations he developed a similar lesion on his right thigh at the site of a VAQTA immunization. An incision and drainage procedure was performed, from which purulence was obtained but a culture was sterile and a Gram stain was negative. A third golf ball-sized lesion developed on the right thigh after receiving his next PENTACEL immunization 5 months later (on 01-APR-2016), and a fourth abscess appeared on 16-MAY-2017 in the left leg after another dose of VAQTA (also reported as "13 months later following a ENGERIX immunization"). He remained afebrile during all episodes, with no erythema or significant discomfort. He did not receive any antimicrobial therapy for the lesions. The outcome of the events was reported as recovered. The reporter considered the events to be related to aluminum-adjuvant based vaccine VAQTA.

This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of injection site swelling in a 11-year-old female patient who received MENVEO (batch number M16130, expiry date 21st July 2018) for prophylaxis. Previously administered products included INFANRIX with an associated reaction of injection site swelling (for details regarding adverse event, refer case US2018115052). Concomitant products included loratadine and melatonin. On 15th May 2018, the patient received MENVEO. On 15th May 2018, immediately after receiving MENVEO, the patient experienced injection site swelling and injection site itching. In May 2018, the patient experienced headache, rash lips, rash and skin discoloration. The patient was treated with ibuprofen, paracetamol (Tylenol), benadryl (nos) (Benadryl) and famotidine (Pepcid). On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site swelling, injection site itching, headache, rash lips and rash were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the skin discoloration was unknown. The reporter considered the injection site swelling, injection site itching, headache, rash lips, rash and skin discoloration to be related to MENVEO. Additional information was reported as follows: This case was reported by the mother of the patient. The patient received a dose of MENVEO and immediately experienced swelling in arm at site of injection along with itchiness. Caller stated that the patient was given Benadryl and Pepcid right away due to similar reaction with INFANRIX from 2015. The caller reported that swelling was about 3.5 inches around injection site and that 18 hours later patient experienced spots on face and lips that were purple in color. The caller reported that the patient experienced headache as well that Tylenol and ibuprofen did not resolve. Caller reports that events resolved 2 weeks later. Vaccine administration facility information was not obtained during phone consultation. Reporter called back at 2:01 inquiring if the pictures that were associated with the adverse event reports had been received. The sender informed the reporter that he/she would send a follow up and if more information was required she would be contacted by the safety department.

ER visit 07/01/18 at 10:00 AM--instructed to give ALLEGRA and BENADRYL cream, which did not help and hives continued to get worse. Mother initiated oral BENADRYL (1st dose given 3:30 PM). Two phone calls to ER after that- mother was told nothing more they could do and to keep giving BENADRYL. No wheezing or breathing difficulties. Doctor appointment at 9:00 AM on 07/02/2018 with physician at clinic; steroid shot given. Prednisone prescribed if more lesions noted. BENADRYL continues to be given every 4 hours. Lesions on stomach appear bruised, while lesions on back appear bright red.

Tactile fever-night of vaccination, swelling, erythema, warmth and tenderness at site (of (L) thigh, MMRV placed), and lack of appetite-vaccine placed 6/25/18. Mom presented with patient 6/27/18-as above and with worsening symptoms.
Presented in ER on 7-1-18 with 1 day of swelling of both legs. Reaction in both legs some erythema of (L) thigh. Started on KEFLEX.
Excessive crying, "screaming" throughout the day on 7/3. Worsening of rash present that was present prior to vaccination.

The vaccine was given on 6/20. She had fever that evening and none thereafter. On the evening of 6/24, parents noted that the patient seemed to be falling more often than normal and was having some difficulty with her balance. This worsened over the course of the next few days. On the morning of 6/28, she had a brief focal seizure and slept for several hours afterwards. She was seen in our office that afternoon and was acting well apart from some mild gait abnormalities/ataxia. Of note, this patient does have a known seizure d/o and it had been recommended by neurology that she be on anti-epileptic medications; however, the parents have been hesitant to start these. I am doubtful that the seizure was related to her vaccines (and suspect that she would have had one again soon without the recommended antiepileptic drugs), but am unclear as to the possibility that her mild ataxia/gait changes may be. Now, about a week later, dad states that the patient is back to her normal self without any ongoing problems. And, they have started her on KEPPRA per her neurologist.
Hives within 2 hours.

This spontaneous report was received from the office manager refers to 12 week old male patient. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history, drug reactions, allergies and concomitant medications were not reported. On 17-OCT-2017, the patient was vaccinated with improperly stored doses of ROTATEQ orally, lot# M038209 with an expiration date 23-APR-2018 and lot# M041768 with an expiration date 25-JUN-2018. (dose was not reported). Reporter stated that the vaccine was deemed stable. There was no adverse effect reported. No product quality complaint was involved. Administered doses of vaccine experienced the temperature excursion from 32 degrees Fahrenheit to 35 degrees Fahrenheit for 27 hours. Data logger was involved. There were previous excursions reported (from 32 degrees Fahrenheit to 35 degrees Fahrenheit for 27 hours and form 47 degrees Fahrenheit to 77 degrees Fahrenheit for 27 hours). This is one of the report received from the same reporter.

Parents noticed warm, red area at injection site around 8:00 pm 7/5/2018. Parent called office today because area had increased to half dollar size and seemed tender. No fever or streaking. Will monitor and follow-up as needed.

After administration of vaccine, client stated his arm hurt. Advised client to move arm around and client stated "I feel like I'm going to faint." Client assisted with transfer to cot and placed in lying position with knees bent. Client given juice to drink. Client's legs began shaking as if he was shivering. Client had color in cheeks and was not diaphoretic. Arms and body began shivering. Client stated "when I try to move I shake more. Client advised to relax on cot and take slow deep breathes. Pulse 84 beats per minute. Client understood. Client alert and oriented to person, place, and time. After ten minutes, client sat up on cot. Stated he was feeling better. Client was a stand-by assist to sit in chair, no longer shaking. After 5 more minutes of observation, client able to walk to car.
Fever for 2 days starting 5 days after receipt of vaccine and rash started 10 days after receipt of vaccine.

Left outer thigh large indurated erythematous area 10 cm, mildly tender. Swelling at site of KINRIX shot two days ago - no fever. Imp Local reaction to immunization. TYLENOL or MOTRIN for discomfort. Apply ice pack - should resolve in 2-3 days.
Be very careful and not give the wrong vac.

Son stated he got dizzy, closed his eyes and fainted, 911 was called and EMT arrived, son woke approximately 45 seconds later, lips and face were flushed, EMT checked vitals (blood pressure, oxygen saturation, glucose, and heart rate) all vitals were normal, refused Emergency transport to local ED.

Within 24 hours of the vaccine, the patient exhibits excessive bleeding, usually in the form of a bloody nose. This has happened with all 5 doses, but this is the first time I was aware I could report the reaction. The patient has experienced severe bloody noses and bleeding gums after every DTaP shot, with the bloody noses being very heavy in flow, they start extremely easily or with no provocation, and occur frequently throughout the day. This begins within 24 hours of the injection, and lasts about 1-2 weeks. It has gotten worse with each dose, and has now also occurred with the Hib vaccine given about 2-3 weeks after this recent reaction. Nose bleeds will finally stop with an Icepack applied to the base of the skull.
Diahrrea immediately following vaccines. Leg couldn't be touched for three days due to extreme pain in injection site. Patient died 5 weeks after vaccines were given.

Patient received 1st dose of VARIVAX and 6 days later came to our office with classic chicken pox. I unroofed one of the lesions and culture was (positive) for varicella. There was an outbreak of varicella at her daycare with 2 other kids diagnosed in same week.
Redness and swelling at shot site.

He received DTaP and varicella. Twenty-four hours later he woke with rash on buttocks and inner thigh, pink-red, that spread to sides. Later in day, he was noticed to have raised pink welps under arms and on chest and upper arm as well. Red rash in diaper area and inner thigh faced. He also developed an area of erythema, warm and induration around DTaP in left thigh the size of two fifty-cent pieces.

He received his ADACEL, HPV and meningococcal conjugate vaccine. Very early on Saturday morning, he was covered in hives. BENADRYL given. By 4 PM, he was so covered in hives that it was on his face, neck, ears, and over 80% of his body. Urgent care told us to use BENADRYL every 4-6 hours. I have been giving him BENADRYL every 4 hours because if it goes to 5 hours, he breaks out in a horrible, itchy rash. We are still giving BENADRYL every 4 hours and it has been 3 days.

Patient became lightheaded after receiving this vaccine. He was revived with ammonia capsule, after it was placed under the nose. He was given water to drink. Vitals were taken BP 120/70, P 68, R 16. Patient stated that he felt fine, no longer dizzy or lightheaded. He was made to sit for about 20 minutes. He refused to lay down and stated he was fine.

We delayed the vaccines she would normally receive at 4 months to a week before she was 6 months. At this point shortly after the shots she developed a fever. Then March 2nd the day she turned 6 months she went into a grand mal seizure. We have continued the scheduled vaccinations with her pediatricians and now she is diagnosed with intractable epilepsy, autism, severe developmental delay, and a number of respiratory issues.
Left deltoid with redness, swelling, warmth, 8x6cm, instructed to apply warm compress 3-4 times daily and to call for appointment if fever or worsening symptoms occur within 24 hours.
DTAP was ordered, TDAP was mistakenly given.  Patient did not have any adverse reaction. Physician was notified.
Localized reaction on the left leg injection site 4.5cm x 4.5cm non indurated bump shortly after vaccine was given. Full Range of movement of the left leg.
Pt was given vaccine and then mother breast feed baby for about 10-15 min and pt then had hives, no breathing concerns and purpura like rash. BENADRYL was given and referral to allergy.
An area of redness affecting Rt Deltoid reaction about 6". Non tender and there is no induration. Less than 24 hrs after the injection.

2 weeks post WCC with vaccines (listed above)  patient developed "pox style" rash on arm/leg/torso.  Spreading # for 2 days. Total # of lesions 6. Of note - 1 week post vaccines patient seen for 103 temp in urgent care at Hospital.

This spontaneous report was received from a physician assistant and refers to a 4-year-old child. The patient's concurrent condition, medical history and concomitant therapies were not reported. Several hours after injection his R thigh and knee began to swell. He reported pain in the area. The pain and swelling worsened throughout the night and he was unable to walk on the leg the following day. He was seen in our office in follow-up the next day and diagnosed with limb swelling secondary to vaccine and instructed to provide supportive care. Due to worsening swelling he was seen in an ER later that night and diagnosed with cellulitis and prescribed KEFLEX of which he only had 1 dose. He was seen in our office again (by myself) on 7/11 (2 days after injection) and noted to have swelling of entire R leg however no erythema or warmth was noted in the leg or around the injection site. His reaction was again determined to be unilateral limb swelling secondary to vaccine.

PATIENT RECEIVED 2 DIFFERENT IMMUNIZATIONS IN 2 DIFFERENT ARMS. RIGHT WAS TDAP AND LEFT WAS MENINGOCOCCAL. PATIENT HAD NO SIGNS OR SYMPTONS OF FEELING ILL WHEN LEAVING THE IMMUNIZATIONS ROOM. HE WENT TO SIT IN THE WAITING AREA WITH MOTHER AND BROTHER. THIS PERSON WALKED OUT THE DOOR TO CALL ANOTHER PATIENT BACK AND I LOOKED AT THE PATIENT AND SAW THAT HE WAS NOT LOOKING WELL AND LOST COLOR TO HIS FACE. THE MOTHER STATED "SHOULD HE LOOK LIKE THIS?" HE WAS THEN IMMEDIATELY BROUGHT BACK TO THE TREATMENT ROOM AND LAYED ON THE PATIENT BED WITH HIS FEET ELEVATED. AN ICE PACK WAS PLACED BEHIND HIS NECK. HE WAS ALSO GIVEN SOME ORANGE JUICE AND WAS ABLE TO SWALLOW AND TOLERATE IT WELL.  HIS PERSON THEN TOOK THE VITAL SIGNS AND GAVE THEM TO THE CLINIC NURSE. THE PATIENT HAD AN APPOINTMENT WITH HIS PRIMARY CARE MD TODAY AND WILL FOLLOW UP WITH HIM. HE REMAINED ON THE PATIENT BED FOR APPROXIMATELY 30 MIN AND MOTHER CAME BACK TO TAKE HIM TO HIS REGULARLY SCHEDULED APPOINTMENT. HE STATED HE WAS FEELING BETTER AND THE COLOR DID RETURN TO HIS FACE. HE THEN WALKED WITH HIS MOTHER AND BROTHER TO HIS APPOINTMENT IN ANOTHER CLINIC WITHIN THE HOSPITAL.

Patient received Meningococcal conjugate vaccine on 7/11/18. Patient woke up the following morning with right arm redness, induration, and itching. Patient presented to MD office with measured redness 10 x 10cm. Patient denied any other symptoms. Patient with no previous reaction to any other vaccine. Patient instructed to take cetirizine in AM and BENADRYL in evening as needed for itching and to use ice packs for about 20min several times a day. Patient discharged home with instructions to return if symptoms worsen. Meningococcal vaccine added to patient's allergy.

Infant did not have an adverse event, per Immunization Program Director Dept of Health recommended us to file a report. ERROR vaccine administration, Vaccine KINRIX (recommended for 4 year) administered to 6 month infant in error. Infant did not have any reaction, mom only reported fever last night.
ANGIOEDEMA REACTION. SWOLLEN LIP.

Injection site at Right arm became swollen, inflamed, red, and tender, spreading to about 4" and raised about a 1/2". Maintained inflammation, hardness and swelling for about 10 days. From the 29th until 7/12 the area was hard but not tender, with massaging it the hardness dissipated on the 12th. The area is still discolored to purplish tint on skin. A friend that is a nurse at clinic kept an eye on it for us.

Patient awakened with crying and left sided jerking on 4/12/2018. She was brought to our pediatric office where seizure activity was observed and patient was taken to Hospital where she was admitted from 4/12/2018-2/14/2018. She was without fever at our office and in the Emergency Room. Pediatric Neurology was consulted. After workup was completed she was diagnosed with a seizure disorder and she was discharged on Phenobarbital and KEPPRA.
Vomiting, fever, irritability, not eating.

Mother emailed and called on 4/23/18- noted jaw pain x 20 minutes on 4/18/18, then 4/23/18, face tender to touch with worsening on opening mouth, stretching neck to either side. Swelling to both jaws/cheeks. Patient points to area "right under each ear lobe" when asked about pain. Treated with MOTRIN. Pain persisted. No fever.

Approximately thirty minutes after immunization was administered Mom reports that patient experienced a 20 second seizure. States she had some lip smacking and was tonic during seizure activity. Once seizure resolved patient was post ictal.
Rash on R arm and hand and BL deltoid, exactly where injection placed, rash is itchy and raised.

One vaccine was given in the left thigh and the other was given in the right thigh. The vaccine that was given in my daughter's right thigh is the one that caused a reaction. Within six hours of receiving the vaccine, my daughter's thigh became swollen, red, and hot to the touch. The following day a severe rash covered the area of the injection site. It has been five days and there is still redness, warmth, and a rash. I gave my daughter BENADRYL on day three, but it did not alter the reaction.

Child was sitting in exam room chair to receive vaccines. Immediately after receiving second injection (ADACEL), child became diaphoretic, pale, and stated he did not feel well. RN escorted him to exam table, where he lay down. EMS was called. At no point did child lose consciousness. At no point did child fall or hit any part of his body on any surface. At no point did the child become short of breath. There was no visible or palpable local reaction at the vaccine site. Child was assessed by EMS, sat up, sipped water, stated he felt better. Child was taken by EMS to local ER for further evaluation, his father accompanied him.

Diffuse rash and fever up to 102.2.

Parent noticed a red spot on the right thigh near the injection site 3 hours after vaccination on 7/16/18. No other rashes were noted that day. Mild fever was reported at 1AM on 7/17/18, 99.2 temporal. Parent gave TYLENOL and symptoms resolved. No additional fevers. When child woke up 7/17/18, parents noticed a rash above the waist which was spreading to upper arms and head. At the time of the office visit, provider noted faint erythematous blanchable patch  about 1 cm. size and 1 inch from injection site on R. thigh and erythematous macules and papules on torso, back, upper arms, head. The provider's impression was that the rash was more likely to be viral versus hives. I called parent to follow-up today to see if symptoms have resolved, changed or worsened but I was unable to reach them.

This case was reported by a other health professional via call center representative and described the occurrence of constipation in a 2-year-old female patient who received BOOSTRIX for prophylaxis. On 5th May 2018, the patient received BOOSTRIX. On 5th May 2018, unknown after receiving BOOSTRIX, the patient experienced inappropriate age at vaccine administration. On an unknown date, the outcome of the inappropriate age at vaccine administration was unknown. Additional information was reported as follows: The healthcare professional did not have the lot number or expiry date for BOOSTRIX. The healthcare professional reported that they inadvertently administered a 2 year old patient with BOOSTRIX, which led to inappropriate age at vaccine administration. Follow-up information reported by the other healthcare professional on 11th July 2018 was as follows: On the date of reporting the healthcare professional called the representative and updated with information provided to them by the patient's mother. All the information provided by the healthcare professional in this call was documented. The reporter details were updated. The reporter also stated that the healthcare professional was a supervisor at a chain of urgent care facilities, not the child's pediatrician. The case was upgraded to serious for the event constipation with seriousness criteria as other serious (as per reporter). On 24th May 2018, the patient was vaccinated with BOOSTRIX. Eleven and a half weeks after the vaccination, the patient was diagnosed with high formaldehyde level by her pediatrician, constipation, hemorrhoids and behavioral changes of agitation and hitting. The patient was treated with by the pediatrician with probiotics and a detox soup. The outcome of the events constipation, hemorrhoids and behavioral changes was recovered. The VAERS details were updated. Healthcare professional also stated they were available via email for follow up questions if needed. Lab Comments: On an unknown date, the patient carried out formaldehyde test that showed high formaldehyde level.

This case was reported by a consumer via sales rep and described the occurrence of injection site pain in a 12-year-old female patient who received Men ACWY-CRM NVS (Meningitis ACWY vaccine (potential Menveo)) for prophylaxis. On 24th October 2013, the patient received the 1st dose of Meningitis ACWY vaccine (potential MENVEO). In October 2013, 1 day after receiving Meningitis ACWY vaccine (potential MENVEO), the patient experienced injection site pain, injection site lump, injection site warmth, injection site swelling, injection site erythema and local reaction. On an unknown date, the outcome of the injection site pain, injection site lump, injection site warmth, injection site swelling, injection site erythema and local reaction were recovered/resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the injection site pain, injection site lump, injection site warmth, injection site swelling, injection site erythema and local reaction to be related to Meningitis ACWY vaccine (potential MENVEO). Additional details were provided as follows: The case was reported by the mother of the patient. The patient got a meningitis vaccine to cover group A about 5 years ago. The mother does not know the brand name. The patient had pain at the injection site and a lot of swelling at the injection site. The patient developed a large red lump on her arm at the injection site. The lump was the size of a golf ball and very warm to the touch. It stayed like that for a couple of weeks. She started having those symptoms the next day after the injection. Reporter believed that her daughter had to go back to the office for a booster dose at 16 years.

Pt started vomiting about 5-10 minutes after receiving vaccine, pt was brought basin for fluids and was given EPIPEN. Pt complained of tummy aches and back pain. No other symptoms noticed. Pt threw up small amounts of bile for 20 min after receiving vaccine.

He had his shots on Thursday. He was fine Thursday and Friday. He was fussy during Friday night. He woke up early Saturday. He was fussy. I checked his temperature around 7:30am, no fever. I went to work. Picked him up at 12:15pm and he was warm and clingy. Went home and took his temperature and it was 102. Gave him 5ml of MOTRIN. I went and changed his diaper. Then I started to rock him, before I put him down to nap. He was fussy at first and then he closed his eyes to sleep. He then started having a seizure in my arms. I ran with him to get my phone and called 911. They had me put him on his left side. His tongue was hanging out of his mouth. He stopped breathing and turned blue. The 911 operator to me to start CPR. I started chest compressions. He started breathing. The EMT showed up. He was hospitalized overnight.
Pt began feeling faint. We sat her down. She drank some water and cool rag placed on neck and forehead.
Red lump about quarter sized. Still has lump under skin (6 days later today).

Initial information received on 10-Jul-2018 regarding an unsolicited valid non-serious case received from a nurse via phone. This case involves two months old female patient who received 0.5 ml dose of ACT-HIB (batch number, expiry date) intramuscularly in the left leg on an unknown date. Concomitant medications included PREVENAR (lot number U1822AA and expiry date 02 June 2019). It was actual medication error due to Wrong solution used in drug reconstitution as nurse administered the ACTHIB vaccine, but used the diluent for the MMR vaccine. This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error. Documents held by sender: none.
Potential Rotavirus associated Hematochezia. Had 2 MOS imms. on 7/13/18 and her Sxs developed on 7/16/18 with one time frank blood in stool. FOB positive. Parents aware. Child had loose stools.

Patient came in for 5-yo WCC. It was determined that patient would need the Varicella and MMR vaccines. These were ordered and drawn up and administered. When attempting to enter the NDC and LOT numbers it was noticed that the wrong order was put in for the MMR. What had ultimately been determined was that the PROQUAD and Varicella was given instead of just single MMR and Varicella.  These were both recorded in patient's chart. State was called to make sure of any potential adverse reactions and any instructions needed from them. VIS was given to mom. Dr. was informed. Mother called to let her know what the mistake and what to look for. Reassured mom that we did not expect any reaction since he had had already received the first dose and was already exposed. Asked her to keep an eye out for any swelling, redness, fever, unusual behaviors. She understood. Business coordinator notified to have one the varicella vaccine charge be removed and only charge for the PROQUAD. Will call in a week to see how patient is doing to be sure no reactions occurred.

Patient was administered HPV vaccine without issues/complaints. Escorted to waiting room, ambulating without assistance. Patient later stood and walked to front desk with mother, at which point he felt dizzy/lightheaded and was guided to the floor with assistance of staff. Patient placed in semifowlers position, BP was checked, cool compresses applied to head/neck, and patient offered sips of juice until recovered to a sitting position. Patient monitored for 15 minutes and released with mother after symptoms resolved. During recovery mother informed staff that patient's father has had syncopal episodes following injections in the past, recommended to patient and mother that in the future staff being informed about possibility of syncopal events.

Following the vaccine my daughter developed a whole body rash with severe itching that took 4 months to resolve. She was diagnosed with Gianotti Crosti syndrome and there was absolutely no treatment that could help her until it finally resolved on its own.
Patient developed fever of approximately 102.7f  and began to seize. Taken to Medical Center by ambulance. Parent gave Tylenol for fever.

After immunization, patient left the room walking and started wobbling and lost balance. MA and MD caught patient prior to falling. Patient was taken back to a room and laid down, vitals within normal limits, and gave patient apple juice. After lying down for a few minutes patient was feeling better. Patient did not loose consciousness or have a allergic reaction, MD states patient had a vaso-vagal/anxiety response after immunization.
Started with swelling on the thigh. Mother described the area as red, swollen and purple. Swelling of the thigh was started at the middle thigh and reached to the knee.

The patient did not have any pertinent medical history, drug reactions/allergies and was not taking any concomitant medications. On 02-DEC-2016, the patient received the first dose of ROTATEQ (dose, unit not reported) (lot# M029252, expiration date: 14-MAR-2018) orally, on 10-FEB-2017, the patient received second dose of ROTATEQ (dose, unit not reported) (lot# M031650, expiration date: unknown) orally for vaccination (immunization). On 05-APR-2017, the patient received the third dose of ROTATEQ (dose, unit not reported) (lot# M031650, expiration date: unknown) orally for vaccination (immunization) (Drug administered to patient of inappropriate age). On 22-NOV-2017, the patient went to an unspecified hospital and was diagnosed with intussusception. The patient sought medical attention.The patient was treated with an unspecified enema and air treatment. No lab diagnostics/studies were performed. The event intussusception was considered to be life threatening. No product quality complaint (PQC) was reported. Upon internal review, the event intussusception was determined to be medically significant. This is one of the two reports from the same source. Sender's Comments:  US-009507513-1807USA006275.

This case involves a 15 months old patient who was vaccinated with expired dose of ACT-HIB. The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided. Concomitant medications included DTAP for Immunisation. On 12-Jul-2018, the patient received a dose 4 Primary dose of suspect HIB (PRP/T) VACCINE lot U1796AA in the left thigh. It was an actual medication error due to expired dose of ACTHIB. The patient outcome is reported as Not Applicable for nurse gave an expired dose of ACTHIB. This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holders compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error. Documents held by sender: None.
Given in error, should have been DTaP.

Extensive swelling to right thigh and right proximal lower leg. Mild redness distal to thigh on day 3 resolved on day 4. No fever, no limping, well appearing child. Elevated CK, CRP, and ESR. CT demonstrates fasciitis.
Localized swelling, mass and lump, right upper limb requires KEFLEX, bacitracin and MOTRIN.

Within 2 hours of receiving vaccinations, the patient developed "spells" which involved sudden involuntary neck weakness (head drop). These spells are momentary but occur in clusters of 4-5, occurring within 1 minute of each other and clusters can occur multiple times per hour. Additionally, the patient had staring spells with decreased activity levels.

Patient did well when TDAP and MCV4 were given in left deltoid but as soon as I gave the HPV in right deltoid, patient's head fell back and his eyes rolled back and he started jerking movements that lasted a total of 5-7 seconds. He came to when I called his name. He was diaphoretic, pale, and felt nauseous. Mom stated that he had not eaten anything yet today and it was 10:50AM. I attempted to give him Kool-Aid that mom had in her possession and cookies that the clinic provides, but he immediately vomited both. I applied an ice pack to his neck and took vitals. His O2 was 98-100% and his heart rate was 65-70 and he was able to answer my questions, "What's your name, how old are you, what school do you go to" but after observing him for a few minutes, he remained lethargic and both mom and I agreed to call 911 and EMS came and transported him to the hospital.

Small rash at site of the injection on L thigh (papular, on an erythematous base) beginning July 17. Was very itchy. Progressed to inflamed erythematous 2x2cm area with excoriations/scabs from scratching when I saw her in clinic on July 20. Patient was also experiencing fever at visit on 7/20, to 100.4 per parent report. Also feeling fussy with low appetite. No other symptoms (cough, rhinorrhea, vomiting, diarrhea, rash elsewhere).
Vaccine given beyond recommended age in error, no adverse reaction occurred.
Vaccine given beyond age recommendation by error. No adverse reactions occurred.
Vaccine given beyond recommended age in error, no adverse reaction occurred.

Day two after the vaccines severe bump on thigh. Day three cough started, by day 5 after the vaccine was given, severe wheezing/fever. Confirmed pneumonia at doctors office 6 days after vaccine was given. Had to go to emergency room to get stronger nebulizer treatment and was prescribed antibiotics by doctor.
Spiked fever of 102.4, grunting respirations, retraction in breathing, red swollen face, red puffy eyes, heart rate 188, inconsolable, decrease in appetite.

After receiving the shot at 8:30 am on 7/20, my son's left shoulder began to swell and was hard and red around the injection site. He complained of itching throughout the day, but seemed otherwise fine. Throughout the day on 7/20, 7/21 and 7/22, his arm became so swollen and hard and the redness and swelling moved down to his elbow and around the back of his shoulder and arm. I took him to the Urgent Care to have him evaluated. It was determined that it was a significant negative reaction but there was no infection or cellulitis. They advised me to give him some Benadryl.
Fever of 101 degrees - 103 degrees.

This spontaneous report has been received from the medical assistant refers to 12 months old male patient. The patient's concurrent conditions, medical history, drug reactions and allergies were not reported. Concomitant therapies administered to them included sterile diluent (MRK) used to reconstitute the VARIVAX was properly stored. On 01-JUL-2018, the patient was vaccinated with improperly stored doses of VARIVAX (dose, units and frequency not reported) (lot # N035937 and expiration date: 18-DEC-2019), subcutaneously. The doses of VARIVAX were exposed to a temperature excursion of 6 degrees Fahrenheit (°F) to 14°F (also reported as "9F") for a time frame of 10 minutes; and of 15°F to 46°F (also reported as "25F") for 20 minutes. The temperature excursion was not detected by the Digital Data Logger. There was no previous temperature excursion either. No adverse effects or product quality complaints were reported. This is one of the multiple reports received from the same reporter.

On 05-FEB-2018, the patient was vaccinated with improperly stored dose of VARIVAX (lot # N022979, expiry 23-AUG-2019) for prophylaxis. No adverse effect was reported. The VARIVAX temperature excursion occurred on 14-DEC-2017 and 30-DEC-2017. On 14-DEC-2017, the vaccine was exposed to the temperature of 16.9 degree Fahrenheit (F) for 30 minutes. On 30-DEC-2017, the vaccine was exposed to the temperature of 6 degree Fahrenheit (F) to 14 degree F for 30 minutes. It was reported that the event was because of data logger. No product quality complaint was involved. This is one of the several reports received from the same reporter source. Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1802USA001558.

At approximately 7:30pm patient spiked a temperature of 103.3. Sure was writhing in pain and screamed when touched. The red lump in the right thigh got as large as a quarter in size, before falling into a large bruise after 72 hours. While the lump was large patient reacted very strongly to get leg being touched or bumped. She refused to crawl or to roll into her stomach putting pressure on that thigh.

This spontaneous report was received from a registered medical assistant refers to a 13 month old female patient. Patient received vaccines and was instructed to remain seated for 15 minutes after administration. Approx. 3 minutes after vaccines were given, patient became very pale and faint, followed by vomiting. A cool compress was placed on her neck and she was laid flat. Dr. was notified and she checked her immediately after this episode began. Patient remained lying flat for approx. 20 minutes and then was given a Coke to sip on. She was able to leave the office without difficulty.

As a first time mother, I should have been thoroughly explained each and every vaccination my two month old son was going to receive. However, I was not, and only given a white sheet with bare minimal information to read over on my own with no assistance from the medical professionals. My son was administered numerous vaccinations without me signing any type of paper work or receiving explanations on what type of adverse reactions to look for afterwards. Immediately after the vaccinations being administered my son cried and screamed of distress for almost 2 hours straight. After finally settling him down he refused to eat and he went into a deep sleep. After a 6 hour nap, I forced my son to wake up and his entire face and eyes were swollen immensely and had hives. He still would not eat (had been almost 9 hours since his last feeding). I immediately took my son to the emergency room where we stayed and were closely observed for hours and administered TYLENOL as his fever came down. He slept until we left the hospital, and were discharged with swelling and hives still present. After getting home, he still refused to eat and I administered more TYLENOL and he stayed asleep. He was not sleeping as he normally does, but rather a very deep sleep. He woke up at approximately 8 AM, and was still not interested in eating a bottle. I forced him to eat 2 oz as it had almost been 20 hours since his last feeding. He immediately projectile vomited all over himself, me, our clothes, and bed. I bathed him, he passed a large bowel movement, and he began to feel a tiny bit better. I got him into a new pediatrician and his hives and swelling were still noticeable. This pediatrician believes that he had a severe allergic reaction to vaccinations. However, he still has swelling and trouble with appetite and sleepiness over 24 hours later.

Post vaccination syncope within 30 seconds of administration, controlled descent to exam table without trauma or injury. Syncope with loss of bladder control. Loss of consciousness lasted for 1-2 minutes. Use of ammonia inhalants to help restore consciousness. Physical exam including neuro WNL after event. EKG sinus arrhythmia otherwise normal. Monitoring for 30 mins after patient normal and felt well. Mother instructed to watch for ALOC at home and go to ER if occurs. Mother is concerned if patient should get additional doses of menveo in the future.

Immediately after vaccination, patient became very sleepy and difficult to awaken. This was different from her normal behavior at that age. She was not interested in nursing and slept for 4 hours. When she woke up, she started screaming and was inconsolable. She had a high pitched screaming cry that lasted for 6 hours. She was very tense and would not make eye contact or soothe. We tried the following comfort measures with no decrease in symptoms: nursing, bottle, rocking her in a dark room, warm bath, cool packs to vaccination site. After about 6 hours she fell asleep, she was limp and did not wake up for 8 hours to nurse (not typical for her at this age). She had redness and swelling and tenderness to vaccination site for days. I called the pediatrician office the next day (1/22/2014) and spoke with a nurse who advised me to give TYLENOL and told me "it's not the vaccines, some babies just cry a lot."

Information has been received from a consumer, referring to a 12 months old male patient. The patient had ear tube insertion and penicillin allergy. There were no concomitant medications. On 14-AUG-2015, the patient was vaccinated with the last dose of PROQUAD (dose, strength, expiration date and lot# unknown), intramuscular, both for prophylaxis as scheduled (Incorrect route of drug administration). On an unknown date, the patient experienced "bruise much more easily". On 19-APR-2016, the patient experienced "covered in petechiae and bruising" and was taken to see an unspecified physician. The patient had a platelet count of 7000 (unit unspecified) and was admitted to hospital after being diagnosed with idiopathic thrombocytopenia. The patient had multiple intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) treatment, multiple courses of dexamethasone and prednisone. The patient had been admitted to the hospital on for separate occasions including for an unspecified time in the summer of 2017 for a brain bleed that required long term treatment. On unknown dates the patient had auto-immune testing, multiple computed tomography (CT) scans, Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI), platelet testing, Antinuclear Antibody (ANA) testing and blood draws 6-8 times per month. The outcome of idiopathic thrombocytopenia and "bruise much more easily" was reported as not recovered. The causality assessment was not reported. Upon internal review, idiopathic thrombocytopenia was determined to be medically significant.

A few minutes later the school nurse who was participating in the school registration event came and asked me to come check on the patient because she felt her color was "not right" and her lips were very pale. Pt. was sitting up at a table with her head down on her arms when I arrived, she talked to me but her skin color was very pale and her lips in fact had no color either. Mother carried patient to the nurses office where we laid her down and I elevated her feet and put cool wet towels on her forehead, because she felt very warm. After approx. 2 minutes the patients lip color started to return and shortly after that he color was just about back to normal. Pt. denied any pain or difficulty breathing, and her pulse ox was 99%, the school nurse took her other vitals (which I didn't get before we left) and stated other than her pulse being a little low they were normal. Pt never lost consciousness and was able to talk to me throughout the whole process, and her pulse rate also increased after a few minutes. Pt sucked on her lollipop and finished it as we sat together and also started playing with her sister again before they were discharged.

Pt received the Pediatric Hep A vaccine. I stepped away from imz booth to fill out form for mom and when I returned, mom said he isn't feeling well. Pt looked pale, head was hanging down, and eyes closed. I shook pt, called his name, and asked if he could hear me and only nodded his head. He was not very responsive. Checked his breathing and pulse, both were fine. After talking to him a little longer and he was still responding poorly, I decided to move pt to the floor and so I could prop up his legs. During this time I had pharmacy tech go get water for him and a pillow to put pt's head on. Mom also went to get a sugary soda. We also placed a cold rag on his forehead. After laying there a few more minutes and sipping some soda and water, pt became more responsive and talking more. Mom wanted to get him up, so I help stand him up and he seemed a little unsteady but able to walk. I advised for them to stay longer, but mom thought he was okay, just had become a little light headed. I told them if he did not continue to get better and got worse, to go to ER. So with Mom walking at his side, they left the store. I followed up with mom a couple of hours later and said pt was playing video games and doing well. She also said she was checking on him frequently.

She complained of aches and i took her temperature (something the doctors / nurses had not done at the office prior to her physical and administering her shot) She had a low grade fever of 99.5. Within an hour after that her temperature was 100.3. We treated with Tylenol. At that time I noticed a spot on her throat - something that looked like cocksakie. Her fever got worse, she had chills, and sweats. She's finally went to sleep. Next day ( 8/3/ 18) fever stayed above 100, treated her with Tylenol. Sores in mouth worsened. Slept on and off all day.  Day 3 - fever and sores still existing. Treating with Tylenol to keep fever down. Trouble swallowing fluids and eating foods. In a lot of pain everywhere.
101.8 fever that night, 100.4 next morning. Eczema flare (including new places on her body) starting the next morning,  and continuing to worsen.

My son fainted while still in the hallway of the doctor's office about 5 minutes after receiving the shots. He felt it coming so I was holding on to him trying to get to a chair when he fell to the ground. I was able to lay him down gently. He turned very pale. The nurse said it was a reaction to the HPV vaccine. She gave him a pedialite popsicle and he laid there for about 15 minutes and then he was ok.
No adverse symptoms occurred, but the RN was made aware that the KINRIX was given as DTAP dose #4, instead of as dose #5.

Vomiting and syncope initially, had subsequent cerebritis - unsteady gait, weakness. Evaluated by Neurology. Ag 3 2018 9:30AM Patient is here with chief complaint of ER F/U. Patient accompanied by her mother. Got hep B on 7/30 cried a lot right after, unusual for her. No other Sx. Vomited 3 times first night and that night seemed to have fainted - fell to the floor from a standing position, bumped her head on the floor after falling. Went to the ER, observed only, EKG normal. Vomited 2 times next AM, none in the last 24 hrs. No fever, no diarrhea, no cough, no cold Sx. Was totally fine before the shot. Was walking fine right after shot, but not walking well after fainting that night, has been wobbly, walking and will hold on to railing to go up stairs. Not sleeping more but sitting around the house. No rashes. No travel, no mosquito bites or tick bites noted.
