This initial spontaneous report was received via an online news article. The article described an infant who suffered a severe reaction to the MMR vaccine (manufacturer not specified). The infant was a one year old healthy baby girl who was already walking and climbing. On 13-FEB-2013, she received vaccinations for MMR (manufacturer not specified), hepatitis A (manufacturer not specified), Hib (manufacturer not specified), PREVNAR, and varicella (manufacturer not specified).  That evening, the mother noticed the baby was irritable and feverish. After a call to the doctor, the mother was advised to give the baby TYLENOL and BENADRYL. The fever continued for several days and on the evening before the baby's scheduled pediatrician visit (exact date not specified but considered to be in 2013), the baby began having seizures. She was rushed to the Emergency Room (ER) where she went into cardiac and respiratory arrest and doctors placed her on a ventilator. The seizures and cardiac arrest left the baby with severe brain injury, encephalopathy, cortical vision impairment, truncal hypotonia, and kidney failure. After months of treatment at the hospital, she finally went home but her disabilities require specialized medical care and supervision around the clock for the rest of her life. The settlement would pay for the baby's constant high-level medical care for the rest of her life. The author of the article went on to say that the government and "Big Pharma" consistently tell the public that vaccines are safe and effective.  However, "the fact that vaccines kill and injure people, including young babies and infants, is not a fact that is in dispute". The outcome of cardiac and respiratory arrest was considered resolved. It was unknown whether the irritability, fevers, and seizures continued. The outcome of severe brain injury, encephalopathy, cortical vision impairment, hypotonia, and kidney failure were considered not resolved as the patient required specialized medical care and supervision around the clock for the rest of her life. Causality assessment was considered related to MMR for all events. Causality assessment was not specifically stated for the other vaccines. Brain injury, seizures, cardiac arrest, respiratory arrest, encephalopathy, cortical vision impairment, hypotonia, and kidney failure were considered disabling as the baby now required medical care around the clock for the rest of her life. Upon internal review, brain injury, cardiac arrest, respiratory arrest, seizures, encephalopathy, cortical vision impairment, and renal failure were considered to be medically significant. This is one of two reports from the same reporter (see case # 1509USA014655 discussing autism in boys in the same article). Additional information is not expected as there was no contact information.

Pt. had all 3 immunizations while seated in a chair. Pt. did not appear anxious. After all shots were given, pt. remained looking at her phone and didn't report feeling any different. After approximately 2 minutes, pt. dropped the phone and began to slump out of the chair. Staff and pt.'s family caught her and lowered her to a seated position on the floor. Her eyes appeared to roll back and she went limp.  After about 10 seconds, she looked up and said, "What happened?" She felt dizzy and nauseous for the next few minutes and felt like she was going to vomit. She was given a cool wash cloth and had a fan on her. She stood up and was encouraged to sit in the chair for a few minutes. Pt. c/o headache. She was encouraged to lie down on the cot with her feet elevated slightly. She remained there for about 10 minutes and then felt well enough to leave with her family. Pt. reports she only had applesauce for breakfast that morning. Mom reported that this is the first time she has reacted to vaccinations like this.

This case was reported by a other health professional via patient support programs and described the occurrence of fainting in a 12-year-old male patient who received BOOSTRIX (batch number 4P9CL, expiry date unknown) for prophylaxis. Co-suspect products included MENVEO (batch number MI7077, expiry date unknown) for prophylaxis. On 21st August 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of BOOSTRIX and the 1st dose of MENVEO. On 21st August 2018, less than a day after receiving BOOSTRIX and MENVEO, the patient experienced fainting. On 21st August 2018, the outcome of the fainting was recovered/resolved. The reporter considered the fainting to be probably related to BOOSTRIX and MENVEO. Additional details were provided as follows: This case was received from other health professional via the vaccine patient assistant program. The patient fainted for approximately 5 seconds following the administration of BOOSTRIX and MENVEO. The reporter was unsure which vaccine caused the reaction. The reporter advised that oxygen was started as it dropped to 93 and slowly went up. The events did not require surgical medical intervention. The patient was not admitted to the hospital overnight or prolong an existing hospitalization. The health care professional did not consider the event as life threatening event. The health care professional did not consider the events to result in persistent or significant disability or incapacity. The event did not resulted in congenital anomaly or birth defect. In Summer of 2014, patient had tingling and numbness of left arm and hand. A CT scan was done and reported as "normal." Two years later, it was discovered that that test was not normal. In June of 2016, patient had unsteady gait, involuntary muscular movements, and slurred speech due to multifocal strokes caused by cerebral central nervous system vasculitis. She was in the hospital for a week, received daily steroid infusions, and after beginning treatment to hopefully protect her reproductive eggs, she began monthly infusions of chemotherapy in the hospital along with daily steroids. After 7 chemo infusions, she began oral chemo. The chemo lasted for about a year and a half and she was on steroids for a year. The steroids caused high blood pressure while taking 3 BP pills at a time, elevated thyroid levels, and elevated pressure in her eyes. Her doctor prescribed calcium to protect her bones from the steroids. Because of all of the calcium intake, she suffered from kidney stones twice. The first one only required an emergency room visit. The second one required surgery and a hospital stay. Even though she was taking the calcium, the steroids caused avascular necrosis of the femoral head (hip bone) and she had to have a surgery called core decompression and bone grafting. She was on crutches for a month. The orthopedic doctor said she'll probably have to have a hip replacement in the future and she has constant hip pain. Last summer, it was discovered that the vasculitis caused moyamoya of her brain. She had 2 surgeries (one of each side of her brain) called pail synangosis (a grafting of blood vessels). She was weaned from the chemo in June, went for a follow up visit with the neurologist last week, and the neurologist said he thinks the vasculitis is back, based on her symptoms of headaches, involuntary muscular movements, and weakness again. She has had 2 steroid infusions in 2 weeks. The doctor recommended chemotherapy again, but my daughter doesn't want to start that all over again. She said she would rather die. She's having mental issues now, such as anxiety, depression, and hopelessness. She has seen a neuropsychologist for these feelings and is trying different meds to hopefully combat these feelings. Her lifelong dream was to become a nurse, but because of her limitations, that is not possible for her now.

Took to doctor to check - he said yes, it's a reaction to the vaccine. It was not infected and he should be better by Tuesday (which is 6 days from the shot!). Last night (8/31) he had diarrhea and today (9/1) he has a terrible headache and can't sit up or stand without throbbing pain. He has now missed 2 days of school because of this vaccine.

This case involves an 11-week-old male subject who developed congestion and breathing problem during the study participation. The subject's medical history was not reported. The subject's concomitant therapies were not reported. On 23 July 2018, seven days after receiving an intramuscular dose of blinded therapy in the upper right thigh (dose number: 1367126), the subject developed congestion and breathing problem. The subject also received non-investigational products i.e. an intramuscular dose of PENTACEL in the upper left thigh (batch number: C5461AA), an intramuscular dose of PREVNAR 13 in the lower left thigh (batch number: T88778), an oral dose of ROTATEQ vaccine (batch number: N021101) and an intramuscular dose of ENGERIX B in the lower right thigh (batch number: 52X7T) on 16 July 2018. The event appeared after visit 1. On an unspecified date the subject was hospitalized. The event was MAAE. The lab data was not reported. The subject had no corrective treatment. The event congestion and breathing problem was resolved on 09 August 2018. According to the investigator, the event was not related to the study vaccine or trial procedures. Relationship to non-investigational products according to investigator: not reported. Relationship to investigational product according to company: not reportable. Relationship to non-investigational products according to company: not reportable. The serious adverse event did not lead to the termination of the subject from the study. List of documents held by sender: none. Sender's Comments: Follow-up information received on 08 September 2018: A 11-week-old male subject who developed congestion, seven days after receiving a dose of study product. Based on the available information, the sponsor assesses the event as not related to study product or trial procedure, in agreement with the investigator.

From Derm Note: Dermatology- Within 3-4 days post-vaccine, patient developed discrete pruritic pink papules on his head/neck which gradually progressed to his upper trunk. Patient was then seen in ED last night, as lesions progressed to his lower trunk and legs. He was seen by Infectious Disease and started on PO Clindamycin at that time (1 dose so far). MOP states patient's only other medication is PO BENADRYL PRN for itching (approximately 2-3 times per day).  She states he has otherwise been health, no significant past medical history. Derm T-con-.Called and spoke with mother of patient (MOP) regarding patient's biopsy result showing psoriasiform and spongiotic dermatitis. Patient is not contraindicated to receive TDAP/Meningitis vaccine in the future.

Initial information received on 22-Sep-2018 regarding an unsolicited valid serious case issued from a literature article (extracted from VAERS). Literature Abstract: Aim: To characterize cases of myocarditis (MC) and pericarditis (PC) recorded in the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS). Methods: Cases were extracted from VAERS (2011-2015) and assessed for causality using standardized WHO algorithm. Disproportionality analysis was performed through reporting odds ratio (ROR) with 95%CI. Database was also searched. Results: In VAERS, 199 cases of MC or PC were collected, among which 149 reported smallpox vaccine. The remaining were: 15 cases in 'YOUNGER GROUP' (YG; b18 years old) and 35 in 'OLDER GROUP' (OG; N18 years old). Main reported vaccines were against Human Papilloma Virus (n = 6) in YG and influenza (n = 16) in OG. Causality always resulted "undeterminate" for YG, whereas either "undetermined" (30 cases) and "correlated" (3 cases) for OG. Statistically significant ROR was found in YG for meningococcal vaccine (ROR = 3.55; 95%CI = 1.23-10.24) and in OG for thyphoid vaccine (11.13; 7.73-16.03), Japanese encephalitis vaccine (8.54; 2.7-27.01), anthrax (25.5; 18.8-34.5), and, as expected, smallpox (71.88; 49.25-104.89). In database, 91 articles were found: positive/possible causality was frequently reported. Conclusions: MC and PC after immunization appear extremely rare; only in very few cases can a role of vaccine be actually identified. Signals for vaccines against typhus, Japanese encephalitis, anthrax and meningococcus warrant monitoring. Also had meningitis vaccine.....body aches (hurt to walk or ride in vehicle) low fever to high fever of 103.8. Skin rash, severe headache, nausea, dizziness, sleeping constantly, dehydration, stomach pain wouldn't eat or drink hardly. Blood shot eyes.

Localized allergic reaction. Flu shot given 9/27/18 Rt thigh. Patient developed swelling 9/29/18 with erythema skin reported by mother. Seen 10/1/18 swelling site of shot, no erythema, no tenderness. Swelling and itching. Oral steroid given. F/U 10/4/18. Pt was started on prednisone/and BENADRYL. F/U in 2 days. 10/4/18 child doing well per mother. She cannot come for appt. Pt has previous H/O allergic rash to metals. Pt has previously received flu shot without any problem.

Skin Normal except as noted 13.5cm by 11.5cm area of erythema surrounding central punctate injection site on left vastus lateralis. Warm to touch with swelling at site of erythema. No streaking on extremity. No involvement of hip or knee joints. Covering for cellulitis with KEFLEX today. Advised using cool compresses and ok to continue ibuprofen and BENADRYL. Area of erythema and warmth marked with a pen.
Mom called 10/5/18 to state patient had 102 temp, with body aches and chills on 9/29/18 last until 9/30/18 (lasted 24 hrs) then was fine.
Patient was diagnosed with erythema multiforme. I was instructed to give him BENADRYL and watch for further complications.
The evening of the vaccine my daughter had 103 fever, given TYLENOL and MOTRIN, woke with hives the next morning.

Her right thigh was bright red, hot-to-touch, very swollen with a large, hard knot under the injection site within 15 hours. It has now been 48 hours, the redness, swelling, and fever has spread further out. I have tried cold compresses, topical BENADRYL, and TYLENOL. I have contacted the Dr's office 2 times with concerns and provided a picture. They have told me it is a normal reaction and should clear up in 5-7 days. I have talked to other medical professionals and after seeing her leg, they do not think it is normal.

Infant developed watery diarrhea stools greater than 10 times daily on the day after vaccinations.  No fever, no blood observed in the stools. Still continuing to have frequent watery and loose stools greater than 6 times daily on 10/3/2018 (10 days after vaccinations given). Normal stools for infant are 1-2 times daily. No change in diet or foods (mostly breast fed, but occasional formula supplements).
No events or outcomes at this time.

Patient got the vaccination, stood up and fainted, hitting his head. Mother of the patient said she is a nurse practitioner and stated that she did not want any additional follow-up and took the child home.

Baby was babbling and starting to put together CVC sounds before MMR vaccine. Within two days he stopped at sounds. Evaluation at 18 months by county eating intervention program put him at the speech level of a 9 month old. Speech therapy begin at approximately 18 months, still working hard to regain speech.

My child has been screaming nonstop since 5 hours after the shots. It's been 32 hours and if she isn't eating or sleeping, she is screaming. Generally I can put her down in a bouncer or a play mat but she will not have any of that today. She is screaming even when held, walked around, bounced etc. No fever but TYLENOL does. I thing.

Approximately 10 mins post vaccination, patient started feeling dizzy and faint and stated her arm felt tingly. BP=110/86, P=80, No medication was given at clinic site. Patient remained dizzy sitting in chair and parent requested to call EMS. Vitals remained stable and patient was transported to Hospital by rescue. Followed up with patient and was told symptoms had totally resolved.

In late November 2015 she developed a UTI.  After treatment from antibiotics follow up urine tests indicated large amounts of blood and protein in urine. We were referred to urology in January 2016 and finally nephrology by May 2016.

This spontaneous report was received from a physician and refers to a 15-year-old male patient. The patient's concurrent condition included environmental allergy and fatigue. His medical history included nasal congestion. Historical medications included MOTRIN PM for allergy and MOTRIN IB SINUS for nasal congestion. The patient had several FLUZONE vaccinations in past flu seasons. The patient did not take any concomitant medications. On 11-JUN-2018, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of GARDASIL 9 intramuscularly, lot# R003245, expiration date: 16-NOV-2020 and with FLUZONE lot# UT6258NA, both into left arm (doses and routes of administration were not provided). On the same day, the patient experienced syncope after receiving the vaccinations. No drug treatment prescription was required for the event. The outcome of syncope was reported as recovered on an unknown date in 2018. The relatedness between the events and GARDASIL 9 was not provided. This is one of two reports received from the same source. Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1809USA005320.
MOC noticed right arm was hot to the touch and red with mild swelling. Pt diagnosed with cellulitis.

Redness and swelling noted around site of vaccine one day after administration. Redness and swelling were worse the second day after vaccine given. Mother reports yellow drainage from vaccine site.  Mother gave pt Benadryl. Mother brought pt to clinic 3 days after vaccine given. Mild swelling and redness around site to right thigh. Tender to touch. Mother reports pt had a fever after vaccines were given. Fever for one day.

Patient walked out of the office with her mother after receiving the vaccines. They had stopped at the front desk to ask for a note for school and a clerical staff called to report that the client ''passed out''. When I saw her she was standing, and her mother was holding her tight in a hug. When asked what happened, she said she got dizzy and fell on the floor. She denied hitting her head. Placed her on a chair. She admitted that she did not eat any breakfast. The mother stated that she was planning to treat her to a breakfast at a restaurant after getting the shots. A pouch of juice was given. No other problem noted. The client verbalized feeling better and got up, went out via the elevator with a steady gait.

Received vaccines 10/1/18. Patient developed fever on of 10/3/18. Tmax 101. Mom gave Motrin before bed that night. Checked on him before she went to bed and his temp was 99. Next morning he was found dead in crib. No blankets, stuffed animals in crib. Autopsy found no signs of trauma. Tox screen, tissue samples still pending.

Patient received his flu shot around 9:15am on Friday Oct 5th. He did well with the injection and went to school for the day. At pick up, around 5:30pm, he was noted to be feeling unwell. He was febrile upon temperature check at home by 6:00pm to 101.3F.  His fever persisted through Saturday afternoon Oct 6th with minimal other symptoms. Upon waking up on Sunday morning, Oct 7th, he had a prominent red rash (erythematous confluent maculopapular rash) over his face with some periorbital swelling and involvement of cheeks and ears bilaterally. He also had a rash over the dorsal and palmar sides of both hands. He received loratadine and BENADRYL with some improvement but the rash persisted all day into Monday Oct 8th. By Monday, he had a noticeable rash on his legs/feet as well. His torso and back were much less affected. No oral lesions or hand/foot lesions were noted.

Fever was 105 and I was alternating MOTRIN and TYLENOL and also giving lukewarm baths. Injection site swelled up to 5-6 inches and was hot to the touch. This went on for 3 days. Fever finally broke and his leg swelling started to go down

Client's mother contacted clinic on Friday 10/05/2018 stating that patient didn't go to school today because she has been having following symptoms since received TDaP vaccine yesterday: 15 minutes after getting her vaccine, in the car she started having tingling, numbness in her left arm, cramps and tingling in both legs, back and neck pain. When asked about her immunizations previously, mother stated that she had her first vaccines at age 3 and was given only 1 vaccine at a time and didn't have any reactions or side effects and her vaccines were spaced. On day of vaccination client was advised to wait in waiting room for 15 minutes per our policy, she was not complaining of any problems right after receiving TDaP vaccine and stated that she expected to have more pain. Mother was instructed to contact PMD regarding this problem, or go to local ER if client's condition worsens, and also let our clinic know how her daughter is doing. On October 9th mother was contacted to f/u on her daughter's condition and she stated that patient was feeling better and went to school today.

This spontaneous report from a consumer was retrieved from an online article and refers to a 7-month-old female patient. The patient was a healthy baby with normal physical and cognitive development before vaccination. On an unknown date (reported as when the patient was 6-month-old), the patient was vaccinated with first doses of ROTATEQ, oral (lot #, expiration date and dose were not provided), RECOMBIVAX HB (dose, route of administration, lot # and expiration date were not provided), PREVNAR 13 (dose, route of administration, lot # and expiration date were not provided) and Hib conj vaccine (unspecified carrier), diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified), poliovirus vaccine inactivated (unspecified), tetanus toxoid (manufacturer unknown) (dose, route of administration, lot # and expiration date were not provided). On an unknown date, after vaccination, the patient became fussy and lethargic. She also suddenly became unresponsive, both mentally and physically and she could not hold her head up right or move her arms and appeared to display symptoms of a stroke. Due to these events, the patient was brought to the emergency room and had computed tomography (CT) scan and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) performed (results were not provided). On the same day, the patient was sent home and referred to a pediatrician. On an unknown date (reported as by next morning), the patient was unable to sit and appeared paralyzed in several parts of her body. Due to this event, the patient was hospitalized and placed in intensive care unit (ICU) on breathing machine and received unspecified steroids as treatment. The patient was in the ICU for 8 days. On an unknown date, the patient had bleeding in her brain and additionally was diagnosed with transverse myelitis spinal cord disease. On unknown dates, the patient experienced trouble walking, numbness in her feet, headaches and constant back pain. She would have episodes where she appeared stuck for 30 to 45 minutes. In 2015 (reported as last year at the time of the report), the patient was diagnosed with Chiari malformation. In October 2015, the patient was vaccinated with the second round of immunizations with 5 in 1 combo vaccine DTaP-Hep B-IPV and haemophilus influenzae type B vaccine and the patient's health worsened after that. On an unknown date, the patient also experienced severely damaged vision, speech impediments, difficulty communicating, behavioral problems and bowel movement problems (because of which the patient was forced to use diapers). The outcome of lethargy, being unresponsive, having symptoms of stroke, being paralyzed, bleeding in brain, transverse myelitis, spinal cord disease, numbness in feet, constant back pain, Chiari malformation and bowel movement problems was not reported. The outcome of chronic headaches, irritability, severely damaged vision, speech impediments, difficulty communicating and behavioral problems was reported as not recovered. The outcome of being unable to walk was reported as recovered on an unknown date. The relatedness between the events and suspect vaccines was not reported. Upon internal review, the events of having symptoms of a stroke, being paralyzed, bleeding in brain, transverse myelitis spinal cord disease and Chiari malformation were considered to be medically significant.

At 4:00 AM the morning following his vaccinations, patient drank an 8 oz. formula bottle as usual, but immediately projectile vomited it up. This was his first time to vomit in his life. We stopped formula. At 7:30 he vomited again, this time a bright yellow bile type vomit. We began giving PEDIALYTE as the pediatric nurse at his clinic recommended over the phone. He continued to vomit at 9:20 AM, 10:30 AM, and 5:30 PM. Around 8 PM, after having no wet diapers since 9:00 AM, I took him to the ER at Hospital to be treated for dehydration upon the suggestion of his pediatric nurse. He was given an IV for fluids and ZOFRAN for nausea. His vomiting continued into the next day, but on a smaller scale. The following 7 days he was lethargic, had a low appetite, was not smiling as usual, and was pale. On 10/14/18 we visited his pediatrician for a follow-up and after vomiting that morning. She examined him and said his stomach exam was clear. He has not been the same since his vaccinations: he still has a low appetite, he is still vomiting about once a day, he is not smiling as usual, and he is still fussy and seems not to feel well. No one in the house has gotten a stomach bug, which leads me to think this is not a virus, but a reaction to his vaccines since it began just hours after.

Several lymph nodes on her jaw/neck swelled up really big. She got a fever and was having headaches is when I noticed the lymph nodes a few days after the vaccine. After several days the fever and headaches went away. Her lymph nodes didn't go down though. After about a month they started to get bigger so I rushed her to the ER. They didnt know what caused the swelling, just told me to go back to my pediatrician after a couple weeks if they don't go down. We waited about 2-3 weeks and no change. I then took her to her pediatrician. I asked him if the HPV vaccine could of caused the swelling (with fever/headaches for a few days) since it happened right after the vacccine. He said, "there's no way the vaccine caused it", but didn't know what did. Just told us to wait a few more weeks and the swollen lymph nodes should go down. After about 3-4 weeks they went back down to normal. Since the doctor immediately denied it having any connection but now that I've researched and put it all together I know that's what caused it bc it was so soon after the vaccine.

She received her shot around noon and by dinnertime, her leg was swollen, her fever was 103, she wouldn't eat, very fussy. This is common so it was upsetting but not worrisome. I treated her with cold compresses and children's MOTRIN. However, that evening she awoke after going to bed and cried a piercing, screaming cry for six straight hours. I emailed her doctor who said he was sleep to hear it and brushed off my concerns, saying the vaccines do more good than harm. MOTRIN did nothing. Her crying continued off and on for two weeks. She woke crying frequently at night. Her fever lasted five days. She did not want to eat or play. She was withdrawn and definitely not herself for at least two weeks and my husband and I were very concerned. She honestly seemed like a different child. It was incredibly upsetting and worrisome and I hated that the doctors office was more concerned with making sure I brought her back for more shots than making sure she was actually okay. I have not done any vaccines since.

On Monday July 16, 2018 at 4:30pm, patient received a HIB-PRP-T (ACTHIB, HIBERIX) 0.5mL intramuscular vaccine to the left thigh. On Sat. July 21 he woke up screaming, and was not consoled easily. We took him in to see Dr that afternoon and he was diagnosed as "Fussy Child" since there were no outward symptoms. That evening he came down with a fever of 103F that persisted on and off for 3 days, while taking ibuprofen and TYLENOL. He had a follow up with MD on Mon. July 23 and was diagnosed with "Viral Illness". He started showing a mild limp on Tues. July 24th and it didn't resolve, so he was seen by MD on Fri. July 27, and he was diagnosed with Transient Synovitis. He recommended we give Ibuprofen and TYLENOL for the pain and come back if not resolved in 2-4 days. Patient's walking regressed to crawling so he was seen by MD on Tues. July 31. She ordered an xray and labs that day but based on results, continued with the diagnosis of Transient Synovitis. On Sat. Aug. 4 the fever returns so he was taken to Hospital. He was admitted and received an MRI on Sunday Aug. 5 that confirmed acute myelitis of the lumbar region and corresponding diskitis. Patient was released from the hospital on Wed. Aug. 8, and was treated at home with cephalexin 125mg susp 4 times daily for 6 weeks. During this time he saw MD and MD from Infectious Disease for the remaining treatments, receiving weekly lab checks to ensure he was improving. There was no known trauma that caused the myelitis. The problems began 5 days following the Hib vaccination.

Patient went home after the vaccine and called our office and spoke with the NP reporting the symptoms. Initial call was made at 12:50 PM where symptoms were reported: patient woke up projectile vomiting, she was more fussy than usual, parents were not sure if she had a fever but they denied that she had difficulty breathing, they reported 3 episodes of emesis. Per the physicians orders we advised the Parents were advised to come into the office to be examined, and also to give a dose of BENADRYL before coming in (Parents were unable to give dose as they were en route to office- dose to be given at the office). The parents where the doctor examined a pinpoint rash on her trunk. NO swelling of lips, tongue, difficulty breathing, drooling, diarrhea or further emesis once at the office. She was given a dose of BENADRYL 12.5 mg/5 ml) (3.75 ml) and transported to the hospital via parents despite doctor's recommendation to go via ambulance and administer EPIPEN before travelling there. In the ED, patient appeared well with no distress, no respiratory distress and negative for any abnormalities on physical exam. The rash mildly erythematous macular rash mainly distributed over the trunk. Because there were 2 systems involved (GI and SKIN, the child was given epinephrine 0.1 mg injection and ZANTAC in the ER Epinephrine injection given at 3:49 PM no 10/26/18. They observed her for two hours and then discharged her home with BENADRYL, ZANTAC and ORAPRED. Dr. talked to the parents today and received an update that she is better today, no fever, no vomiting, almost seems to be back at baseline. Reinforced the continuation of medication that was given from the ED, and a follow-up made for Monday to be seen at Pediatrics. Told to call 911 or our answering service over the weekend if any symptoms occur. Parents verbalized understanding and had no further questions or concerns at that time. (Patient does have a known suspected egg allergy and per recommendations did receive the Flu Vaccine on this day).

Mom called 9/24/18 reported R thigh with red, pin point rash at injection site and swollen area size of baseball denies hot to touch, no itch, doesn't seem to bother him. Pt developed slightly tender raised area right ant thigh where HAV given 24h after injection; purple reddish, raised; now fading and flattened out; no other SXs. Redness and swelling at site of injection. Low grade fever and vomiting. TYLENOL, applying ice, and Ibuprofen. Pt was seen in office on 5/18/17 and was given prescriptions for KEFLEX and Prednisolone.

Mom reported patient had vague sense of not feeling well, said heart rate increased to 186 bpm and she vomited. She was taken into ED and given IV fluids with HR 150 which then normalized and sent home from ED. She awoke the next morning at home and was back to normal.
11/29/17 patient was dx with chicken pox.

Patient had seizure like action about 3 minutes after her flu shot, in her seat, and lasted about 3-5 seconds. Once she came out of the event she did not remember what happened and was stated she was "okay". Had patient sit down for 15 minutes to monitor her. Checked on patient every 5 minutes with no episodes that continued. Patient parents did not want to call 911 and did not want her take her to the ER, but wanted to monitor her. Discussed with patient's parents that they do not have a new PCP due to them recently moving here. Management was informed and parents did not want to file an incident report. After 15 minutes elapsed parents opted to go about their time. Will follow up with parents tomorrow. Follow up with patient, mother states they took her to urgent care the same night and it was diagnosed as fainting with seizure like action. They are not concern and patient went to school.

Patient went to ER who reported that they had a Arthus reaction. Was told by ER to take ibuprofen especially but also acetaminophen as needed for discomfort. They do not expect to have fever or increasing redness after 48 hr. If she does return to ER.
3-4 cm round swollen area at injection site, 100.3 fever, headache.

Hives tracking from injection site to left scapula, associated itching within 2 hours from injection; following morning faint rash extended to right scapula. This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of fever in a 12-week-old male patient who received PEDIARIX for prophylaxis. Concurrent medical conditions included gastroesophageal reflux (diagnosed when patient was three weeks of age.) and milk allergy. Concomitant products included CARAFATE and PREVACID. On 16th October 2018, the patient received the 1st dose of PEDIARIX. In October 2018, less than a day after receiving PEDIARIX, the patient experienced fever, esophageal reflux aggravated, appetite impaired, injection site warmth, injection site induration, injection site pain, mucous diarrhea, injection site swelling and feeling of warmth. On 22nd October 2018, the patient experienced lymphocyte count increased, viral infection, granulocyte count decreased and monocyte count decreased. On an unknown date, the outcome of the fever, esophageal reflux aggravated, appetite impaired, injection site warmth, injection site induration, lymphocyte count increased, injection site pain, viral infection, granulocyte count decreased, monocyte count decreased, mucous diarrhea, injection site swelling and feeling of warmth were unknown. It was unknown if the reporter considered the fever, esophageal reflux aggravated, appetite impaired, injection site warmth, injection site induration, lymphocyte count increased, injection site pain, viral infection, granulocyte count decreased, monocyte count decreased, mucous diarrhea, injection site swelling and feeling of warmth to be related to PEDIARIX. Additional details were reported as follows: The reporter's son had a history of gastroesophageal reflux that was diagnosed when he was three weeks of age. It was well controlled with medication. The morning after receiving the PEDIARIX vaccine he had a temperature of 99.4 degrees. His reflux started acting up, and he was not eating well. When the reporter went to change his son's diaper that afternoon, the injection site on his leg was hot, hard, swollen, and painful to the touch. A few hours after that, he had watery diarrhea with mucus. The injection site continued to get harder and more swollen. The reporter took him to the doctor that night and she was told to put cold compresses on the injection site 4-5 times a day and come back in two days. Patient was given 4 months vaccinations at the pediatricians office and later went down for a nap. When the patient woke up she presented with oscillating rhythmic jerking. Parents took patient to Hospital, where they ran test and later said she had a myoclonic seizure disorder. They prescribed vitamins and seizure medications (KEPPRA and ONFI). After her one week hospital stay patient came home where her jerks got worse and presented more like seizures. Patient was weaned off of seizure medications and when she was 9 months old she had a 5 plus minute seizure. Patient was taken to the hospital where more tests were run and she was put back on KEPPRA. Once back at home seizures looked more like the jerks from before and Patient started therapy. Patient was then taken to another Hospital for a second opinion. At hospital the neurologist stated that she did not have a seizure disorder after looking at an EEG their hospital performed. The neurologist also did an MRI that stated that her ventricles appeared bright asking the parents if mother had a normal pregnancy, if patient lost oxygen at any point, or if patient had a cardiac event. Mother had a normal pregnancy and the patient did not lose oxygen or have a cardiac event to the parents or doctors knowledge.

This spontaneous report as received from a registered nurse refers to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient's pertinent medical history, drug reaction or allergies and concomitant therapies were unknown. In approximately April 2018 (reported as an unspecified date since 03-APR-2018), the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of VARIVAX (lot # N009768, expiry date: 24-MAR-2019) which was reconstituted for prophylaxis with properly stored sterile diluent (MERCK) (lot # N021894, expiry date unknown). Dosing details were not reported. No adverse effects were reported. The temperature excursion occurred at a temperature range between -14 degrees Celsius (°C) to -10°C (-13.3C) for a time frame of 10 minutes. No previous temperature excursion occurred. The call was because of a data logger. No adverse effects were reported. Product quality complaint (PQC) was not involved. This case was considered to be non-valid due to lack of patient identifiers. A phone call was placed to the registered nurse on 26-SEP-2018, a request was made for patient identifiers and for the dates of vaccination. Upon receipt of the follow up information, the case has now become valid after updating the patient identifiers. Follow up information has been received from the nurse on 26-SEP-2018. The nurse reported that a 11 minute temperature excursion of - 13.3 degrees Celsius occurred on 03-APR-2018. All other temperatures were in range and average temperatures remained stable. The vaccine in the freezer at the time of excursion was PROQUAD of lot # N015623 with an expiry date of 15-NOV-2018 and VARIVAX of lot # N022981 with an expiry date of 23-AUG-2019. No doses of PROQUAD was given since excursion. It was reported that one dose of VARIVAX was administered. No adverse vaccine reactions reported. The nurse reported that this was a "supported temperature excursion" since it was between - 10 and - 14 (Units unspecified) for a period of 11 minutes and that supply could remain in stock and was viable. 10/30/2018: After receiving his immunizations, patient was angry and cried briefly. He suddenly then became cyanotic around his mouth and limp. He had not tonic-clonic movements during this event. Event was witnessed by MPH-MA and patient. Dr was notified within seconds of the event. Upon Dr's arrival, patient was pale. He was awake, but sleepy. Within 30 seconds to a minute, his color began to improve, and he returned to being the smiling infant that he was before his shots. His lungs remained clear. No tachypnea. No retractions. Normal heart sounds without murmur. Normal rate and rhythm. Brachial and femoral pulses 2/4 and symmetric. CRT brisk. PERRL. EOMI after the event. Normal tone after the event. Movement remained symmetrical. His oxygen saturation and pulse WNL (noted below). Review of his history with his mother revealed that he has no history of this activity with he 2 month old immunizations. He doesn't cry often, but when he does, he sometimes does breath hold briefly. He had never lost consciousness before today. Pulse: 97 on 10/30/2018 Oxygen Sat: 100 % on 10/30/2018. 11/1/18 @ 0807: Spoke with mother. She said patient is doing good! He was a little fussy Tuesday night (10/30/18) but she thinks it was just from getting the shots. Yesterday (10/31/18) he was back to his normal happy self. Final diagnosis was breath holding spell.

8 cm circular well-circumscribed area of mild edema and erythema around the influenza vaccination site. It is not tender. He moves his shoulder well but has some mildly increased discomfort with movement. There is no streaking anywhere. There is no fluctuance. He has full sensation throughout the left upper extremity. Differential diagnosis includes moderate local reaction to influenza vaccine versus cellulitis. He likely had a similar toxic local reaction last year that was more severe than his current. Should the pain increase or he develop any fevers or of any questions or concerns that this may be more of an infectious scenario that he should return for reevaluation. For now, recommended symptomatic management with ice and rest and observation.

Per father, HE believes that ever since the patient received the HPV vaccine, she has not been herself. He reports that her sleeping pattern changed first and she complained that she was not feeling quite like herself. Two weeks after the vaccine was given she started with vomiting and mild diarrhea. Those symptoms resolved but again at the time he expressed his concern that this was due to the vaccine despite discussions of viral illnesses that could be present. Three days later she started complaining about a sore throat, she was seen at ER and diagnosed with Mononucleosis and Strep Throat. Despite treatment for strep throat, her sleep pattern and behavior continued to worsen, so she was seen again in ER. At that time she was admitted for altered mental status for two days, while tests were performed. She had been referred to psychologist in October when she reported not feeling quite like herself, and has continued in counseling. At the hospital, she was referred to a neurologist for continued care as well. While I do not believe the vaccine was the cause of the events that transpired, her dad is extremely concerned that it could have contributed to her symptoms.

Received flu mist on a Thursday afternoon. By Thursday evening she said she felt "weird." Rested on Friday. Seemed fine on Saturday and Sunday. Tonsils were very swollen. She kept complaining that her eyes "hurt and felt hot." Took her to Urgent Care when symptoms did not get better. They assumed it was strep and started her on anti-biotics.  Received notification that strep cultures came back negative, as did mono testing.

She felt right afterwards and a few hours later has been having an allergic reaction since. Her face is puffed up with blotches (may be hives) her eyes are very swollen and her stomach has been hurting her since. She also developed a dry cough. I am unable to go back as the Health Department is closed on Sunday and on Monday due to Holiday.

Patient reported to his mother Saturday afternoon that his armpit of the arm where he got shot was sore. It wasn't extremely painful, so she was not concerned. Unfortunately it was not better by this afternoon, so she called to ask me if that was a normal side effect. I asked her to look at the injection site to see if there was a reaction and she could barely see pinkness around the injection site. Then I asked her to look at his armpit to see if it was swollen or red. After comparing both of his armpits, she could tell that the one closest to the injection site looked raised, perhaps a swollen lymph node. I recommended she give ibuprofen and do warm compresses. If the soreness and or swelling continues, please contact his regular doctor.

Day 1: Injection given in office at routine visit. Day 2: 12:30pm extreme lethargy (as referred to moving forward: limp, heavy eyes, little movement, however, can still move limbs and neck) and low grade fever of 100.3; extended nap, normal eating and drinking habits, extreme lethargy; 6:00pm fever of 102.3 - treated with Infant MOTRIN; normal night sleeping habits. Day 3: No fever upon waking up, however, still lethargic; 10:30am fever of 101; extended nap and increased discomfort/fussing; 2:00pm fever of 102.5, treated with Infant MOTRIN; called nurse at Pediatrician and discussed being seen next day if no improvement; very restless night. Day 4: Woke up with fever of 103 - treated with Infant MOTRIN and given bath; called Pedatrician and made appointment for 9:45am; seen by Pediatrician with outcome: all physical exams ok, told to treat with MOTRIN and/or TYLENOL as needed and make comfortable; continued extreme lethargy and fever throughout the day, treated with MOTRIN and TYLENOL. Very restless night - fever spiked to 105. Called night nurse through Pediatrician and walked through treatment, symptoms.  Made appointment for Saturday morning. Day 5: Woke up with continued fever - low grade at this point. Seen by NP at Pediatrician. Blood count via finger prick taken. White blood cell count normal, however, lymphocytes elevated. Told to make comfortable, continue treating with MOTRIN/TYLENOL, and sleep. Advised of wet diaper expectations, continue to push fluids, and return to doctor if no improvements by Tuesday or Wednesday. Extreme discomfort and hard stomach (almost as if bloated) later in day while inconsolable crying, called on call nurse back, advised to seek emergency medical treatment if more than one hour of inconsolable crying. Day 6: Fever free, extreme discomfort and bloating, suspended use of MOTRIN/TYLENOL due to potential constipation, rash presented beginning at hairline and eventually all over trunk. Day 7: Fever free, rash still present, woke up with mild congestion.

On Oct 29, 2018, pt began complaining of pain in her left leg. She continued to play and baby the leg slightly. We looked at it to see if there was a bump, bruise or mark, but we did not see anything. The next day, Oct 30th, 2018, pt woke up in pain, saying her knee/leg hurt. She had a lot of trouble putting weight on it and I noticed she was hot, so I took her temp and she had a low fever. I gave her Tylenol, and within 30 min she was walking normally and her fever had gone down. She went to school, because there were no signs of any congestion, cough, sore throat, or anything respiratory- besides the leg pain and very low fever (100.1-100.3). I picked her up from school that day and the teach told me she had been fine all day - playing and acting normal, until she woke up from her nap (2:15 end of the day). I walked in and she was on the floor, telling me she couldn't walk. I asked her where it hurt and she said her leg. So I picked her up and carried her out. When we got home her fever was higher than before - 101.5-101.8. I gave her Tylenol once again and about an hour later her pain was gone and so was the fever. She was walking around and playing like normal. She went to bed and woke the next morning (Oct 31st) and has some pain and low fever (100.1-100.4), but was walking. She went to play at the museum in town, had lunch and went down for a nap. When she woke up around 3pm she was in  a lot of pain. We decided to take her into Urgent Care because it was day 3 and did not seem to be getting any better. They sent us to the local hospital and we were seen right away. The began an IV and took blood. They saw elevated white blood cell counts and told us it was indicative of an infection somewhere in the body. They gave her Tylenol and transferred us to Hospital. We checked into the ER and were seen by several doctors - they too took blood and confirmed the high white blood cell count and elevated CRP levels in her blood - indicating infection. They decided to keep her overnight to watch her. The next day, Nov. 1st they began running blood tests for bacterial infection and an infectious disease doctor and Oncologist came in to assess pt and sort of get the history of what had been happening with her. The next day, Nov. 2nd, we began IV antibiotics. We continued on the antibiotics and are still currently on them via PICC line. Over the next days Nov 3-9, we did two MRI's, a CT scan, bone marrow biopsy, PICC line insertion and the only thing they could find was that the bone marrow appeared to be darkened on the MRI - in the same place on both MRI's. There was no abscess, or "highlighted" areas on the scans to indicate "infection", however they would treat this as Osteomyelitis, since the antibiotics did seem to space her fever out further, and make the pain go almost completely away as well. We left on 11/11/18 with the PICC line and order of IV of antibiotics to complete at home over the next 3 weeks. We go for our follow up visit today, 11/15/18 to read further blood test results, etc.

The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided. Concomitant medications were not reported. On 15-Nov-2018, the patient received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect Diphtheria-2/Tetanus/5 AC Pertussis Vaccine (lot C5519AA and expiration date 12-Sep-2020) via intramuscular route in unknown administration site. On the same day, the patient also received a 0.5 ml dose of suspect Influenza Quadrival A-B Vaccine (lot number not reported) via intramuscular route in unknown administration site. On 15-Nov-2018, the patient developed a non-serious tingling (paraesthesia) and numbness from his elbow down to fingers, the 5th, 4th and 3rd fingers were particularly affected (hypoaesthesia) within 20 minutes following the administration of Diphtheria-2/Tetanus/5 AC Pertussis Vaccine and Influenza Quadrival A-B Vaccine. Till 16-Nov-2018, the symptoms continued and he was evaluated by the physician. Physician reported that his strength was good and was able to squeeze hands equally. ROM fair. On an unknown date, the patient developed a non-serious pain, redness and swelling at the injection site (vaccination site inflammation) following the administration of Diphtheria-2/Tetanus/5 AC Pertussis Vaccine and following the administration of Influenza Quadrival A-B Vaccine. (Other relevant tests included No lab data.) Final diagnosis was pain, redness and swelling at the injection site, numbness from his elbow down to fingers, the 5th, 4th and 3rd fingers were particularly affected and tingling. It was not reported if the patient received a corrective treatment. Physician recommended ibuprofen and cool compress. The patient outcome is reported as Unknown for tingling, numbness from his elbow down to fingers, the 5th, 4th and 3rd fingers were particularly affected and pain, redness and swelling at the injection site. My daughter was at school and entered her class and that is all she remembers. She fell flat on her face and had snoring respirations and then had a seizure that lasted 2 minutes. She was taken by EMS to the hospital. Lab work was done and they did not want to do a CAT scan due to the radiation. She was referred to a neurologist and I made an appointment for Monday. She was not herself over the weekend. Was seen by Neurologist on Monday morning. They did a stat EEG. MRI was done on 11/14/18. She saw the Dr. again on the 15th. All tests were negative. She is still not herself and does not want to go out for fear she will have another seizure.
Simple febrile seizure, lasting about 1 minute. Patient otherwise well and returned to baseline.

Localized rash developed at right thigh injection site on 11/20/18. Rash grew in size over three day period but remained on leg only. As of 11/24/18, local rash primarily disappeared, however a diffusely raised and erythematous rash developed to bilateral buttocks, thighs, and calves. Benadryl was given, response currently unknown. Will be seeking follow up in medical clinic/ER if adverse reaction persists despite treatment.

Day of vaccine, runny nose worsened, congestion, poor sleep, by 3-4 days past vaccine, runny nose was a sinus infection; 4 days past vaccine, child developed a fever of 101. Fever lasted approximately 48 hours and peaked at 105 in spite of treatment with ibuprofen and acetaminophen at direction of care provider. During days 5-6 following vaccination, when fever was aggressive, child experienced staring and jerking (dozens of myoclonic-like jerks) while waking and sleeping. These were not febrile seizures; each jerk lasted <1-2 seconds. On day 6, child was seen by pediatrician who noticed no physical signs of infection, nor did infection or inflammation present in bloodwork. Fever and jerking subsided by day 7 after vaccination when rash started to appear. Rash covering trunk, neck, upper arms and legs lasted two days (day 7-9). Child remained extremely fatigued from day 5-day day 9.

Approximately 1-5 seconds after receiving the immunization, the patient rested her forehead down and proceeded to lose consciousness. The patient slid from the chair and knocked her head on the floor. Our facility's protocol was initiated and 911 called. Since the patient was underage authorities spoke with her father/guardian who waved and ambulance/fire being dispatched.  Patient was given water and remained seated with reporter and father for ~30 minutes. Father then took the patient home after waving any other services being called with the understanding he needed to take her to the emergency department if her condition worsened or any vomiting/headache occurs.

Soon after vaccines were given by MA, patient had syncopal event and MA came to get me. When I arrived he was altered, had eye deviation, head turn and upper extremity shaking consistent with a seizure. He then seemed to come to normal state of consciousness for a short time and then had another brief seizure. Patient remained in and out of normal consciousness for the next 20 minutes before EMS arrived. Transported to ER by medic, observed and returned to baseline and was sent home.

She stated she did not notice any brusing, just the knot. She took the child to Dr.'s office on 11/14/18 saw NP. Mom stated the hematoma was encapsulated. I also explained about the vaccine compensation program and gave her the phone number and website for more information.

My daughter was meeting a few of her milestones like rolling over, holding her head, swatting at toys and her eye track was great. The day of the vaccines I told her pediatrician she had a cold and to hold off on thee vaccines. She had goopy eyes and sniffles. The doctor said the vaccine would not affect her at all so we went ahead and got her the vaccines. Trusting my pediatrician knew what she was doing. My daughter at the time was 19 lbs she is now almost 4 and we struggle to keep her at 26lbs. The day of the vaccine she began shaking at night so I took her to the ER and was told she had a seizure. I have records of all this. She stopped moving her limbs, did not track and was basically in a vegetative state. She lost weight so I took her to many specialists after.

Patient presented to ER on 7/1/18 with increasing ecchymoses and petechiae. She was transferred to PICU for severe thrombocytopenia with platelet count of 1K. She received 2 doses of IVIG 1 g/kg and 1 dose of SOLU-MEDROL 4mg/kg, stabilizing and improving platelets to 65K on 7/4/18. She developed fever of 104.8 on day 2 of hospital stay, 5 hours after receiving 2nd dose of IVIG. She was given 1 dose of ROCEPHIN IV. Patient was diagnosed with neutropenia on 7/4/18 and was discharged after discussion with hematology. She followed up with PCP on 7/5/18.

Approximately 15-20 minutes after influenza vaccine, patient started crying and complaining of abdominal pain and headache. She vomited once. Pulse was found to be bradycardic at 52, so EPIPEN 0.15 mg was administered. She was also given BENADRYL PO 12.5 mg and 10 mg of DECADRON IV. She was given intravenous fluids with normal saline. Pulse improved to 108 after EPI. She was placed on 1 L O2 via nasal cannula for comfort only (no hypoxia). EMS was called and pt. was transported to ER for further evaluation/management.

Developed acute hives all over body on 11/23/18 with no other symptoms: started on ALLEGRA which helped with rash. Throat Cx positive for Group A strep: started on pen V K on 11/24/18.

On an unknown date, at 12 months of age, the patient received initial doses of measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (manufacturer unknown), hepatitis A virus vaccine live, influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) and pneumococcal 13v conj vaccine (crm197) for prophylaxis (dose, route and site of administration, lot# and expiration date were not provided for any of the vaccines). Fifteen minutes following administration he developed coughing, pruritus, and facial/lip angioedema. He was evaluated in an emergency department (ED) and received intramuscular epinephrine for presumed influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) anaphylaxis secondary to egg hypersensitivity. Three months later, he developed cough and facial/lip angioedema within five minutes of his 15-months immunization with varicella virus vaccine live (oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown), Hib conj vaccine (unspecified carrier) and diphtheria toxoid, pertussis acellular vaccine (unspecified), tetanus toxoid (dose, route and site of administration, lot# and expiration date were not provided for any of the vaccines). On an unknown date, at 17 months of age, the patient was referred for evaluation of anaphylaxis to vaccines. Skin testing was positive for gelatin (11mm), egg (9mm), measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (manufacturer unknown) (5mm) and varicella virus vaccine live (oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown) (9mm) and negative to influenza virus vaccine (unspecified) (3mm) with appropriate histamine and saline controls. Radioallergosorbent Testing (RAST) was positive to bovine gelatin (25.1kU/L) and negative to egg. The outcome of the event was not reported. The authors concluded that the patient was sensitized to gelatin, and reacted to gelatin-containing vaccines. They mentioned that measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (manufacturer unknown) and varicella virus vaccine live (oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown) vaccines contain over 10000 micrograms of gelatin per dose, and influenza vaccines include much smaller amounts. The authors considered the event of anaphylactic reaction to be related to vaccines which contained gelatin: measles, mumps, and rubella (wistar ra 27-3) virus vaccine, live (manufacturer unknown), varicella virus vaccine live (oka/Merck) (manufacturer unknown) and influenza virus vaccine (unspecified). Upon internal review, the event of anaphylactic reaction was considered to be medically significant.

Completed based on review of ER note from 29 November 2018: Patient's father reported on the morning of 28 November she started feeling weak and fatigued with some generalized malaise, anorexia, and subjective fevers. Per the father's report no significant headache, cough, difficulty breathing, chest pain, abdominal pain, leg swelling. Her father stated that at one point he gave her a bath because she was feeling ill then placed her into bed and went to get her something to drink. While he was in the other room he heard her vomiting, rushed back into the room, and found her lying unresponsive and pulseless. He started CPR and called for his wife to call 911. Patient was transported by ambulance to the ER; while in the ambulance she received a dose of epinephrine and chest compressions were continued. On arrival to the ER she was noted to be in PEA. She was emergently intubated and resuscitation efforts to include multiple rounds of epinephrine, continuous chest compressions, multiple doses of bicarbonate, atropine, epinephrine drip, calcium gluconate, and glucose were administered. Following discussion with family after approximately one hour and 15 minutes of chest compressions and resuscitation in the ED, not including the prehospital chest compression time, since patient had no signs of life with fixed and dilated pupils the decision was made to discontinue resuscitative efforts. Time of death listed at 0120.

Pt had a syncopal episode status post influenza vaccination. Vaccine administered while pt sat on exam table, she declined to be supine for the vaccine. After vaccine administration pt requested to lay down, she was then assisted to a supine position for about 10-15 minutes. Pt chatted with mother about an upcoming family vacation and used her phone while supine. Pt was discharged after she reported she felt fine and exited exam room. About 5-10 minutes later provider was called to assess pt after a syncopal episode at stores register. Upon assessment, pt was supine and was pale and clammy to touch.  Pt was alert and oriented X4, she denied pain and was crying. BP supine 118/60, HR 60, oxygen saturation on room air 98%, BP sitting up 102/70, HR 65, oxygen saturation 98% on room air. Mother reported they were checking out at register and pt fell forward. Customer who was a paramedic was also on site. Witnesses including mother reported pt did not hit head. Paramedics were called by store personnel and parent declined for paramedics to come and assess pt. Police officer came to the scene and took information from provider and mother. After assessment pt left store with mother in a private vehicle.

Within 2 days of receiving the shot, she began to have muscle contractions in her right bicep/tricep, causing severe tremors in that arm. They started intermittently and then progressed to constantly, even while she slept. A week later it moved to her right leg and now has progressed to her face. She has also had 2 episodes of her chest tightening, having difficulty breathing and being dizzy. Our pediatrician's office saw her 5 days after the shot when the contractions were only in her arm. They brought in 3 doctors, none of which knew what was happening, but all said, "its not the GARDASIL" They referred us to neurology that day. The neurologist performed an exam and ordered tests, all of which came back normal. She said she is not ready to rule out the GARDASIL but she 98% sure it is "conversion syndrome" That is a disorder caused by the brain's reaction to some stressor and according to the neurologist, often sexual abuse. Our daughter adamantly denies any form of sexual abuse, but we did start her in therapy to try and find a cause. She has seen the therapist 6 times and the therapist says there is absolutely no evidence of any trauma or stressor. This girl was a healthy, active 14 year old student. She has a great group of friends, makes straight A's and has good family support. She is a dancer and had to take a medical leave from the studio due to her issues.

This case was reported by a nurse via call center representative and described the occurrence of erythema of extremities in a 5-year-old female patient who received KINRIX for prophylaxis. On 28th November 2018, the patient received KINRIX. In November 2018, less than a week after receiving KINRIX, the patient experienced erythema of extremities and skin warm. On an unknown date, the outcome of the erythema of extremities and skin warm were unknown. It was unknown if the reporter considered the erythema of extremities and skin warm to be related to KINRIX. Additional details were reported as follows: The reporting nurse was grandmother of patient. She asked if it was a common reaction for a 5 year old to have redness and hot to touch from the top to half way down upper arm after KINRIX vaccine. The reporter had not seen this reaction before. The patient's mother called the office and was told this was a common reaction. The reporter had seen redness before but not hot to touch. When asked about consent for GSK to follow up with the patient's physician regarding event, the reporter stated she should really check with patient's mother first.

6 y/o male here to follow up after adverse reaction to flu shot. He got the flu shot here on 12/10/18. He has had flu shot before w/o issue. The next day mom noted his entire upper R arm was pink/hot to touch and swollen. No fevers, no hives/difficulty breathing, no joint aches/pains. He did seem tired. Mom took him to UC where she reports they did not remove the bandaid but just said it was an allergic reaction, but cave him Cephalexin 'just in case'. Mom didn't remove the bandaid until the next day then found that the skin looked like it was 'cut' and one side was blistered where the bandaid adhesive had been in contact with his skin. She says the actual injection site itself looked fine. He has never had an issue with bandaids before, so she thinks that perhaps the skin breakdown was due to the bandaid being on while the arm was swollen. It is looking better now. Exam R upper arm (delt) there is what appears to be an approximately 1 cm unroofed blister there the bandaid adhesive was anteriorly and a scabbed area where is was posteriorly. There is an additional small blister close to posterior axillary fold but mom thinks she caused this one. Injection site not hard or tender, not fluctuant, arm not red or swollen now.

Initial information received from a Nurse on 13-Dec-2018 and additional information received also from a Nurse on same date. This case involves a 3 years old female patient who received vaccine FLUZONE QUADRIVALENT. The patient's past medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided. No concomitant therapy received. On 25-Sep-2018, the patient received a 0.5 ml first dose and 0.25 ml second dose on 26-Nov-2018 of suspect INFLUENZA QUADRIVAL A-B VACCINE lot number UT625JA/UT625UA (expiry date: 30-Jun-2019) via intramuscular route in the right thigh. It was a case of actual medication error due to vaccine underdose and inappropriate schedule of vaccine administered. It was reported that patient actually got a full dose of 0.5 ml in September and then 2 months later got the 0.25 ml dose. As recommended, doses should be administered 2 weeks apart. It was unknown whether patient experienced any adverse event. Documents held by sender: none.

Mom called and LM stating pt had temp 103.5 when he left the office 12/17/18. Mom gave ibuprofen and about 2 hours later he had temp of 102-something. Patient was seen on 10/12/2018 for her month well child check. She was growing well and had a normal physical exam. Vaccines given a 0930. Developed 1 episode of vomiting later that evening but continued to nurse well. Felt febrile to mother about 16 hours after receiving vaccines, temperature was taken and was 104.7 and rising per mom. She was immediately brought to Hospital ED, ED reports initial temp of 38.6 C. She was alert with a social smile. Pulse ox 99% RA, Resp 26, pulse 147. Exam revealed no source of fever. Labs were done. Patient was D/C with a Dx of febrile syndrome. On 10/14/2018 mom felt she was lethargic. Temp taken was 96-97 F. She was bundled and warmed and T returned to normal that day. Patient was seen in our office on 10/15/18. Her exam then was normal and she appeared well. She was seen on 12/20/18 for her 6 month PE growth and development were age appropriated and normal.
Started vomiting on 11-12-18, took to ER on 11-13-18 had U/S then Ba Enema. Dx. with intussusception. Discharged on 11-16-18.

On unknown dates, the patients were vaccinated with improperly stored doses of LIQUID PEDVAXHIB lot number N034005 (expiration date 31-JAN-2020) and lot number reported as "N021920" (expiration date 07-FEB-2020) for prophylaxis (doses, routes and anatomical locations of administration were not reported). Additionally, the patients were vaccinated with ROTATEQ by oral route, lot number N005078 (expiration dates 22-NOV-2018 and 04-OCT-2018) for prophylaxis (doses were unknown), GARDASIL 9 lot number N020352 (expiration date 10-APR-2020) for prophylaxis (doses, routes and anatomical locations of administration were not provided) and M-M-R II for prophylaxis (dose numbers, routes and anatomical locations of administration were not provided; lot numbers N010496 [expiration date 31-MAR-2019], N014485 [expiration date 10-MAY-2019], and N023149 [expiration date 24-AUG-2019]). The vaccines were reconstituted with sterile diluent which was reported to be properly stored. The doses of all vaccines were exposed to a temperature excursion below 32 degrees Fahrenheit (F) (also reported as 31F) during a time frame of 15 days, which was detected by the Digital Data Logger. There was no prior temperature excursion and no adverse effects were reported. Follow-up information was received from the nurse on 17-DEC-2018. The reporter provided patients' demographics which made the case valid. This report refers to a 4-year-old patient of unknown gender. On 08-MAR-2018, the patient was vaccinated with an improperly stored dose of VARIVAX lot number N027002 (expiration date 28-SEP-2019). This is one of multiple reports received from the same reporter. Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1807USA011661.

The morning we took patient to Clinic, he was a happy, healthy toddler who spoke in 5-word sentences and was learning to read. He knew his alphabet, as well as all of his shapes and colors. He could count to 20 and he knew all of his animals and their sounds. Family members described him as 'brilliant'. After receiving his flu vaccine, patient became very tired, so he went to bed early that evening. The morning after receiving his flu vaccine, patient was extremely tired and weak, unable to stand or speak. We believed that the flu vaccine had given patient flu-like symptoms, which I have experienced myself, so we let patient rest. It was my understanding that the flu symptoms can last for up to two weeks. As the days and weeks went by, patient was still not speaking. He began walking very slowly with a pigeon-toed, shuffling gait, as if he was in pain. He also refused to eat or even hold a spoon. Family members were convinced that he was "going through a phase" and that it would pass. As time went by, it became clear that it was not just a phase. We had patient evaluated by a pediatric neurologist who performed an MRI and EEG. We have seen several specialists who performed genetic and nutritional assessments. We have also consulted speech and occupational therapists. Being eligible for Pre-K, the school district evaluated for special needs services. The therapist that evaluated patient wrote his condition as "catatonic." When patient finally said his first word several months after the flu vaccine, the cadence of his voice was noticeably different ? flat and toneless. It has now been nearly two years since the vaccine. Patient is still in intensive ABA therapy for 8 hours a day, four days a week, as well as two days a week of special education. Instead of playing with toys like he did prior to the flu shot, patient exhibits extreme stimming behaviors. These include constant hopping, clapping, drumming, hitting his chest, or running in circles. Every aspect of patient's life has been affected. Before the vaccine, he enjoyed a variety of foods and would feed himself with utensils. After the vaccine, he refuses to eat all but a few foods, and must be spoon-fed. At the age of 5, patient is still not potty trained, and wears diapers full time. Patient is unable to verbalize any of his needs or feelings. Patient went from being a healthy, neurotypical child, to exhibiting extreme, life-altering behaviors the morning after receiving his flu vaccine. We firmly believe this is a case of vaccine injury.

I filled the above to my best ability. The paperwork I have from the office does not give details as to which Heb B and a few others. Therefore the selection didn't match perfectly to the one she had. 11-28-18 vaccines given. The next day low fever (like normal for her after vaccines). Then the following day (11-29-18) seizure like activity started in the evening (similar to infantile spasm look). The next day (11-30-18) they were continuously increasing to the point of being extremely concerned. I (mother to patient) called hospital triage line and they said to take her to ER. We did and she had a few "episodes" in front of the resident doctor who talked to the neurology team and decided to admit her for an EEG and possibly MRI. EEG came clear so MRI was dismissed. However, a follow up with neurology and optometry was recommended. Patient's seizure like activity has almost completely disappeared. However, she does have some random shakes and jerks now. Continued check-ups are needed in the future, but healthcare professionals agree that the vaccines had to cause this or contribute due to timing and decrease of the episodes without medical assistance.

The patient's concurrent condition and concomitant therapy were unknown. On 11-JAN-2017 the patient was vaccinated with VARIVAX (dose, route, batch/lot number and expiration date were not provided), M-M-R II (dose, route, batch/lot number and expiration date were not provided) and FLUVIRIN (0.5ml; route, batch/lot number and expiration date were not provided), all for unknown indication. On 12-JAN-2017, the patient experienced shaking, could not move, constant sleeping, randomly collapsing, jolting, screaming in the middle of the night ever since (always wakes screaming), crying for first week and screaming in the middle of the night ever since (he had been walking in to walls). It was reported that the child was constantly crying and sleeping for the first week after vaccination with FLUVIRIN. Information has been received from a consumer concerning of his son, a current 12 year old male patient. The patient was allergic to morphine. The patient had no pertinent medical history nor concomitant medications. In August 2017, the patient was vaccinated with the first dose of GARDASIL 9, route reported as "shot" (strength, anatomical location, lot number and expiration date not reported) to prevent human papilloma virus (HPV) prophylaxis. On an unknown date in 2017 (reported as "soon afterwards"), the patient complained of leg hurting and starting to lose weight. On an unknown date, the patient suffered from constipation, diarrhea, chronic inflammation and his weight went from 81 pounds to 69 pounds. On an unknown date, the patient visited a gastrointestinal specialist who gave unspecified treatment. Multiple tests were done included blood work, magnetic resonance imaging, "MRE", ultrasounds, colonoscopy and endoscopy; no results reported. In March 2018, the patient received dose 2 of GARDASIL 9, route reported as "shot" (lot number and expiration date not reported). About three weeks after the second dose, the patient was hospitalized as his condition worsened. On an unknown date, as his condition continued to get worse and the patient saw a vaccination specialist who was considering an autoimmune disease. At the time of the report, the patient had not recovered from the aforementioned events. The causal relationship between aforementioned adverse events and GARDASIL 9 was not reported. Upon internal review, the autoimmune disorder was considered as a medically significant event.

Pts mom came in and showed me picture of childs arm. Arm looked red and enflamed in the area of shot. I explained to mom to keep it iced down and take tylenol. If it got worse or more painful to see dr.

My son developed a severe rash resembling measles within 3 days after receiving the vaccine that started on his face. By day 5, His body was completely covered from head to toe with what looked like the chicken pox or measles. He has had severe pain and itching with this rash. The rash and itching is still present. Four days after the rash started he was presenting with fevers over 103° F. We brought him to urgent care, they ruled out hand foot and mouth and gave him an antibiotic due to his rash looking like an infection was starting. They told us to follow up with our regular doctor.  We weren't able to see our normal doctor so we saw the next available one 2 days after urgent care visit. This doctor did no tests, and said it was scabies. We then went to a holistic nutritionist to get a second opinion and they said it was absolutely not scabies and did cold laser treatment on his body. They thought it was fully related to the vaccines. My son has been in daycare and around his siblings with no one getting any of the signs and symptoms he presented with. After that we got in to our regular doctor (at the beginning of October), at this point the rash was so severe my son was itching chunks of skin off his body. Up to this point, we tried, coconut oil, antibiotics, creams, lotions, anti-itch, BENADRYL. At this appointment he was prescribed another antibiotic. 3 days later his head was seeping pus, and we were sent to the hospital. He was tested for many things and given IV antibiotics and topical steroids but still did not have any answers to what it was and did not get better. After 5 days we were discharged home still with rash present. We continued with BACTRIM at home for 10 days. The hospital used ATARAX to help itching, this did not help relieve the symptoms. We followed up with his primary after that and he said there wasn't much he could do for him we just had to wait it out. On December 12th, 2018 we went to a holistic doctor. He said it was eczema most likely caused by vaccinations.

He received the vaccinations on 12/7. On 12/8 he had an erythematous area on his left thigh which was non tender. On 12/12 he developed fever to 103 and was seen in the office. He had pharyngitis and a cough. Rapid strep testing and viral PCR were negative. The fever to 103 persisted until 12/15. On 12/14 he went to the Emergency Department where he had a chest xray that was normal. On 12/15 the fever resolved and he developed a maculopapular rash on his face and trunk. The rash resolved on 12/17 and on 12/18 he was seen back in the office and he was back to his baseline.

This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of induration in a 37-year-old female patient who received DTaP vaccine for prophylaxis. On an unknown date, the patient received the 1st dose of DTaP vaccine. On an unknown date, unknown after receiving DTaP vaccine, the patient experienced induration, mass, skin warm and redness of legs. On an unknown date, the outcome of the induration, mass, skin warm and redness of legs were recovered/resolved. It was unknown if the reporter considered the induration, mass, skin warm and redness of legs to be related to DTaP vaccine. Additional details were provided as follows: The patient received 3 doses of the Tdap vaccine starting when she was 3 months old. The patient developed a hard knot in her left leg the size of a pea or a walnut. The area was also red and warm to touch and resolved after a week. The reporter reached out through the whooping cough website and was instructed to call the agency. The reason for reporter call was to advocate for vaccines not to report an adverse event (AE). The reporter had 3 kids and the advice of the physician, she did not vaccinate the other two because of the reactions her first child experienced but now she wishes she had vaccinated them as well because the other 2 kids had bad cases of whooping cough but the first child (the patient in this report) never had it. For tolerance to further doses, refer cases US2018GSK232635 (2rd dose) and US2018GSK232634 (3th dose).

Information has been received from a medical assistant regarding a 2 years-old patient of unknown gender. The VARIVAX was stored at a temperature range of -9 degrees Celsius (°C) to 8°C for the time frame of 70 hours and 45 minutes, and another range of 9°C to 25°C (17.7C) for the time frame of 34 hours and 30 minutes . This spontaneous case, initially received from a physician via pharmaceutical manufacturer (Merck) on 23-Oct-2018, concerns a 11-year-old, child, female patient. The patient's current condition included seasonal allergies. The patient's historical drug included NASONEX for seasonal allergies. It was unknown if the patient was taking NASONEX when the vaccines were administered. On 11-Oct-2018, the patient was administered influenza vaccine (batch number: U1982AC (as reported), anatomical location: left arm, dose, route of administration, expiry date, trade name and manufacturer: not reported). On the same day, the patient was also administered non-company suspect vaccines MENACTRA (anatomical location: right arm, batch number: U5986AA, dose, route of administration and expiry date: not reported), ADACEL (anatomical location: left arm, batch number: C5519BA, dose, route of administration and expiry date; not reported). The patient also received GARDASIL 9 (route of administration: intramuscular, anatomical location: right arm, batch number: R008163, dose and expiry date: not reported). On the same day, within minutes after receiving the four vaccines, the patient experienced a systemic bilateral rash on upper part of the body during an office visit. The rash was described as a red, blotchy shirt (as reported). The patient was given BENADRYL in the office and emergency services were called. The patient's blood pressure, oxygen level and temperature were monitored, and the vitals were reported as good. It was reported that, the patient was recovering, so the patient's parents declined the use of emergency services. The patient was taken home, after about an hour of vaccination. The field representative stated that, the emergency services had been contacted as a precaution, but the event was not life threatening. The reporter assessed the case as non-serious.
